<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Charged in Kids' Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A Tennessee couple is suspected of  
driving several miles into Arkansas to abandon their 18-month-old 
son in a ravine. Three days later, authorities believe, they tossed 
his brother in a lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Ware, 33, and Chantilly Harrell, 21, of Memphis, Tenn.,  
were charged Wednesday with murder in the death of Alexander Ware, 
whose skeletal remains were found Friday near the St. Francis 
River. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware and Ms. Harrell appeared in court without lawyers Wednesday  
and did not enter pleas. The couple were jailed on $250,000 bail 
and a hearing was set for Oct. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Fletcher Long Jr. also was weighing whether to charge  
the couple in the death of Alexander's 2 1/2-year-old brother, K-Von. 
Police said Ware told them he threw K-Von into a murky, stagnant 
part of Blackfish Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to comprehend a person's state of mind that they  
could dehumanize the children,'' Memphis police Lt. Sharon Cox 
said. ``All of us are very sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Memphis police, the boys' father told them that he  
and the boy's mother abandoned Alexander a few miles from Forrest 
City on June 16 and threw K-Von into a lake about 12 miles away 
three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Memphis police Lt. Brenda Maples said Ware confessed to the  
crimes, and sheriff's investigator Glenn Ramsey said the father 
showed investigators where he and Ms. Harrell left the children. 
</P>
<P>
	K-Von's remains have not been found, despite a five-day search  
through waist-deep mud and the draining of the lake. The boy 
probably drowned, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of his brother's death remains unknown. Alexander  
likely sat alone in the desolate ravine amid the farmland of 
eastern Arkansas, until heat and dehydration overcame him, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very cruel. The chances of anyone discovering the child  
would have been nil,'' Sheriff Dave Parkman said Wednesday. ``It 
was very hot, and animals could be a factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The children initially had been reported by their mother as  
kidnapped. The Commercial Appeal newspaper of Memphis reported 
Wednesday that Ms. Harrell told police she left Ware in June 
because of abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Harrell's mother, Venita Harrell of Memphis, said at court  
Wednesday that her daughter was innocent and blamed Ware for 
abandoning the children. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said there was no known motive.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's only conjecture at this point,'' Long said. ``They  
wanted rid of two children.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
