<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Danforth To Head Waco Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- former Republican Sen. John Danforth was named  
today to investigate the FBI's 1993 Branch Davidian standoff. 
Attorney General Janet Reno made the appointment amid calls for her 
resignation. Danforth spent most of the afternoon yesterday at the 
Justice Department meeting with various officials, including Reno, 
about the scope of the investigation and how much authority he 
would have, according to government officials familiar with the 
discussions. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools Finally Open in Detroit  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Teachers welcomed 180,000 students to their first  
day of classes today after testing the reform-minded school board 
and their own union leaders by staying off the job for more than a 
week. The teachers approved a temporary extension of their contract 
yesterday. The youngsters have a half-day of classes today, 
followed tomorrow by a full day. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. To Pull East Timor Staff  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- The United Nations prepared today to  
evacuate all but a skeleton staff from East Timor. U.N. officials 
said about 40 to 50 U.N. staff, including police and military 
liaison officers, will stay behind when another 150 U.N. 
international workers and 167 local staff members are to be 
evacuated tomorrow by the Australian air force. Meanwhile, the 
Roman Catholic Church said today that militiamen opposed to 
independence for East Timor have massacred nuns, priests and 
civilians. 

</P>
<P>
	China Religious Persecution Studied  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new State Department report says Chinese  
citizens can face harassment or prolonged detention in labor camps 
if they practice religion outside officially sponsored churches. 
The report also cites credible reports of incidents of abuse 
against Buddhist monks and nuns in China, including Tibet. China is 
one of 194 countries or territories examined in the report -- the 
first of what will be an annual series on religious freedom around 
the world. The study was made available yesterday to members of 
Congress and was being released to news organizations today. Brief 
excerpts from the report were made available yesterday to The 
Associated Press by a government official. 

</P>
<P>
	Egyptian Security Chiefs To Be Tried  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Three top Egyptian police officials in the  
northern city of Port Said will go before a disciplinary board on 
charges of dereliction of duty during a visit by President Hosni 
Mubarak, a police official says. Mubarak was attacked and slightly 
injured by a knife-wielding man during the visit. The three 
officers, including the Port Said Security Chief Lt. Gen. Hassan 
Gibril, have been transferred. Their new posts were not announced. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Prisoners Released in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	BEITUNIYA, West Bank (AP) -- Israel released 199 Palestinian  
prisoners today under the peace process that is back on track after 
nearly a year of deadlock. The inmates, raising cuffed hands in 
triumph and flashing victory signs, chanted ``God is great'' as 
buses carrying them to freedom were greeted by cheering relatives 
and bagpipe bands at army checkpoints in the West Bank and Gaza 
Strip. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Announcement Irks Fishermen  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's announcement last week of  
$5 million in emergency funds for New England fishermen gave some 
observers a sense of deja vu. That's because the aid had been 
announced last fall by congressional representatives who spent much 
of the year putting the aid package together. Now Gore's 
announcement of the aid -- which initially drew praise during his 
recent stop in Boston -- is attracting criticism from fishermen who 
mistakenly thought Gore was offering new aid. ``It really stinks of 
cheap, election-year politics,'' Paul Cohane, head of the Gulf of 
Maine Fisherman's Association, told The Boston Globe. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 13.62; Nasdaq Up 22.89  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the hour, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 13.62 at 11,049.96. Declining stocks on the NYSE 
outnumbered advancers 1,259-1,115. The Nasdaq Composite Index was 
up 22.89 at 2,831.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-German Sports Chief Indicted  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- The former head of East German sports and a  
one-time leading sports doctor were indicted today on charges that 
they set up a program to distribute synthetic hormones to young 
swimmers and track and field athletes. The indictment accused 
Manfred Ewald and Dr. Manfred Hoeppner with being accessories to 
causing bodily harm through the drugs in cases involving 142 female 
athletes. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
