<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns To Fight Emotions, Steelers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- ``Cleveland Rocks'' is more than the catchy  
rock 'n' roll anthem Drew Carey used as the theme song for his TV 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the truth, and Cleveland never rocks harder than when the  
Browns are playing at home. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday night, when Cleveland returns to the NFL for the first  
time since 1995, Browns fans will experience a range of emotions 
that have been building up for four years. 
</P>
<P>
	As their beloved Browns come running through the tunnel, 73,200  
screaming fans will christen the new Cleveland Browns Stadium with 
a sound that's bound to shake the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame a few 
hundred yards away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody will be hyped up,'' Browns cornerback Antonio  
Langham said. ``We'll be geeked to go. We'll be geeked to line 'em 
up and go toe to toe and fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Browns can fight the Pittsburgh Steelers, they'll  
have to fight their emotions. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland coach Chris Palmer has talked all week of the danger  
of his team being sky-high for the game. With so much attention 
being given to the Browns' rebirth in the NFL, Palmer doesn't want 
his players to get so caught up in the emotion of the night that 
they forget their assignments. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just have to try and stay focused,'' Palmer said.  
``Everything we have done this season has been a first time. 
Eventually, we'll get to where we have a regular week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion Browns haven't had that luxury this week. Not only  
is their first game against the rival Steelers, but it will be on 
prime time national TV as the final game of the NFL's opening 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Langham, one of three Browns who played in the last game in the  
old Cleveland Stadium, said Cleveland's first two exhibition games 
gave him a sense of how electric the opener will be. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be impossible to remain calm, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know early on I'll be hyped,'' he said. ``I'll be running  
around and jumping around. But at some point you have to calm down. 
If you don't that's when trouble starts. You have to calm down 
sooner of later. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to get that emotion out of you early and calm down.  
Because when you get too emotionally involved in the game, you make 
too many mistakes. You want the game to come to you. If you let it, 
good things start to happen, you make plays. When you start 
pressing, and trying to force things, you get out of position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Ty Detmer may be under more pressure than any of the  
new Browns to perform well in the home debut. That's always the 
case for starting QBs, but especially in Detmer's case since his 
backup is Tim Couch, the team's No. 1 draft pick in April and 
franchise player of the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Detmer said he goes through some mental checks to keep his  
emotions reined in. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to keep reminding yourself, `Hey, it's just what  
you've been doing all week in practice. Don't do anything special, 
drop back, throw the ball and make your reads,''' Detmer said. 
``There's always going to be adrenaline and that rush, and 
sometimes your mind gets ahead of your feet and your arm. But if 
you settle in and keep reminding yourself of those things, you can 
handle it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's easier for a veteran to control his emotions. For a rookie,  
like middle linebacker Wali Rainer, it's a different story. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's his first start in the NFL, so it will be hard,''  
defensive end Derrick Alexander said of Rainer, who is replacing 
Chris Spielman. ``The first couple of plays I wouldn't be surprised 
to see him pretty winded.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
