<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 16:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teammates, Friends Recall Hunter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Reaction to the death Thursday of Hall of Fame pitcher Catfish  
Hunter: 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Catfish Hunter was the cornerstone of the Yankees' success  
over the last quarter-century. We were not winning before Catfish 
arrived, and since his arrival in 1975 the Yankees have the best 
record in baseball, as well as four world championships. He 
exemplified class and dignity and he taught us how to win.'' -- New 
York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a fabulous human being. He was a man of honor. He was a  
man of loyalty.'' -- Reggie Jackson, who played with Hunter on 
championship teams in Oakland and New York. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team played very well on the field together, but there  
were problems. But Catfish got along with everybody. He was a team 
leader. Everybody liked Catfish. If you didn't like Catfish, you 
just didn't like people.'' -- Seattle manager Lou Piniella, a former 
Yankees teammate. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to call him this morning. The line was busy and I was  
going to call him after the game to see how he was doing. It's a 
shock. He was one of my best friends on the club and we stayed in 
touch all these years.'' -- Milwaukee Brewers special assistant Sal 
Bando, a former Athletics teammate. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``That was certainly the wakeup call about how underpaid players  
were. The spring training following this, in every clubhouse, there 
was curiosity and questions like, `Were you surprised at the 
amount?' and `What do you think it means if a lot of players became 
free?''' -- Marvin Miller, head of the players' union when Hunter 
signed a $3.75 million, five-year contract with the Yankees on Dec. 
31, 1974. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``The last time we saw him was in Florida during spring  
training. It was comforting to see his sense of humor was still 
there. That's what made him special. Catfish was upbeat about 
everything.'' -- Yankees coach and former teammate Chris Chambliss. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very sad day for baseball. He was a consummate pro. A  
great father, husband, a great man.'' -- Cincinnati pitching coach 
Don Gullett, a former Yankees teammate. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Catfish was a very unique guy. If you didn't know that he was  
making that kind of money, you'd never guess it because he was 
humble. And he was very reserved about being a star type player.'' 
-- Piniella. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``All of baseball is saddened by the death of Jim ``Catfish''  
Hunter. He was a great pitcher, a great athlete and a great 
competitor. The latter was particularly evident when I saw him in 
spring training while he was battling Lou Gehrig's disease.'' -- 
commissioner Bud Selig. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Catfish Hunter was a man among men. He was a genuine person.  
There was nothing phony about him. I learned a lot from him, both 
on and off the baseball field.'' -- former Oakland pitcher Vida 
Blue. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``The bigger the game, the better he pitched.'' -- Hunter's Hall  
of Fame plaque at Cooperstown, N.Y. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
