<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 05:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Herbert Stein Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Herbert Stein, an economist who served as  
chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers in the Nixon 
administration, has died. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Stein died Wednesday at Washington Hospital Center after several  
months of illness, said Christopher DeMuth, president of the 
American Enterprise Institute, where Stein was a senior fellow. No 
cause of death was given. 
</P>
<P>
	Stein was one of the key architects of Richard Nixon's economic  
policies, including efforts to fight inflation with wage and price 
controls. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Nixon administration as a member of the Council of  
Economic Advisers in 1969 and was appointed chairman of the council 
by Nixon in January 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	While Stein stepped down as CEA chairman in August 1974 to be  
succeeded by Alan Greenspan, he continued to be an active player in 
economic policy debates in Washington for the rest of his life, 
writing books, testifying before Congress and contributing opinion 
pieces to newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been a senior fellow of the American Enterprise  
Institute, a conservative think tank, since 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Stein often employed his wry sense of humor to help make dense  
economic issues understandable to the average reader. Among his 
books were ``The Illustrated Guide to the American Economy'' and 
``What I Think; Essays on Economics, Politics and Life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stein stressed pragmatism above rigid adherence to any one  
doctrine in economics. He once called himself ``a conservative's 
liberal and a liberal's conservative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the Nixon administration, Stein had served for 22  
years with the Committee for Economic Development, which had been 
organized during World War II to study economic issues. During the 
war, Stein had served as head of economic analysis at the War 
Production Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a daughter, Rachel Epstein, and a son, actor  
Ben Stein, who gained fame playing an economics teacher in the 
movie ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'' and is currently the host of the 
Comedy Central quiz show ``Win Ben Stein's Money.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 16:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
