<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Bills Players Unsure About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Andre Reed, Bruce Smith, Thurman  
Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	All three are a part of football's greatest stretch of  
postseason futility -- four straight Super Bowl losses in the early 
1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	They still resonate with the roar of the crowd, and are studies  
in perseverance. 
</P>
<P>
	Will all three be back next year? Don't count on it.  
</P>
<P>
	``When will I retire?'' said Thomas, starting his 12th season  
with the Buffalo Bills at age 33. ``I don't have a clue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas ranks ninth on the NFL's career rushing list with 11,786  
yards. Odds are he won't catch No. 1 Walter Payton with 16,726 
yards, but Thomas is within 1,000 yards of fourth-ranked Tony 
Dorsett and needs 334 to catch eighth-place Franco Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, who rushed for 381 yards in a reduced role last season,  
isn't entirely motivated by his pursuit of other great backs or a 
Super Bowl win. ``Football is still fun,'' said Thomas, whose 
touchdowns dwindle in number as they grow in importance. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas broke three NFL playoff records with a single touchdown  
in his 20th career postseason game, at Miami last season. His 
1-yard run in the second quarter set new marks for points with 126, 
touchdowns (21), and consecutive games scoring a touchdown (9). 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills opted for quality over quantity in their selective use  
of Thomas. Playing as the third-down back last year, Thomas 
averaged 4.1 yards per carry and caught 26 passes for 220 yards. He 
never broke 100 yards rushing in a game, but was always ready to 
go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've carried the ball almost 3,000 times,'' said Thomas, who  
has 2,813 career carries. ``I'm getting a limited amount of plays 
but I'm also fresh at the end of games in the fourth quarter, and I 
think that's where they need me the most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo also needs Thomas to show other players, even veterans,  
how excellence is achieved. ``Thurman has helped me a lot just by 
being the leader he is,'' fullback Sam Gash said. ``He doesn't say 
a whole lot but he runs every play as hard as he can, and he works 
out before and after practice. He doesn't have to do that; he's a 
Hall of Famer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Antowain Smith only 95 percent recovered from a groin  
muscle tear and third-rounder Shawn Bryson lost for the season with 
a knee injury, the Bills' running game needs help. 
</P>
<P>
	Some might say that neither Reed nor Bruce Smith would be missed  
now that receiver Eric Moulds is emerging as a superstar, and 
defensive end Marcellus Wiley has proved more than capable of 
stopping the run and pressuring the pass. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite an influx of young talent the players said they  
would be lost without the Super Bowl veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We young guys run around with our heads cut off at times,''  
Wiley said. ``We try hard but we still don't know in which 
direction to point all our energies. Bruce can't pass on his great 
ability but he does pass on what he knows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith smiles at the mention of retirement, then shakes his head.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you this,'' he said last month. ``If we win the  
Super Bowl, I'll retire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith has made two recent trips home to Norfolk, Va., to visit  
his ill father, George, plagued by emphysema and heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not doing well; the future doesn't look good for him,''  
Smith said. ``I'm going to go back every time I get a chance. I 
want to make sure I don't neglect my obligations here. I'm going to 
try to stay focused but it's going to be difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith still draws double teams at the age of 36, and played in  
his 11th Pro Bowl after boosting his career sack total to 164 with 
10 last year. But the 15-year veteran still has one guy to chase: 
Reggie White, the NFL's career sack leader with 192.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Among active players, Smith and Reed have been teammates since  
September 1985, longer than any pair in major pro sports. The next 
closest are John Stockton and Karl Malone of the Utah Jazz, 
teammates since October 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed's 889 receptions leave him just 51 catches shy of Art Monk  
as the second-leading receiver in NFL history. Jerry Rice is first 
with 1,139. 
</P>
<P>
	``People ask me how long I'm going to play,'' said Reed, who  
ended a short holdout when he signed for three years. ``I don't 
know. It's probably going to be more like one or two years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
