<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: Indonesia Must Keep Peace  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today insisted that  
Indonesia accept international peacekeepers if it can't quell 
violence in East Timor. ``If Indonesia does not end the violence, 
it must invite -- it MUST invite -- the international community to 
assist in restoring security,'' Clinton said. Speaking to reporters 
on the White House lawn, he said he is reluctant to embrace further 
economic assistance to Indonesia if it continues to resist East 
Timor's ``clear, unambiguous'' vote for independence. 

</P>
<P>
	Catfish Hunter Dies at 53  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hall of Fame pitcher Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, 53,  
died today after battling the muscle disease named after Lou 
Gehrig, a fellow baseball great. Hunter, who died at his home in 
Hertford, N.C., had fallen and hit his head on Aug. 8. He was sent 
home from the hospital on Saturday. In his career (1965-79), Hunter 
earned five World Series rings with the Oakland Athletics and the 
New York Yankees. The righty had five straight 20-victory seasons, 
pitched a perfect game and won a Cy Young Award. He went 224-166 
with a 3.26 ERA. 

</P>
<P>
	Danforth Opens Waco Inquiry  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., opened an  
independent inquiry today into whether the FBI started the deadly 
fire at the Waco siege and later tried to cover its actions. Vowing 
to pursue the ``dark questions,'' Danforth pledged a thorough 
inquiry that could include questioning of Attorney General Janet 
Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh. ``The only thing I would ask is 
that he conduct a thorough and prompt investigation,'' said 
President Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Wary on N. Korea, Iran Missiles  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Over the next 15 years, North Korea and Iran  
are likely to develop missiles potentially capable of killing 
millions of Americans, the CIA said today. In an intelligence 
report with major implications for the Pentagon's efforts to 
develop defenses against ballistic missiles, the CIA said Iraq 
posed an additional -- though somewhat more distant -- threat. The 
report is a summary of a classified National Intelligence Estimate, 
the first the CIA has done on ballistic missile threats since 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Leaders Won't OK Budget Summit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top congressional Republicans said today they  
will not engage President Clinton in budget summit talks this year 
because he would insist on higher spending in exchange for the 
GOP's cherished tax cuts. ``We're just not prepared to trade with 
the president with the American people's money, a spending buck for 
me, a tax reduction for you,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, 
R-Texas, said. Armey renewed the GOP's pledge to use Social 
Security surpluses solely to reduce the $5.6 trillion national 
debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Offers Gun-Buyback Cash  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today introduced a $15  
million federal plan to buy back guns. The new program will give 
local police departments up to $500,000 to buy guns in and around 
public housing projects for a ``suggested price'' of $50. The guns 
will be destroyed. Clinton said American children under 15 are nine 
times more likely to die by accidental shooting than children in 
the other 25 industrialized nations combined. 

</P>
<P>
	9-9-99 Goes Smoothly  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dreaded high-tech date 9-9-99 arrived today  
with no reports of any major Y2K-like computer trouble. There had 
been fears that Sept. 9, 1999, might cause some computers to 
misread the date as an old command to end a program. But those 
concerns appeared to be largely unfounded. 

</P>
<P>
	Hasbro Buying Pokemon Cards Seller  
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Pokemon trading cards, so popular that  
stores are finding it hard to keep them in stock, are joining G.I. 
Joe and Monopoly in the toy lineup of Hasbro Inc. The nation's 
second-largest toy maker said, in a $325 million deal, it is buying 
Wizards of the Coast, a games company that also owns the 
best-selling game Magic: The Gathering as well as Dungeons &AMP; 
Dragons. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 43.06  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher as a late rally lifted a  
market. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 43.06 today to end at 
11,079.40. Internet and technology firms were strongest. On the 
NYSE, gainers led losers 1,480-1,478. The Nasdaq rose 43.29 to 
2,852.03. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa Hits 59th, but Cubs Lose  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs hit his 59th homer  
today, increasing his major league lead and moving one away from 
becoming the first player to reach 60 twice. But Cincinnati's Greg 
Vaughn hit No. 36 to give the Reds a 5-3 victory. They remained 
three games behind Houston, which beat Philadelphia 3-1, in the NL 
Central. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  





  	   	
</P>
