<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> STDs on Rise for Gay Seattle Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Syphilis and gonorrhea have surged among gay men  
in the Seattle area, suggesting that many of them are letting their 
guard down against AIDS and engaging in risky sex, the government 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said cases of  
syphilis among gay men in King County, which includes Seattle, 
increased from zero in 1996 to 46 during the first half of 1999. 
Gonorrhea went from 180 cases per 100,000 gay men in 1997 to 430 in 
1998 and 420 in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the exact reason for the rise in the sexually  
transmitted diseases is unknown, the CDC said it appears to be due 
to an increase in unprotected sex with anonymous partners, 
especially in places like bathhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing in the Seattle population of men having sex with  
men large numbers of persons with large proportions of anonymous 
partners, and this has resulted in extensive transmission of 
syphilis,'' said Lyn Finelli, an epidemiologist with the CDC's 
National Center for HIV, STD and TB Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC and other health officials have warned recently about  
growing complacency about AIDS because of the powerful new drug 
cocktails that can subdue the virus. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend in Seattle is alarming because those infected with  
syphilis run a much higher risk of acquiring and transmitting the 
AIDS virus, the CDC said. In Seattle, more than 70 percent of the 
gay men infected with syphilis had the AIDS virus. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think if we're not able to reverse these kinds of behavior,  
increased HIV rates will follow,'' said Alonzo Plough, director of 
public health for Seattle and King County. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar syphilis outbreaks in gay men have been reported in San  
Francisco and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Syphilis causes rashes and lesions and, if left untreated, can  
lead to degeneration of bones, heart and nerve tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	After an epidemic in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the number  
of cases of syphilis in King County dropped off dramatically in the 
mid-1990s. The estimated rate of syphilis in the Seattle area is 
projected at 200 per 100,000 gay men for 1999, compared with 90 per 
100,000 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a call for action, a reinvigorated education effort for  
gay men,'' said George Bakan, senior editor of the Seattle Gay 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's an absolutely dangerous decline in the amount  
of educational programs'' promoting safe sex, he said. ``Maybe 
we've lost that momentum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``I think we always assume that young people just  
assimilate this information, and they don't. Many of these people 
come from homes where sex was just not talked about.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
