<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New HP CEO Lays Out Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- In one of her first appearances before  
customers, Hewlett-Packard Co. CEO Carleton Fiorina on Thursday 
acknowledged criticism that the computer maker was slow to respond 
to the Internet, but stressed that the company will aggressively 
roll out new online initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been said that Hewlett-Packard didn't jump on the  
electronic bandwagon fast enough,'' she told a conference of 
business executives. ``We did not articulate a single plan or 
vision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A prime focus going forward will be the world of Web services to  
be developed through the company's Internet business unit, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiorina came to Hewlett-Packard in July from Lucent Technologies  
and spoke at a session originally booked for company chairman Lewis 
Platt. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, the company spent most of its Internet-related time  
``bulletproofing customers,'' said Fiorina. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Hewlett-Packard has bought Open Skies, which sells  
airline tickets online, and stakes in Internet companies as 
vehicles to promote its hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can count on the fact that we will be a bit more  
aggressive this time around,'' said Fiorina, one of the nation's 
leading women executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The purpose of the E-services World conference sponsored by  
Hewlett-Packard and other high-tech companies was to build business 
with decision makers while briefing them on the future of doing 
business on the Internet. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
