<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers' Burkett Knows Pitching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- At times, John Burkett baffles the Texas  
Rangers as much as opposing hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	During the first two months of this season, Burkett looked like  
a batting practice pitcher. For the past month, he's resembled the 
pitcher who won 22 games in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Burkett won his third straight start Wednesday night, pitching 6  
2-3 shutout innings in the Rangers' 3-0 win over Cleveland. His hot 
streak also began against the Indians, baseball's highest-scoring 
team, when he gave up just one run in eight innings three weeks 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has pitched back-to-back games as well as you can against  
that ballclub,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``When he's in a 
groove like that, he can throw any pitch where he wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burkett (7-7) used different strategies in his two outings  
against Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 18, he got the Indians to chase high fastballs, leading  
to a season-high eight strikeouts. He tried it again Wednesday, but 
quickly shifted to Plan B. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to throw the ball up a couple of times, but I wasn't  
able to control it very well,'' he said. ``It seemed like I had 
really good control down, which is safer anyway, so I stuck with 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By keeping the ball low, moving it inside and out and changing  
speeds, Burkett retired the first two batters in each of the first 
six innings. Oates pulled him with two outs in the seventh and 
runners on second and third. He left to a standing ovation from a 
crowd that had jeered him at the start. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was warming up and they announced the battery, I  
happened to hear the boos. It was a nice feeling to be able to 
change that around,'' Burkett said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bitter fans remembered how lousy Burkett was in April and  
May, when he allowed 32 earned runs in 27 1-3 innings. He lost his 
spot in the rotation after allowing a club-record 12 runs in one 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	That dark side still lurks every time he takes the mound. For  
instance, he gave up eight runs in 2 2-3 innings of a 21-3 loss to 
New York in his only bad outing during the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just weird,'' said Burkett, who has a 2.33 ERA in three  
starts since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Another oddity is how well he's pitched in September and October  
since joining the Rangers in 1996. He's 8-3 with a 3.62 ERA in 
those months; during the rest of the season, he's 22-31 with a 5.48 
ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe in September I concentrate a little harder,'' Burkett  
said. ``I really don't know what it is. I try to be on my game all 
the time. I go out there with the same attitude all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Rangers one game ahead of second-place Anaheim, Oates  
gambled that Burkett would be at his September best last season by 
letting him start twice in the final 10 games. Burkett won them 
both, allowing just two runs in 16 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Texas has an 8 1/2-game lead over Oakland in the AL  
West, so the focus is on trying to catch Cleveland and New York for 
the best record in the league and home-field advantage in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Rangers and Indians meet in the postseason, there's a  
good chance a key pitcher for Texas will be a guy who started the 
year 0-3 with a 13.23 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing,'' Burkett said, ``is no matter what happens, I  
have a lot of confidence in myself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
