<DOCNO> APW19990909.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes Up 43.06 at 11,079.40 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher Thursday as a late rally  
lifted a market that had sputtered for much of the day amid worries 
about a sinking dollar and rising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 43.06 to close at  
11,079.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also ended higher. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 rose 3.51 to 1,347.66, and the Nasdaq composite index 
rose 43.28 to 2,852.02. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet and technology companies were the strongest performers  
in a relatively quiet, flat market. IBM rose 4 to 134 3/4, helping the 
Dow contain its losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo rose 9 1/4 to 162 11/16 after Lehman Brothers raised its  
rating on the stock to ``outperform'' from ``neutral.'' And online 
auctioneer eBay rose 9 11/16 to 144 7/16 after CIBC World Markets 
launched coverage with a ``strong buy'' recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	But for much of the session, the broader market languished due  
to the dollar's continuing decline against the Japanese yen. After 
the Japanese government released a stronger-than-expected report on 
the nation's economic growth, the dollar fell to a three-year low 
of 107.78 yen, down sharply from 111.08 yen Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong report and the rising value of the yen helped push  
Japan's Nikkei stock average 0.2 percent higher. Weakness in the 
dollar has been a persistent undercurrent in the U.S. stock market 
in recent weeks, as improving economies in Asia and Europe attract 
investors who previously sought out the relative safety of U.S. 
securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak dollar also makes imports more expensive, laying the  
ground for price inflation. That threat further unsettled 
investors, who already fear that the Federal Reserve will raise 
interest rates a third time this year in its effort to quell 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the Labor Department reported the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits fell 
unexpectedly last week to 286,000. Any level below 300,000 is 
considered a sign of an extremely tight labor market, potentially 
adding to the Fed's concerns that wage pressures are escalating. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will probably stay in a holding pattern until more data  
comes out,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, chief investment 
strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``Each bit of economic data is 
important as people try to figure out what the Fed is going to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next key figure, the Producer Price Index, was scheduled for  
release Friday morning, and analysts say any surprise in the data 
could shake stocks out of their narrow trading range. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today was a fairly neutral session as people wait for the  
PPI,'' said Dan Ascani, president and research director at Global 
Market Strategists Inc. in Gainesville, Ga. ``The fixation on the 
numbers has deterred a lot of people from making any big moves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Continued strength in energy stocks helped lift the market.  
Rising crude oil prices helped Dow component Chevron gain 3 1/8 to 97 
9/16, and BP Amoco rose 4 11/16 to 115 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks were mostly lower, due largely to the interest  
rate fears. Chase Manhattan fell 4 1/4 to 77 1/2 after a Friedman 
Billings Ramsey analyst said the bank may see revenue from capital 
markets slip. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products dropped 2 1/4 to 40 1/16 amid reports the  
company is facing a federal investigation involving the 
government's 1996 approval of the drug Redux. American Home 
Products has already seen its share price battered as the company 
faces thousands of civil lawsuits over its diet drugs, which have 
been linked to heart valve problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues were just even with decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Composite volume totaled 930.78 million shares, 
compared with 942.24 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.87 to 437.77.  
</P>
<P>
	In Europe, France's CAC-40 index rose 0.8 percent to a record  
close. Germany's DAX index rose 0.7 percent and Britain's FT-SE 100 
gained 0.1 percent. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
