<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Matthews Ready for 1st NFL Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Shane Matthews is used to people  
doubting him. 
</P>
<P>
	It happened when he was at Florida, where he led the Gators to a  
28-8 record and two SEC championships in three years as a starter. 
</P>
<P>
	It happened his first five years in the NFL, when he was cut  
four times by the Chicago Bears alone. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's happening now, even though the quarterback will start  
Sunday's season opener against the Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wonderful if you play well and you can say, `Hey, I've  
showed these people that I can play,''' Matthews said. ``But I'm 
not worried about those people that doubted me. I just want to go 
out and prove to my teammates and my coaches and myself that I can 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a great opportunity for me,'' he added. ``I'm  
looking forward to it. I'm thankful that (coach) Dick Jauron 
believes in me. He's given me this chance, and I'm going to try and 
take full advantage of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were plenty of snickers when the Bears cut Erik Kramer two  
days before training camp began. Rookie Cade McNown hadn't signed 
yet, and the Bears were going to rely on Matthews? Come on. 
</P>
<P>
	He set 50 Gators records and 19 SEC marks at Florida but hasn't  
duplicated that success in the NFL. He's been in the league five 
years but has played in just two games, never starting. 
</P>
<P>
	He's bounced between the third string, the practice squad and  
the waiver wire. He's spent part of almost every season at home, 
waiting for a team to call. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't going to quit or anything, but I never knew that my  
day would come,'' he said. ``But it goes to show that if you keep 
working hard, good things will happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews never doubted he could play. He did, after all, survive  
three years with Florida coach Steve Spurrier, not exactly a 
warm-and-fuzzy forgiving type. He threw for 9,287 yards and 74 
touchdowns in the Fun 'N' Gun system. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also the only quarterback Spurrier never benched, and the  
two still talk at least once a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all about opportunity. You can't show what you can do  
if you're never put on the field,'' Matthews said. ``There are a 
lot of guys in this league that have never been given a chance. And 
there are some guys that have been given thousands of chances and 
they go out and play terrible and continue to keep their jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews got his shot when McNown sat out the first 11 days of  
training camp. Though McNown is the team's future, he's not ready 
to take over the starting role just yet. 
</P>
<P>
	But Matthews wasn't exactly awe-inspiring, either. He was  
8-for-18 for 110 yards in his first preseason game, and 5-for-7 for 
85 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hadn't been a starter since college,'' he said. ``The first  
couple of preseason games, I went out there and played a little bit 
timid, scared to make mistakes. I've put that behind me the last 
two preseason games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He went 21-for-24 for 228 yards and two touchdowns without an  
interception in the last two preseason games. His final preseason 
rating was 107.8, seventh-best among quarterbacks who threw 40 
passes or more. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also a good fit for the Bears' new offense, which has  
multiple sets and requires the quarterback to call plays on the fly 
at the line of scrimmage. At Florida, Matthews estimates he called 
audibles on 82 percent of the plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``He plays with a good, fast tempo,'' Bears offensive  
coordinator Gary Crowton said. ``He's very accurate. He has a good 
release and he gets rid of the ball fast. The way his mind works is 
good for the coaches because he thinks like we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews knows he's got plenty of doubters, and he's OK with  
that. It isn't the first time, and it probably won't be the last. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there are a lot of people who have already written us  
off for the first game since I've never started a game, we have so 
many young players, we have a new coach and this and that,'' he 
said. ``But in this league, anybody can beat anybody. If we 
outprepare those guys and go out there and outexecute them, we'll 
win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
