<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deputy Waco Investigator Is Chosen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The lawyer selected by former Sen. John  
Danforth to assist in his probe of the Waco siege is a federal 
prosecutor who comes from a family prominent in law and public 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Danforth selected U.S. Attorney Edward L. Dowd Jr., a Democrat,  
as his deputy in the probe of the 1993 incident that left cult 
leader David Koresh and 80 followers dead in a fiery blaze. 
</P>
<P>
	Dowd, 51, who was named U.S. attorney in 1993, resigned to take  
the Danforth job. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was made a day after Danforth accepted U.S.  
Attorney General Janet Reno's invitation to head the investigation 
into whether the FBI started the deadly fire and tried to cover up 
its involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a person of persuasive character and knows what he wants  
to do, then he goes after it with a lot of zeal,'' said Dowd's 
brother William, also an attorney. ``Senator Danforth has known him 
for a long time and knew his record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dowd, 51, grew up in St. Louis and graduated with honors in 1977  
from St. Mary's Law School in San Antonio, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	His family is prominent in St. Louis law circles, and many  
members hold public office. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Edward L. Dowd Sr., was city circuit attorney in the  
1950s and was the 1972 Democratic nominee for governor. A brother, 
James R. Dowd, and a cousin, Robert G. Dowd Jr., serve on the 8th 
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis. They are both former 
St. Louis Circuit Court judges. Another cousin, David Dowd, is the 
city's chief workers' compensation judge. 
</P>
<P>
	There are five Dowds in the St. Louis firm of Dowd &AMP; Dowd, that  
was established in the 1950s by the father. 
</P>
<P>
	Dowd worked as an assistant federal prosecutor in St. Louis from  
1979 to 1984. He won about 30 trials and coordinated the U.S. 
attorney's drug task force. 
</P>
<P>
	Danforth, also from St. Louis, described Dowd as ``a person who  
is very highly regarded in our community, a very respected 
prosecutor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
