<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Ark. Kicker Little Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Former Arkansas kicker Steve Little was  
remembered Thursday as a courageous man who kept a positive 
attitude under trying circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Little, 43, had a record-setting career at Arkansas but his  
professional career came to a stark end when he was paralyzed from 
the neck down in a car accident in 1980 -- the day he was cut by the 
St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas athletic director Frank Broyles said people should  
learn from Little's poise. 
</P>
<P>
	Broyles, who recruited and coached Little, spoke to 250 during a  
memorial service Thursday. Little tied an NCAA record with a 
67-yard field goal against rival Texas in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Monday at his home in Little Rock. The cause of death  
has not been determined, but may have been from complications 
related to the 1980 wreck, according to his brother, Gene Little. 
</P>
<P>
	Former teammates signed two footballs in the lobby of the  
funeral home where Thursday's service was held. A portrait of 
Little making a kick stood in the room where the service was held. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67-yard field goal against Texas tied the record set by  
Texas' Russell Erxleben. The Texas kicker recalled Thursday that 
Little was lined up to kick a 66-yarder but, before the play, moved 
the tee back a yard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It bothered me when he did it because I thought he stuck it in  
my face. But I can't tell you how happy I am today he did it,'' 
Erxleben said. 
</P>
<P>
	Erxleben attended the service along with many former Razorbacks  
players, including linebacker Mike Massey, defensive end Jim Howard 
and offensive tackle Gerald Skinner. 
</P>
<P>
	Former defensive tackle Brison Manor, who played with Little at  
Arkansas and went on to play for the Denver Broncos, was among 
those sitting with Little's family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not his brother but that's the way we treated each other.  
It's part of being a Razorback,'' Manor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Little came to Arkansas in 1974 from Shawnee Mission South High  
School in Overland Park, Kan., where he was an all-state 
quarterback and defensive back. 
</P>
<P>
	Broyles remembers making eight consecutive Sunday trips to  
Little's home to recruit him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed a kicker bad and he was the best in the world,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Little played for the Razorbacks from 1974 to 1977, setting  
school records for points by a kicker (280) while making 53 of 89 
field goals, including seven of 13 from beyond 50 yards. He also 
made 121 of 131 extra points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Victor Nixon said he remembered watching Little play.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I was the only Razorback fan who asked, `How can  
he do that?''' Nixon said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1976, Little played for the Arkansas team that defeated  
Georgia 31-10 in the Cotton Bowl and in 1978 was a member of the 
team that beat Oklahoma 31-6 in the Orange Bowl. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
