<DOCNO> APW19990909.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 03:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The release of unexpectedly strong data on Japan's  
economy sent the dollar plummeting against the yen today and 
boosted Tokyo share prices slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 108.84 yen in late trading, down 2.38 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
111.08 yen overnight. It ranged between 108.73 yen and 111.16 
during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 36.18 points,  
or 0.21 percent, to close at 17,677.56. On Wednesday, the average 
closed down 66.12 points, or 0.37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency shocked economists when it  
announced that Japan's real gross domestic product grew 0.2 percent 
in the April-June quarter from the prior quarter, or an annual pace 
of expansion of 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists had forecast on average a 0.4 percent  
quarter-on-quarter contraction of the GDP, or the value of all 
goods and services produced in a country. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said market participants' attention was now fixed on  
whether or not the Bank of Japan would buy dollars to stem the 
yen's appreciation against the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 115.55 yen, down  
from 118.24 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices advanced moderately on the GDP  
figures, but the yen's strengthening against the dollar kept gains 
to a minimum, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market's reaction to GDP was short-term,'' said Paul  
Migliorato, senior salesman at Commerzbank, adding that investors 
quickly turned cautious as the yen advanced above the 110-yen level 
following release of the data. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen hurts Japan's exporters because it pushes up the  
prices of their goods overseas, making the companies less 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 473.99 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, down from 484.61 million 
shares Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 586 to 564, while 185 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 2.21 points to close at 11,036.34. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 5.05 points, or 0.34 percent, to 1,507.62. The 
TOPIX closed down 2.05 points, or 0.14 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8200 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8100 percent. Its 
price fell 0.09 points to 100.67. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
