<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Futures Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures finished mixed Thursday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors maneuvered ahead of the 
government's monthly harvest reports. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn prices declined as the market anticipated only a minor  
reduction by the U.S. Department of Agriculture in its forecast of 
the nation's largest crop. 
</P>
<P>
        Concerns that crops have matured too quickly are balanced by  
the recent run of good drying weather. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans initially rebounded from the previous day amid investor  
jockeying ahead of Friday's USDA reports on production and supply and 
demand, but fell late in the session, dragged down by corn and wheat. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures were pressured by concerns about the world supply  
level. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery fell 3/4 cent to $2.85 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 2 cents to $2.19 cents a bushel; December oats rose 
1/2 cent to $1.16 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 1 cent to $5. 
07 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and pork futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle fell .35 cent to 68.17 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle fell .30 cent to 78.97 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
fell 2 cents to 43.30 cents a pound; February pork bellies fell 1.20 
cents to 53.10 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
