<DOCNO> APW19990909.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 13:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Offers Gun Buyback Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking a page from local communities,  
President Clinton announced a $15 million federal plan Thursday to 
slow gun violence by having authorities buy firearms in and around 
public housing projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a group of mayors joined with members of Congress,  
police chiefs and clergy to urge the House of Representatives to 
enact tougher gun safety measures passed earlier this year by the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing on the steps of the Capitol, Denver Mayor Wellington  
Webb, president of the U.S. Conference of Mayors, compared the 20 
mayors gathered there to an infantry division in a battle to reduce 
gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need some air support from the House,'' Webb said.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the new federal program will give local police  
departments up to $500,000 each to buy guns in and around public 
housing projects for a ``suggested price'' of $50. The guns will be 
destroyed, the White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton twice recited this statistic to mayors and police chiefs  
at his White House meeting: American children under 15 are nine 
times more likely to die by accidental shooting than children in 
the other 25 industrialized nations combined. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every gun turned in through a buyback program means  
potentially one less tragedy,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The buyback plan is modeled on local programs in cities such as  
Washington, Sacramento, Denver and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration calculates that the $15 million program  
should bring in close to 300,000 guns. The money will go to 
individual public housing authorities, which will work out the 
buyback plans with local police, the White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration will suggest that housing authorities hand  
out gift certificates for goods or services rather than cash, the 
White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new plan drew criticism from Wayne LaPierre, vice president  
of the National Rifle Association, who said in a statement there is 
no evidence showing that the popular buyback programs reduce crime. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the thousands of weapons turned in through such  
programs over the past few years barely cut into the 220 million to 
250 million guns estimated by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and 
Firearms to be in circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayors at the Capitol endorsed the federal buyback plan,  
although one city leader, Paul Helmke of Fort Wayne, Ind., wondered 
about its effectiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Its good to get any weapon off the street but I'm not sure how  
valuable a tool it is,'' said Helmke, a Republican and past 
president of the mayor's group. ``I think we find that many of the 
folks who return guns wanted to get rid of them anyway. I'm not 
sure in a macro sense what good it ends up doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, a Democrat, was more enthusiastic.  
</P>
<P>
	``How do you eat an elephant? One bite at a time,'' Webb said.  
``In the same way, you have to get guns off the street a number at 
a time. It's just common sense that fewer guns on the street mean 
they can't be used to commit crimes or harm people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As with the Washington program, the national buyback offer would  
not include amnesty for any crimes committed with the guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the country, monetary rewards have lured many to give up  
their firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	In Connecticut, a 1994 statewide gun buyback attracted so many  
weapons the program quickly wound up owing $400,000 more than it 
had to give away. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget constraints prevented the Salt Lake City police  
department from offering money, so they had collected only a 
handful of guns during a recent 10-day program. A city buyback 
program several years ago drew about 1,000 guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb said his city's most recent buyback program offered tickets  
to professional sporting events in Denver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 13:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
