<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Child Dies in Alleged Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) -- A 2-year-old boy died and his 3-year-old  
sister was found seriously injured today in a car their father said 
was carjacked at gunpoint several hours earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Spicknall II called police at about 2:40 a.m. to report  
that an armed hitchhiker he had picked up on a bridge Wednesday 
night had thrown him into the river, and his car and children were 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	State Police Spokesman Maj. Greg Shipley said construction  
workers found the car at about 8 a.m., parked about a half mile 
from the bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Spicknall III, 2, and Destiny Array Spicknall, 3, were  
still in the back seat, Shipley said. Both were taken to Dorchester 
General Hospital, where Richard was pronounced dead. Shipley would 
not say how they were injured, saying only that they had suffered 
severe trauma to the upper torso. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipley said police still were searching for the alleged  
carjacker. He would not say whether the father, who is separated 
from the children's mother, was considered a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not ruling anything out,'' Shipley said.  
</P>
<P>
	Troopers continued to interview the man. Shipley said police  
were trying to account for Spicknall's time between when he said he 
was carjacked at about 11 p.m. Wednesday and when he called police 
from a pay phone at 2:40 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Spicknall told police he was taking his children to see their  
grandparents when he stopped for a hitchhiker on a bridge over the 
Choptank River, state police Sgt. Mitchel Parke said. 
</P>
<P>
	He told police the hitchhiker, an older white man with a  
mustache and a beard, showed him a black automatic handgun, the men 
struggled, and Spicknall was thrown into the river. He told police 
he ``floundered around'' before reaching a fishing pier and calling 
for help, Parke said Police found him at the phone, dripping wet. 
</P>
<P>
	Spicknall suffered a scrape on his forehead but didn't need  
medical attention, police said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
