<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 20:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Court Delays Louis. Execution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANGOLA, La. (AP) -- Less than 30 minutes before he was to be put  
to death, convicted murderer Feltus Taylor was granted a stay of 
execution by the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The stay, Taylor's sixth, was granted so the justices will have  
time to determine whether his constitutional rights were violated 
at his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 38, had prepared for his execution by visiting with  
family members and his spiritual advisor at the prison Thursday, 
Warden Burl Cain said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He broke down. He was very glad,'' Cain said.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers claimed in an appeal that Taylor was given  
anti-psychotic drugs during his trial on an irregular schedule 
without his attorneys' knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 38, admitting shooting Donna Ponsano to death in March  
1991 after he robbed the safe of the Cajuns Fabulous Chicken 
Restaurant in Baton Rouge. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Clark, the former manager at the restaurant, survived the  
attack after being shot four times in the head, but is now 
paralyzed on his left side. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just turned around and started shooting, Clark said. ``He  
said he wasn't going to leave any witnesses that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stay was announced shortly before Taylor's scheduled 6 p.m.  
execution at the Louisiana State Penitentiary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
