<DOCNO> APW19990909.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hit Man To Testify Against Cohorts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A reputed hit man who admits killing 20 people has  
agreed to plead guilty and to testify against organized crime 
leaders in return for a promise to get out of prison in as little 
as eight years, according to court documents unsealed today. 
</P>
<P>
	John Martorano, 58, will plead guilty to federal racketeering  
charges, which include the murder allegations, and testify against 
former Winter Hill gang cohorts James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger and 
Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, according to a document ordered 
unsealed by U.S. District Judge Mark Wolf. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger, Flemmi and Martorano are defendants in a 1995 federal  
racketeering case that has been challenged by defense lawyers who 
say it should be thrown out because the FBI gave Flemmi and Bulger 
free rein to commit crimes short of murder while they were 
government informants. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf is expected to rule within days in the case that also  
includes reputed New England mob boss Francis Salemme and Robert 
Deluca as defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano had been part of the hearings challenging the  
indictment, but dropped out to cooperate with authorities, sources 
told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	After 14 months of negotiations and hundreds of hours of  
interviews with the state police and the Drug Enforcement 
Administration, Martorano admitted taking part in 20 murders 
spanning three decades and three states, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most occurred in the Boston area as a result of mob feuds, but  
some involved bystanders, such as two passengers in the car of a 
targeted nightclub manager. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to racketeering, race-fixing, bookmaking and  
extortion, Martorano agreed to plead guilty to racketeering charges 
related to 12 gangland murders in which Flemmi and the fugitive 
Bulger are implicated, according to the documents signed by 
prosecutors and Martorano's lawyer, Francis DiMento. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have agreed to recommend that Martorano be sentenced  
to 12 1/2 to 15 years in prison, court papers said. Because of time 
served awaiting trial, Martorano could be free in eight to 10 1/2 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which Wolf must approve, was given the green light by  
prosecutors from Massachusetts, Florida and Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oklahoma killing happened in 1981, when Roger Wheeler, Telex  
Corp. chairman and owner of World Jai Alai, was slain as he 
finished a round of golf in Tulsa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
