<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor Orders French Bank Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French investigators have opened an inquiry into a  
Paris-based bank for its management of funds from Russia's Central 
Bank, including money loaned by the International Monetary Fund, 
judicial sources said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary investigation is aimed at determining whether  
Eurobank moved money from Russia's Central Bank to the Financial 
Management Co., or FIMACO, based on the British Channel Island of 
Jersey. Eurobank owns FIMACO, and Russia's central bank has a 70 
percent stake in Eurobank. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation, opened Friday, would be a first step toward a  
formal investigation, which could eventually lead to charges. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest episode in a many-tentacled inquiry into the  
Russian Central Bank's handling of its funds, and whether Russian 
finance officials were straight with Western lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	FIMACO and Eurobank play central roles in other investigations  
that do not concern France. The French investigation is limited to 
whether there was proper authorization for management of funds in 
France. 
</P>
<P>
	The French prosecutor opened the inquiry based on a complaint  
Aug. 3 by French stock market regulators that FIMACO and Eurobank 
were managing assets in France without the required authorization. 
</P>
<P>
	At the request of the IMF, the firm PricewaterhouseCoopers  
investigated the relationship between the Central Bank and FIMACO 
and found that the bank secretly sent billions of dollars of its 
foreign reserves to FIMACO in the mid-1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF was never informed by Russian officials of the transfer  
of funds -- presumably including IMF money -- out of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The French inquiry is limited to whether French banking  
legislation was respected, the judicial sources said, speaking on 
customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF's deputy managing director, Stanley Fischer, said  
recently that Russia lied about the overall state of its finances 
in 1996, and that if the IMF had known the truth, it would have 
suspended Russia's loan program. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the IMF also says it has not found evidence of  
impropriety in Russia's handling of the roughly $20 billion in IMF 
loans it has received this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the IMF's biggest debtor.  
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, investigators are trying to determine  
whether the Russian mob illegally channeled $10 billion through the 
Bank of New York. Some U.S. newspaper reports have suggested the 
laundered money may have included IMF loans. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
