<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OKs 2 Judicial Nominations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate confirmed three judicial  
nominations, filling federal court vacancies in Florida, Kansas and 
Washington state. 
</P>
<P>
	By identical votes of 93-1, lawmakers on Wednesday approved:  
</P>
<P>
	--Adalberto Jose Jordan to be a U.S. district judge for the  
Southern District of Florida. A native of Cuba who fled to the 
United States at a young age, Jordan has been an assistant U.S. 
attorney in Miami since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	--Marsha J. Pechman to be a U.S. district judge for the Western  
District of Washington state. She has been a judge for 11 years in 
King County, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the Senate by unanimous consent approved the nomination  
of Carlos Murguia of Kansas City, Kan., to be a U.S. district judge 
in Kansas. Murguia for 10 years has been a judge in Wyandotte 
County, Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, an independent, voted against  
Jordan and Pechman. 
</P>
<P>
	The votes brought the number of President Clinton's judicial  
nominees approved this year to 14, a total criticized as inadequate 
by Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the senior Democrat on the Senate 
Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	At this time last year, the Senate had confirmed 39 judges; and  
in 1994, 58 judicial nominees had been approved by this point, 
Leahy said. 
</P>
<P>
	There are more than 60 vacancies on the federal judiciary,  
according to Senate aides and the Senate Judiciary Committee's Web 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's votes left a total of 46 nominations pending either  
in the judiciary committee, which clears judicial nominees, or 
before the full Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the nominations pending is that of U.S. District Judge  
Richard Paez of Los Angeles for a seat on the 9th U.S. Circuit 
Court of Appeals, who was first nominated in January 1996, Leahy 
said. That nomination and a subsequent nomination expired with no 
Senate action, and he was renominated again at the beginning of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not doing our job. We are not being responsible,''  
Leahy said in a floor speech. ``We are really being dishonest and 
condescending and arrogant toward the judiciary ... and it deserves 
better.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
