<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Mercedes Ads Using Humor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A new ad campaign from Mercedes-Benz takes a  
sharp turn from previous marketing efforts, relying more on humor 
than horsepower to sell the German automaker's luxury cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The first ad for Mercedes' largest marketing push ever shows  
images of Kojak with hair and the Mona Lisa with a toothy grin, 
asserting that it's silly to change something that already works. 
There's only a brief, distant glimpse of cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercials are part of a campaign aimed at evoking warm  
feelings about the Mercedes name. It's the first automotive 
advertising from Omnicom Group's Merkley Newman Harty agency, which 
was hired by Mercedes earlier this year after the company fired its 
agency of more than five years, Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to communicate that you can have a complete and total  
experience with Mercedes-Benz that you cannot have anywhere else,'' 
said Mike Jackson, president and chief executive of Mercedes-Benz 
USA. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 ads that will air over the next several months are filled  
with outlandish images, such as five men straining inside a giant 
slingshot, and focus far less on the cars than Mercedes' previous 
ads. 
</P>
<P>
	One features people in business attire, including a leggy woman  
in a microskirt, being subjected to a wind tunnel, a slalom course 
and other auto engineering tests. Another, titled ``Chorus,'' shows 
serene groups of Mercedes employees in odd settings promising good 
customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all are humorous. One ad features a succession of people  
superimposed into scenes of crash tests to highlight safety 
features. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ads also continue a trend of Mercedes spots to rely on  
images of deceased celebrities. The ads use Babe Ruth and Clark 
Gable, whose famous closing line from ``Gone With The Wind'' is 
recast with some computer help as ``Frankly my dear, I don't give a 
hoot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign also includes print and Internet advertising.  
Jackson said the ads were part of a plan to make Mercedes seem less 
aloof. 
</P>
<P>
	Using humor is ``a very engaging way to communicate,'' he said.  
``It makes the brand Mercedes much more approachable than some 
cold, calculating approach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign's price tag was put at $50 million to $60 million  
by Joe Eberhardt, vice president of marketing for Mercedes-Benz 
USA. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ads come as Mercedes, a unit of DaimlerChrysler AG,  
takes part in an industrywide sales boom. Mercedes' U.S. sales are 
up 9 percent this year through August, with 120,966 vehicles sold. 
Among luxury nameplates, Mercedes is second in sales behind Lexus 
and leads BMW, Lincoln and Cadillac. 
</P>
<P>
	One advertising expert said it was rare for an automaker to try  
being funny to sell cars that are priced at up to $129,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``You really have to be very careful, because if there's ever a  
strategy that can backfire, it's humor,'' said Bruce G. Vanden 
Bergh, an advertising professor at Michigan State University. The 
ads must ``walk the fine line where they're funny and relevant and 
present Mercedes in a new light.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers who have broken with the auto industry's  
traditionally conservative marketing have seen mixed results. 
Unique campaigns for Volkswagen and Saturn have been credited with 
improving sales. But a $200 million campaign by Nissan in 1996-97 
with a smiling Japanese man called ``Mr. K'' was junked after the 
automaker's sales slumped. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said he was not concerned that customers might find the  
ads too strange, saying previous efforts by Mercedes went over 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be a certain small percent that will take strong  
issue with the communications, and we accept that as the price tag 
of being edgy,'' he said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
