<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Highlights of Thursday's play in the $14.5  
million U.S. Open tennis championships: 
</P>
<P>
	 *Weather:* Hazy and humid with late afternoon rain and a high of  
83. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Attendance:* Day session: 18,265. Night session: 20,382. Total:  
38,647. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Results:* Men's singles, quarterfinals: Cedric Pioline, the  
runnerup to Pete Sampras in 1993, came back from a set down to 
eliminate No. 5 Gustavo Kuerten. Pioline won three straight 
tiebreaks, including 16-14 in the third set, to overtake Kuerten. 
In the other quarterfinal, No. 7 Todd Martin beat Slava Dosedel in 
four sets, reaching the U.S. Open semifinals for the second time 
and the first since 1994. Martin and Pioline will meet in a 
semifinal on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Schedule:* Friday: Women's semifinals featuring No. 1 Martina  
Hingis vs. No. 3 Venus Williams in a rematch of the 1997 
championship and 1998 champion Lindsay Davenport vs. Serena 
Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Stat of the Day:* For the first time since 1980, three  
teen-agers advanced to the women's semifinals. This year, it's 
Martina Hingis, Venus Williams and Serena Williams. In 1980, it was 
Tracy Austin, Andrea Jaeger and Hana Mandlikova. By reaching the 
semifinals, the Williams sisters and Lindsay Davenport are the 
first American trio in the semis since 1983 when Martina 
Navratilova, Chris Evert Lloyd and Pam Shriver advanced that far. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Quote of the Day:* ``I'm just a little bit frustrated because I  
really played well. I deserved to win maybe. I had the same chance 
as him. That's a little bit frustrating. It's like this. If we 
don't have these moments, we can not celebrate wins, too.'' -- 
Gustavo Kuerten. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
