<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Strange Day in Louisiana Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- There were unintelligible screams from  
one candidate. Another signed up for the fall election using a 
racial epithet as a nickname. Still another filed for a run unaware 
he was too young. 
</P>
<P>
	Even by Louisiana's colorful political standards, the final day  
to sign up for the state's Oct. 23 statewide elections was bizarre. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the serious contenders, including Gov. Mike Foster and  
three major challengers for his seat, had signed up for the race on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the candidates who signed up Thursday to challenge  
Foster were well known. But two caused a stir. 
</P>
<P>
	Darryl Ward, a Democrat who has run near the back of the pack in  
several statewide and congressional elections, signed up as Messiah 
Darryl Paul Ward. 
</P>
<P>
	While signing papers he uttered loud, unintelligible shouts and  
screams, as though he were speaking in tongues. A witness said he 
hurried out of the office telling one group of reporters and 
onlookers, ``God loves you all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later came Albert Jones, a black man who signed up for the  
ballot as Albert ``Super Nigger'' Jones. Asked why he wanted to use 
the racial epithet on the ballot, Jones said it would help draw 
attention to the problem of people not voting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call people who don't vote either niggers or communists,''  
Jones said in a sometimes rambling explanation. ``It doesn't have 
anything to do with color.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wade Martin, head of the elections division for the secretary of  
state's office, said he could find nothing in the law that would 
prohibit Jones from using the nickname. 
</P>
<P>
	Within an hour of the qualifying deadline, a 23-year-old  
political newcomer, Scott Wilfong, a Republican political 
consultant, signed papers to run against incumbent Secretary of 
State Fox McKeithen. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the 5 p.m. deadline rolled around, McKeithen  
jubilantly noted that the constitutionally set minimum age for the 
office is 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilfong had left his office and was not available for comment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
