<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Baptists To Pick New Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- In an election that could set a new course  
for the nation's largest black denomination, the National Baptist 
Convention U.S.A. Inc. voted for a new leader Thursday to succeed 
its imprisoned former president. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven candidates vied for the presidency, many of them saying  
the broad powers of the office contributed to the Rev. Henry Lyons' 
downfall on charges of bilking companies of more than $4 million so 
that he could live in luxury. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one man should have all the power,'' Fannie Williams of New  
Orleans, one of the thousands of delegates at the church's annual 
meeting, said as she waited to vote for the Rev. W. Franklyn 
Richardson. The Mount Vernon, N.Y., minister advocates term limits 
for the president and having an elected, rather than appointed, 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons, 57, resigned after he was convicted in February of  
swindling $4 million from businesses and keeping nearly $250,000 
contributed by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai Brith to rebuild 
burned black churches in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of the scandal, many candidates said the president's  
powers, including control over the group's checkbook, should be 
reduced. Several board members are appointed by the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons, who was paid $100,000 as president, is serving 5 1/2 years  
in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention, which traces its roots to 1880, claims 8.5  
million members, though at Lyons' trial prosecutors said the figure 
was inflated to attract businesses. They said membership is around 
1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Some voters expressed admiration for Lyons' work and an  
understanding of human frailty. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a man, and he was caught up like any of us,'' said  
Bernice Hayes, of Dayton, Ohio. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
