<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Still Opposes Clemency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the political bruising she's  
received from Republicans and even some fellow Democrats, Hillary 
Rodham Clinton insists she was never in the loop on her husband's 
decision to offer clemency to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a decision that had to go through channels, a  
decision that had to be made by the highest levels of 
recommendations to the president and ultimately by the president,'' 
she said Wednesday. ``It is not surprising to me that I was not 
lobbied, or informed or asked about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a ``listening tour'' stop at a Long Island high school,  
Mrs. Clinton said, ``Of course, since we are moving forward I would 
hope that it proceeds smoothly and that the prisoners, when they're 
released, abide by the terms of the clemency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both the president and Mrs. Clinton have drawn sharp criticism  
after he said last month that he would commute the sentences of 16 
Puerto Rican nationalists if they renounced the use of violence and 
adhered to other restrictions on their travel and association. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of them were members of pro-independence guerrilla group  
FALN, which carried out more than 130 bombings in the United States 
in the 1970s and 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, 12 accepted the deal, and they could be free by the  
end of the week. One prisoner rejected the offer, and three 
nationalists -- including two not in jail but who still have 
outstanding fines -- have until Friday to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican critics of the president wondered aloud whether the  
offer was made to ingratiate Mrs. Clinton with New York's more than 
1 million Puerto Rican residents, who could prove vital for her 
presumed run for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated in 2000 by 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton removed any perceived advantage, however, last  
weekend when she said she opposed the president's clemency offer 
because the prisoners failed to respond to the offer quickly 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been three weeks and their silence speaks volumes. I  
believe the offer of clemency should be withdrawn,'' she had said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her surprise announcement infuriated several Puerto Rican  
political leaders, among them Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., who said 
he could no longer support her. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton tried to patch up the rift during a visit Wednesday  
to Bay Shore High School on Long Island, where she was greeted 
warmly by the school's 1,400 students. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stand by that statement, yet I understand the depth of  
feeling in the Puerto Rican community and I look forward to working 
with them on other issues that we can make a difference on,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton did not reply directly to a reporter's question  
about whether a mixup in White House signals had allowed her to 
formally condemn the deal on Saturday, even as the prisoners 
themselves were apparently considering whether to accept it. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she had not been advised in advance they would do so,  
and Howard Wolfson, her press secretary, said there was no 
indication that even the White House knew on Saturday that an 
agreement was close. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfson said Mrs. Clinton also did not know the White House had  
sent a letter Friday to the FALN convicts' lawyers setting a 
seven-day deadline. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
