<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Down on Dollar's Weakness / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bond prices fell Thursday amid a sharp  
decline in the U.S. dollar against the Japanese yen, and more 
pressure from corporate bond sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 9/32  
point, or $2.81 1/4 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.09 percent from 
Wednesday's 6.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for bonds fell as the dollar dropped to its lowest levels  
against the yen since August 1996. The dollar fell as new signs 
showed continued economic recovery in Japan. Bonds prices move 
inversely to the price of the dollar because U.S. government backed 
securities are less attractive to investors when the dollar is down 
against foreign currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasurys also remained under pressure from new corporate bond  
offerings, including one from Freddie Mac and another from Proctor 
&AMP; Gamble. Government bonds are hurt by corporate bond sales because 
they tend to pay higher yields, and thus make Treasurys less 
appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities were down 1/16 point,  
and intermediate maturities were down 5/32 point to 7/32 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.81 percent as the  
discount was unchanged from Wednesday's 4.68 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.13 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage 
point to 4.93 percent. One-year yields were 5.26 percent as the 
discount rose by 0.02 percentage point to 5.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.25 percent from 5.12 1/2 percent late Wednesday 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 13/32 to 113 11/16. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.82 percent from 5.80 percent. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
