<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 97-Year-Old Killed by Road Grader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERMILLION, Minn. (AP) -- A 97-year-old man on his way to morning  
Mass stepped into the path of a road grader and was crushed to 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle was operated by a county employee who was blinded by  
the sun Wednesday and didn't see Peter Marschall until it was too 
late, the Minnesota State Patrol said. No charges were filed 
against the driver. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle was carrying 5 to 7 tons of gravel.  
</P>
<P>
	A parishioner rushed into St. John the Baptist Catholic Church  
with news of the accident. The Rev. Joe Arackal, who had been 
waiting for Marschall to arrive before starting the service, 
administered last rites. 
</P>
<P>
	The bells at the church tolled 97 times for the oldest resident  
of this community of about 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Marschall's body was a listening device that he used to  
plug into the sound system to hear Mass at the church where he was 
baptized in 1902. 
</P>
<P>
	Marschall was a beloved figure in the town about 25 miles  
southeast of Minneapolis. He could be seen walking a mile or two 
every day, wearing his green farmer's cap and waving. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all thought he would make a hundred years,'' said Paul  
Kasel, owner of the grocery. ``His mind was good. He was so spry 
and active.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Pilcher, who was driving the grader, had known Marschall  
all his life. He had no comment Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
