<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Pushes Tax Cut Despite Veto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans intend to spend the  
next several days touting their veto-threatened tax cut as they 
head into a season of struggle with Democrats and the White House 
over issues extending to spending, health, gun control and campaign 
finance as well as taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax bill publicity campaign appeared aimed at blaming  
President Clinton for failure, as many top Republicans doubt 
compromise is possible. House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, 
told reporters today that the promised veto ``would pretty well 
kill it for this year,'' partly because legislative time is short. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey would not completely close the door on an agreement,  
saying Republicans were willing to listen if Clinton wants to 
negotiate seriously on tax cuts. But he said the GOP does not want 
a grand spending and tax deal using projected surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not prepared to trade with the president with the  
American people's money -- a spending buck for me, a tax reduction 
for you,'' Armey said. 
</P>
<P>
	In hopes of shaping the political environment to their liking,  
Republicans plan a public relations campaign culminating in a 
ceremony next week at which congressional leaders will formally 
send the measure to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people have made an overpayment, over the next 10  
year period, in terms of taxes,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent 
Lott, R-Miss., told reporters Wednesday as lawmakers returned to 
the Capitol from a monthlong vacation. ``They've got change coming 
to them. We think they should have an opportunity to keep that 
change that they are entitled to by this overpayment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton insists the 10-year, $792 billion measure would  
jeopardize the nation's economy, however, and has not wavered in 
his stated intention of a veto. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle said Wednesday  
that politically, the GOP tax cut had turned out to be a ``bomb.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans appeared increasingly likely to set the tax issue  
aside until next year's election campaign rather than attempt to 
work out a compromise that also would cover issues as diverse as 
spending and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can wait 14 months, get a new president and then do a tax  
cut,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the Republican whip, 
outlining the case against compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has yet to decide what  
course to follow, according to a spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	More broadly, Lott and Daschle both sounded pessimistic on the  
prospects for compromise this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any indication the president wants to work with  
us,'' Lott told reporters after smilingly predicting an 
``action-packed'' September and October. ``What the president wants 
is more spending, more spending, more spending for everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said he had talked with Lott and he expressed the hope  
they could work together. But, he quickly added, ``Clearly we 
(Democrats) will fight and we will aggressively pursue'' an agenda 
that include gun control, education, legislation relating to HMOs, 
an increase in the minimum wage and money for hard-hit farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no doubt that compromise eventually would emerge on  
spending measures because Congress must provide money for federal 
agencies and programs for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. Only 
one of the 13 required bills has passed, and most lawmakers 
privately concede they will have to break the spending constraints 
imposed by the 1997 balanced budget agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, the prospect was for confrontation this fall, with  
an uncertain outcome: 
</P>
<P>
	--Bipartisan health care legislation is pending in the House, and  
debate is expected by the end of the month. The GOP leadership 
opposes its provision granting patients the right to sue their 
insurance companies, however, and the Senate has passed its own 
version of the measure that Clinton has condemned as too weak. 
</P>
<P>
	--Several months after the shootings at Columbine High School in  
Colorado, gun control issues were being thrashed out in compromise 
talks between the House and Senate. The Senate approved provisions 
to expand background checks for sales at gun shows, to ban certain 
high capacity ammunition clips and to require the sale of safety 
decides with handguns. The House killed all three provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Senate Democrats are eager to try and attach a minimum wage  
increase to legislation that Republicans have crafted to overhaul 
the nation's bankruptcy laws. One Republican aide, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity, said it was possible a GOP senator might 
try to pre-empt the Democrats and bring up the issue first. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Republicans favor ``lockbox'' legislation to safeguard Social  
Security receipts. Senate Democrats have objections to the measure 
as drafted, and Lott indicated he would bring the issue up on the 
Senate floor in the next several days. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The House is scheduled to debate campaign finance legislation  
next week that would ban the use of so-called soft money, which are 
unlimited campaign donations sought by both political parties. The 
measure is likely to pass, setting the stage for a GOP filibuster 
when the issue comes up in the Senate next month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
