<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Afternoon storms soaked parts of the Northeast, mid-Atlantic and  
Southeast on Thursday, while lighter rain fell on parts of the West 
and high pressure kept the central states clear. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front approaching the Northeast and mid-Atlantic states  
triggered afternoon showers and thunderstorms from West Virginia to 
western New York state. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms were expected to increase in coverage and intensity,  
bringing wind gusts to 50 mph, hail and heavy rain, reaching 
coastal areas in the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	On the front's southern tail, foul weather menaced parts of  
Georgia, Alabama, Florida, Tennessee and North Carolina -- where 
more than half an inch of rain had fallen by midday -- but wasn't 
expected to match the intensity of the northern storms. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure dominated the central and western United States,  
with fair to partly cloudy skies from the Mississippi Valley, 
through the Plains into the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Mild showers and storms formed in the Southwest by midday, while  
light rain in Northern California was expected to spread into 
southwestern Washington later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday Thursday, temperatures around the country had gone  
from a low of 27 in Stanley, Idaho, to 98 in Elizabeth City, N.C. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
