<HEADLINE> Md. Dad Charged in Child's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) -- A father was charged with murder Thursday  
after his son was killed and his daughter critically wounded in 
what he claimed was a carjacking by a hitchhiker who threw him into 
a river. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Spicknall II, 27, was arrested around 4 p.m., more than  
eight hours after the children were found in the car. Police said 
Richard Spicknall III, 2, and Destiny Array Spicknall, 3, had been 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they had not established a motive. Spicknall was  
being held pending a bond hearing Thursday night on charges 
including murder and attempted murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation began about 2:40 a.m., when Spicknall called  
police to report that an armed hitchhiker he picked up on a bridge 
over the Choptank River on Wednesday night had thrown him into the 
water 25 feet below, and that his car and children were missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Spicknall called police from a fishing pier more than three  
hours after he said he was thrown into the river. Police found him 
at the phone, dripping wet. 
</P>
<P>
	Around 8 a.m., construction workers found the car parked behind  
a house about a half mile from the bridge, said Maj. Greg Shipley, 
a state police spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Spicknall is separated from the children's mother, Lisa  
Spicknall, 24. He told police he was taking his children to see 
their grandparents in Ocean City when he stopped for the 
hitchhiker, whom he described as an older, bearded white man 
wearing a tan T-shirt and blue jeans. 
</P>
<P>
	According to court documents, Spicknall filed for bankruptcy in  
May. At the time, he had been working for eight months as a manager 
at the ESPN Zone theme restaurant and bar in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Cambridge is 50 miles southeast of Baltimore on Maryland's  
Eastern Shore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
