<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Hear Switched Baby Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The Virginia Supreme Court has refused to  
hear a woman's appeal of a settlement between a hospital and her 
biological daughter, who was switched at birth with another baby. 
</P>
<P>
	In a two-sentence ruling Thursday, the court said ``there is no  
reversible error'' in a Buena Vista judge's approval of the 
University of Virginia Medical Center's $875,000 settlement for 
4-year-old Rebecca Chittum and the families raising her. 
</P>
<P>
	Paula Johnson had claimed that as Rebecca's biological mother,  
she had a right to approve or veto the settlement, which she 
considered insufficient. She is suing the hospital for $31 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson's lawyer, Cynthia Johnson, said she had not seen the  
ruling and had not had a chance to discuss it with her client. She 
declined further comment. The lawyer and client are not related. 
</P>
<P>
	Paula Johnson discovered last year that the child she had been  
raising, Callie Marie Johnson, was not her own. 
</P>
<P>
	Her biological baby, Rebecca, had been sent home with Whitney  
Rogers and Kevin Chittum a few days after her 1995 birth, and that 
couple's true daughter was sent home with Ms. Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson learned the truth a few days after Chittum and Ms.  
Rogers died in a car crash on July 4, 1998, without ever learning 
of the switch. Since then the parents of Chittum and Ms. Rogers 
have been raising Rebecca. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 5, a judge approved the settlement between the  
hospital, Rebecca and the grandparents who have been sharing 
custody of her. But Ms. Johnson claims she had a right to approve 
or reject any settlement for the child. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the University of Virginia Medical Center, where the  
switch was made, said the decision confirms ``that the amount of 
the settlement is fair and is in the best interests of this 
child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the agreement call for Rebecca to get $200,000 up front  
and $400,000 in an annuity that would be worth $1.5 million in 25 
years. The grandparents would share $125,000, and their lawyer 
would get $150,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
