<HEADLINE> Capitals Re-Sign Svejkovsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ODENTON, Md. (AP) -- The Washington Capitals re-signed free agent  
right wing Jaroslav Svejkovsky on Thursday to a three-year deal for 
approximately $1.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Svejkovsky's contract calls for about $550,000 in the first  
year, followed by $600,000 and $650,000 in the remaining two 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Svejkovsky has shown flashes of talent while playing with the  
Capitals for parts of the last three seasons, and the team's front 
office views him as one of its brighter young stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yogi has been a prolific scorer at each level of hockey he's  
played,'' Washington vice president and general manager George 
McPhee said. ``Injuries the last two seasons have hampered his 
production in the NHL, but we are expecting big things from Yogi 
this season and in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year old native of Czech Republic had six goals and eight  
assists in 25 games last year, but injuries sidelined him for 52 
contests. Svejkovsky's best moments came during a seven-game point 
streak where he had three goals and five assists. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-1, 193-pound Svejkovsky also had four goals and one  
assist in 17 games two years ago. He was named the American Hockey 
League's player of the year in 1996-97 after a 38-goal, 28-assist 
performance with the Portland Pirates. 
  	   	
</P>
