<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Champion Expects Tougher Course  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Before competing in the 1998 Comfort  
Classic, Hugh Baiocchi got a few pointers about the mechanics of 
his game from fellow Senior PGA Tour pro Steve Veriato. 
</P>
<P>
	Baiocchi then set a tournament record with a bogey-free,  
20-under-par effort that gave him a two-stroke victory over Bruce 
Summerhays and a six-shot margin over the rest of the field. 
</P>
<P>
	As he prepared for Friday's opening round of the 1999  
tournament, Baiocchi spent some time on the putting green with 
Craig Farnsworth, a psychologist who assisted CBS golf commentator 
Gary McCord on his instruction book. Baiocchi said McCord gave him 
some thoughts on visualization and reading greens. 
</P>
<P>
	Does another round of pointers translate to another victory?  
</P>
<P>
	``Who knows? Lightning might strike twice,'' Baiocchi said,  
chuckling. 
</P>
<P>
	Baiocchi's battle with the Brickyard Crossing Golf Course on the  
grounds of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway was pretty much a 
laugher last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty under was fairly spectacular. I would think something  
in the region of 14 to 15 (under) would be good. I certainly would 
take that,'' he said. ``These are the best seniors in the world. I 
don't know how you defend a course against these guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	You give it more water when it has been as dry as it has this  
summer, course superintendent Jeff Stuart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we try to do is provide consistent conditions, try to  
accommodate the (PGA) officials' requests,'' Stuart said. ``Last 
year was an exception. We didn't have any wind. The greens were 
fairly receptive. There was a lot of roll on the fairways. They 
shot well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More water, and conditioning that water to make it penetrate  
quicker, have made the fairways softer, eliminating much of the 
roll, Stuart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we'll see those scores again,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Baiocchi, 53, is more concerned about the competition than the  
course, especially with 50-year-old Tom Watson making his senior 
tour debut Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm playing OK,'' said Baiocchi, who has top-10 finishes in  
seven of his last 10 tournaments. ``These guys are so damned good. 
And with Tom Watson in the field, that's going to raise the bar 
even higher.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
