<DOCNO> APW19990909.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 22:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> STDs on Rise for Gay Seattle Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- An apparent increase in risky sexual behavior may  
be contributing to a re-emergence of syphilis and gonorrhea among 
gay men in the Seattle area, according to federal health officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington's King County, which includes Seattle, cases of  
syphilis jumped from zero in 1996 to 46 in the first half of 1999, 
while gonorrhea went from 180 cases per 100,000 gay men in 1997 to 
430 in 1998 and 420 in 1999, the Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The outbreak has alarmed health officials because those infected  
with syphilis run a much higher risk of acquiring and transmitting 
the AIDS virus, the CDC said. More than 70 percent of the gay men 
infected with syphilis there had the AIDS virus. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think if we're not able to reverse these kinds of behavior,  
increased HIV rates will follow,'' said Alonzo Plough, director of 
public health for Seattle and King County. 
</P>
<P>
	After an epidemic in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the number  
of cases of syphilis in King County dropped off dramatically in the 
mid-1990s. The estimated rate of syphilis in the Seattle area is 
projected at 200 per 100,000 gay men for 1999, compared with 90 per 
100,000 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The exact reason for the rise in the sexually transmitted  
diseases is unknown, but the CDC said it appears to be due to an 
increase in unprotected sex with anonymous partners, especially in 
places like bathhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC and other health officials have warned recently about  
growing complacency about AIDS because of the powerful new drug 
cocktails that can subdue the virus. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar syphilis outbreaks in gay men have been reported in San  
Francisco and Chicago, the CDC said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ironic that the successes on the drug treatment side can  
gives us even greater prevention challenges,'' Plough said. 
</P>
<P>
	Syphilis causes rashes and lesions and, if left untreated, can  
lead to degeneration of bones, heart and nerve tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	George Bakan, senior editor of the Seattle Gay News, called for  
a ``reinvigorated education effort for gay men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's an absolutely dangerous decline in the amount  
of educational programs'' promoting safe sex, he said. ``Maybe 
we've lost that momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we always assume that young people just assimilate  
this information, and they don't. Many of these people come from 
homes where sex was just not talked about.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Scope of the Waco Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	An order on the Waco inquiry signed by Attorney General Janet  
Reno gives John Danforth authority to investigate whether any 
government employee or agent, in regard to the events of April 19, 
1993: 
</P>
<P>
	--''Made false or misleading statements, allowed others to make  
false or misleading statements, or withheld evidence or 
information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--''Destroyed, altered or suppressed evidence or information.''  
</P>
<P>
	--''Used any incendiary or pyrotechnic device.''  
</P>
<P>
	--''Started or contributed to the spread of the fire.''  
</P>
<P>
	--''Engaged in gunfire.''  
</P>
<P>
	Also, whether:  
</P>
<P>
	--''There was any illegal use of the armed forces of the United  
States in connection with the events leading up to the deaths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In conclusion, ``If the special counsel believes it is necessary  
and appropriate, the special counsel is authorized to prosecute 
federal crimes arising from this investigation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
