<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *American Home Products Corp., down 2 1/4 at 40 1/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Already the subject of thousands of civil lawsuits over its diet  
drugs, American Home Products now faces a federal investigation 
involving the government's 1996 approval of the drug Redux, 
according to published reports. 

</P>
<P>
 *BP Amoco PLC, up 4 11/16 at 115 13/16  
</P>
<P>
 *Exxon Corp., up 1/16 at 81 1/4	
</P>
<P>
 *Chevron Corp., up 3 1/8 at 97 9/16 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks continue to benefit from rising crude prices. In its  
inventory report released Wednesday evening, the American Petroleum 
Institute showed a larger-than-expected drop in oil stocks. 

</P>
<P>
 *Navigant Consulting Inc., up 3 3/4 at 48 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Navigant, a management consulting firm, hired Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;  
Jenrette as a financial adviser to explore strategic alternatives, 
including a potential merger with a larger company. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Drypers Corp., up 1 1/32 at 3 11/32    	
</P>
<P>
	The Houston diaper manufacturer will supply Wal-Mart Stores Inc.  
with private label diapers through an expanded marketing agreement. 
Drypers said the deal should help it achieve strong growth in the 
second half of 1999 and in 2000. 

</P>
<P>
 *NMT Medical Inc., up 1 11/16 at 3 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The medical-device maker received approval from the Food and  
Drug Administration for humanitarian use of CardioSeal, a cardiac 
implant designed to close holes in the heart. Approval for 
humanitarian use requires fewer clinical tests. 

</P>
<P>
 *Avant! Corp., up 9 1/16 at 23 13/16    	
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. District Court judge ruled Cadence Design Systems Inc.  
cannot pursue trade secret claims against Avant, a rival 
chip-design software company. Cadence has alleged that Avant stole 
certain software to design competing products. 

</P>
<P>
 *American Xtal Technology Inc., down 3 9/16 at 24 7/16    	
</P>
<P>
	American Xtal will suspend shipment of its germanium wafers to  
Hughes Electronics Corp.'s Spectrolab unit, cutting revenue by 
about $1 million a month. Spectrolab cited weakness in the 
satellite market. 




  	   	
</P>
