<DOCNO> APW19990909.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 16:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  A's Get Boost From Appier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Kevin Appier had just given up a bloop,  
two-out, two-run, game-tying single to Darren Lewis in the 
Athletics' biggest game of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as he pitched to the next batter, he felt a sting in his  
chronically sore right leg and limped a bit around the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Art Howe and team trainer Larry Davis hurried out to  
check on him, but Appier just growled, told them to get off the 
field and reared back to strike out Mike Stanley. 
</P>
<P>
	And with that, Appier pushed through the pain and kept Oakland  
close in what shapes up as a pulsating race with Boston for the AL 
wild-card berth. The Red Sox lead Oakland by three games with 22 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's wound up 6-2 winners Wednesday in their last meeting of  
the year with the Red Sox, snapping Boston's four-game winning 
streak and ending their own three-game skid. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got Kevin because he's a true professional, and that's why  
he was brought here,'' first baseman Jason Giambi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Appier spent his 10-year career in Kansas City before coming  
Oakland in a July 31 trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's pitching out there hurt,'' Giambi said. ``He wants to be  
a part of all this and the whole team knows it and we get up for 
his games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he was pitching in a game the A's absolutely had to have to  
maintain a realistic chance at catching the Red Sox. Appier would 
go six innings, allowing two runs and four hits. He finished by 
fanning pinch-hitter Reggie Jefferson with two on and two outs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can tell a guy who's a warrior by the way he leaves it all  
out there on the field,'' A's catcher Mike Macfarlane said. ``That 
last strike to Jefferson was filthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Relievers Tim Kubinski and Doug Jones completed the five-hitter  
begun by Appier. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was one of my better outings,'' said Appier, who improved  
to 5-3 with a 5.63 ERA as a member of the A's. ``I was pumped up 
but it was real easy to get pumped up for this one. There was a lot 
on the line and fortunately we played a great game. I'm hoping we 
can play great ball from here on out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appier, who has been bothered by a nagging thigh muscle injury  
since early in the season with Kansas City, said he thinks he can 
get through the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It barked a couple times while I was out there but I don't  
think it inhibited me,'' Appier said. ``It's improved over last 
game and hopefully these last few games, it will be all the way 
back to normal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giambi said the A's are counting on Appier to steady the club's  
young pitching staff as the team gears up for its playoff push. And 
Appier delivered a key lesson with his gritty performance 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin has always been a great pitcher,'' Giambi said. ``He's  
just been snake bit a couple times but he came back strong in a 
huge game for us and we needed that kind of game out of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a heck of a lot easier being three games down than five  
games down. It would have been nice to be two back, but we'll take 
where we are, try to take care of our business every night and see 
where we go from here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland opens a seven-game road trip Friday in Tampa Bay.  
</P>
<P>
	Boston, 4-2 midway through what Butch Huskey calls the team's  
road trip of the year, finishes it against two top teams, starting 
a series Friday in New York before going to Cleveland for three 
more games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a pretty good situation. We're still three games  
up,'' said Boston's Pat Rapp, an unlucky loser Wednesday when three 
Red Sox errors led to four unearned runs. ``We have tough teams 
coming up on the road trip and we still have to battle.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 16:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
