<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sony Signs On With TiVo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) -- Sony Corp. of America joined a growing  
list of companies rushing to market the latest device for couch 
potatoes by taking a stake in TiVo Inc., a maker of digital video 
recorders that could one day replace VCRs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony plans to invest more than $25 million in Sunnyvale,  
Calif.-based TiVo and will become one of the company's two 
producers of ``personal video recorders'' -- set-top devices that 
rely on hard drives rather than videotape to record television 
shows. TiVo had already signed up Philips Electronics to 
manufacture the devices, which began selling at Best Buy stores on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	PVR technology allows viewers to replay a portion of a program  
while the machine continues to record the rest and can skip over 
commercials more readily than VCRs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony would own or 8.8 percent of TiVo after the company's  
upcoming initial public offering, TiVo said Wednesday in an amended 
registration with the Securities and Exchange Commission. TiVo 
plans to sell another 5.5 million shares to the public, hoping to 
raise at least $71.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	TiVo is one of two California companies that have developed PVR  
technology. Replay Networks of Mountain View also has developed the 
technology and has licensed Matsushita Electronic Co.'s Panasonic 
to sell its product. 
</P>
<P>
	The devices range in price from $499 to $1,499. TiVo also  
charges a monthly service fee. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins Players Injured, Sidelined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Second baseman Luis Castillo's breakthrough season  
with the Florida Marlins may be over. 
</P>
<P>
	Castillo dislocated his left shoulder during Wednesday's 5-4  
victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers in 13 innings. He'll be 
sidelined indefinitely, but there's a chance Castillo can return 
before the end of the season, manager John Boles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida also lost outfielder Todd Dunwoody, who fractured his  
left thumb when he was hit by a pitch in the 12th inning. He's out 
for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Castillo hurt his shoulder diving for a ground ball in the  
ninth. He injured the same shoulder in the minor leagues in 1995, 
missing the second half of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Castillo has been perhaps the Marlins' best player this year,  
hitting .302 and stealing 50 bases. He tied a club record with a 
22-game hitting streak that ended Sept. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the 23-year-old second baseman's first full major-league  
season. He won a starting job in spring training and is now 
considered a cornerstone of the franchise's future. 
</P>
<P>
	``With our club, if he doesn't get on base, we have a heck of a  
time scoring,'' Boles said before Wednesday's game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
