<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Cable Co. Formed in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Telecommunications group France Telecom and French  
conglomerate Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux are pooling their cable TV 
assets to create a new company. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture announced Thursday, which represents a long-awaited  
regrouping in France's cable industry, will serve 2.2 million 
homes. 
</P>
<P>
	France Telecom, a former government monopoly that owns France's  
cable lines, and Suez Lyonnaise, a major utility company that also 
provides cable services, will initially hold 49.9 percent and 50.1 
percent stakes respectively in the new company. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, the product of a year of tough negotiations,  
calls for the signing on of a third partner with expertise in the 
cable industry to join in the venture by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The new partner, who has yet to be named, will buy a stake of up  
to 20 percent in the new company while Suez Lyonnaise will reduce 
its interest to around 38.4 percent. France Telecom will gradually 
sell out of the group in the next three years, after which shares 
in the company will be floated on the stock market. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
