<DOCNO> APW19990909.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 01:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Wavers on Immigration Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, facing criticism  
from rival GOP presidential candidates, backed off his vow to deny 
border states reimbursement for illegal immigration-related costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican front-runner told the San Francisco Chronicle  
last week that if elected, he would not pay California back for the 
billions of dollars illegal immigration costs annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not a federal role,'' Bush told the newspaper.  
</P>
<P>
	Those costs include providing illegal immigrants medical  
treatment and education, and incarcerating the criminals among 
them. A 1982 U.S. Supreme Court ruling held that states must 
educate illegal immigrants, and the federal government requires 
states to provide them emergency medical care. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign later said the governor misunderstood the  
question. It released a statement saying that Bush believed he was 
being asked whether the federal government should reimburse state 
for costs of education funding in general. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chronicle, in a story published Wednesday, said its reporter  
specifically asked Bush whether he would reimburse California for 
money the state spends on services and education for illegal 
immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush is supportive of  
reimbursing states for incarceration, education and medical 
treatment of illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, such reimbursements are sometimes inadequate and should  
be improved, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	When he took office as Texas governor, Bush inherited and later  
supported a lawsuit seeking reimbursement from the federal 
government for the costs of illegal immigration. A federal judge 
dismissed it in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican candidate Steve Forbes, riding an Amtrak train toward  
Philadelphia, denounced Bush's position as published in the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes likened border states' immigration costs to a natural  
disaster, and said the federal government should help, just as it 
does after an earthquake or a hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	``Controlling the borders is a national responsibility,'' Forbes  
said. ``I think it's a national responsibility to reimburse states 
for those costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., also seeking the presidential  
nomination, said the federal government's ``refusal'' to reimburse 
California helped precipitate divisive battles over illegal 
immigration. 
</P>
<P>
	``One issue on which those on all sides of the immigration  
debate can agree is that the federal government must meet its 
obligation to reimburse state and local governments for the costs 
associated with illegal immigration,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Harrison, a spokesman for the California Finance  
Department, said the cost of educating illegal immigrants in the 
state is estimated at about $2 billion a year. The federal 
government does not pay for any of that, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It costs the state $577 million to incarcerate undocumented  
immigrants; the state received $173 million from Washington in the 
1998-99 budget year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis has requested $273 million from the federal  
government for 1999-2000, Harrison said, ``basically to make a 
statement that they owe us more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
