<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Global Y2K Air Readiness of Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two months after a deadline, nations worldwide  
are rushing to report the readiness of their airlines and airports 
for the Year 2000 computer problem. 
</P>
<P>
	As of the end of August, 53 countries still had not responded to  
a survey issued by the International Civil Aviation Organization, a 
U.N. group that sets international flight standards. In recent 
days, the number has fallen to 41. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montreal-based organization had asked its 185 members to  
respond by July 1, so other nations could gauge where it will be 
safe to fly on New Year's Eve, when older computers may malfunction 
at the start of the 2000. A report by ICAO, originally due to be 
released by July 31, is now scheduled to be released this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Mead, inspector general of the Transportation  
Department, told a joint meeting of two House subcommittees 
Thursday that it is imperative the lagging nations disclose their 
readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Time is running out,'' Mead said. ``In our opinion, these  
`uncertainties' should be resolved by Oct. 15, 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denis Chagnon, an ICAO spokesman, downplayed the impact of the  
nations' tardiness. ``The ones that have not responded represent a 
small portion of international traffic,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	They include Fiji, the Cook Islands and Papua, New Guinea,  
according to data provided by the Federal Aviation Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	In other testimony to the two panels -- the Science technology  
subcommittee and the House Government Reform and Oversight 
management subcommittee -- a government official said international 
airlines also appeared to be playing catch-up with their Year 2000 
preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Willemssen, head of civil agencies information systems for  
the General Accounting Office, said the FAA had collected 
information on 146 international airlines between April and May. 
According to its latest figures, about 33 percent said their 
computer systems were ready for the Y2K problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 35 percent planned to complete their work by Sept. 30,  
and the remaining 32 percent planned on a later date or did not 
provide information. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the International Air Transport Association,  
which represents international airlines, told a New York news 
conference that travelers should not be concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel confident any airline that chooses to fly  
internationally can do so safely,'' said spokesman William 
Gaillard. ``There will be no safety and security issues that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In general terms, the Year 2000 problem could affect older  
computers. Some were programmed to recognize years in two-digit 
format, such as ``99'' for 1999. There is concern that they may 
misconstrue the Year 2000, or ``00,'' as the start of 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	As of June 30, the FAA said its systems were ready. U.S. and  
Canadian airlines said recently their systems were 95 percent ready 
and would be fully prepared by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Transportation Department plans to issue advisories soon  
about international destinations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
