<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Faces Boxing Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Boxing's bad boy is coming to the Motor City next  
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamboyant WBO featherweight champion Prince Naseem Hamed will  
face WBC titleholder Cesar Soto in a 12-round unification match on 
Oct. 22 at Joe Louis Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The Englishman, of Yemeni descent, is considered one of the  
hardest punchers in boxing -- pound-for-pound. But he is best known 
for his leopard-print trunks and his 10-minute entrances that 
finish with a flip over the top rope and into the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've brought some flash into boxing when it badly  
needed it,'' Hamed said. ``I'm supremely confident, but I always 
back it up. There's no pressure on me, because I know what I will 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in his unbeaten career, Hamed made several Muhammed  
Ali-like predictions of the exact round he would win by knockout. 
But after his last two fights produced just a decision win and an 
11th-round knockout, and since he's facing someone who has never 
been knocked out in an 11-year career, he declined to do much 
prognosticating. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to make any predictions, because I've been wrong  
the last couple times,'' he said Thursday. ``We are both heavy 
punchers, so I think it will end in a knockout, but it could be 
early or it could be late. I just know that it won't be me getting 
knocked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Soto's WBC belt is more prestigious than Hamed's WBO  
title, the Mexican will enter the ring as a huge underdog. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I expect to win the fight,'' Soto said through an  
interpreter. ``We both hit very hard, so I don't think the fight 
will last long. I'm going to fight like a true Mexican warrior -- an 
Aztec.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The card, which will also include a super-bantamweight title  
fight between Erik Morales and Wayne McCullough, will be televised 
live by HBO. That will mark the first time in nearly 30 years of 
boxing that HBO will present a card from Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	On the undercard, Thomas Hearns, a Detroit boxing legend, will  
defend the pbscure IBO cruiserweight title against Crawford Ashley. 
Trainer Emanuel Steward expects it to be the 40-year-old Hearns 
last fight in Detroit, with his career scheduled to end in a 
pay-per-view fight in Las Vegas in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were offered a fight with Ashley last year, but we turned  
it down,'' Steward said. ``He's a tough guy, and we know we are 
bringing in a competitive fighter. Then we should wrap it up in 
December, but we don't know who that will be with yet. The 
mandatory IBO defense is Virgil Hill, but Tommy beat him already, 
and he's a dull fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hearns has been a welterweight, junior middleweight,  
middleweight and light heavyweight champion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
