<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Finally Open in Detroit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Teachers welcomed 180,000 students to their first  
day of classes today after testing the reform-minded school board 
and their own union leaders by staying off the job for more than a 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Detroit Federation of Teachers voted  
overwhelmingly Wednesday to return to work this morning. Some 
headed back to their schools after the vote to begin classroom 
preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	At Joy Middle School, pupils were greeted by yellow and blue  
balloons and ribbons and held a back-to-school rally. Terrance 
Knight, 28, attended with his son, Christopher Long, who started 
the sixth grade today. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can't wait to get going,'' said Knight, who added that it  
was tough to get his children to go to bed on time Wednesday night. 
His daughter started eighth grade. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngsters have a half-day of classes today, followed Friday  
by a full day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased with the teachers' decision to return to  
school immediately. We believe that the return to schools will 
allow Detroit Public Schools to maintain the momentum that was 
developed for improvements in the school system,'' the district's 
chief executive, David Adamany, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's vote by the 11,500-member teachers union didn't  
guarantee an end to the strike that began Aug. 30, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers merely voted to approve a temporary extension of their  
old contract until the union could organize a vote on whether to 
ratify a tentative agreement reached with the school district on 
Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratification ballots were expected to be mailed to teachers  
around Sept. 20, said Keith Johnson, the union's lead negotiator. 
Rejection of the tentative deal could send teachers back to picket 
lines, but Johnson said he didn't think that was likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got an overwhelming vote of confidence from our members,''  
he said. ``It's certainly an improvement from what was initially 
proposed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first academic year for the Detroit district since the  
Michigan Legislature put it under the control of Mayor Dennis 
Archer was to have begun Aug. 31. Union President John Elliott and 
bargainers for the district planned to extend the teachers' old 
contract by 10 days while talks over the new agreement continued. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Aug. 30, thousands of teachers surprised their union and  
the school board by rejecting the contract extension. That marked 
the beginning of a strike that drew fire from state lawmakers, who 
hinted that the teachers would face stiff penalties if they stayed 
off the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools in Detroit, the nation's 10th-largest city, performed so  
poorly that the state Legislature voted to remove the elected 
school board and replace it with a board appointed by Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	But some of the reforms proposed by Adamany -- including a longer  
school day and merit pay -- were sidelined after the teachers voted 
to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Elementary teacher Abdulhaleem Ibnjames said he was ready to go  
back to school. 
</P>
<P>
	``The contract is not to my liking, but when do you go to the  
negotiating table and get everything you want?'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
