<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks Entry to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- The scene is common across China's cities:  
migrants from the cramped countryside crowd street corners looking 
for work while nearby laid-off factory workers squat on sidewalks 
selling shoddy wares for change. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment by official admission is already at unsettling  
levels across China. And the communist government is about to 
increase the pain. 
</P>
<P>
	After a four-month suspension driven by acrimony with the United  
States, China is set to reopen negotiations this week to join the 
World Trade Organization. Even the most benign projections 
acknowledge that the market-opening concessions needed for 
membership will close factories and farms, forcing more people out 
of work. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, China's reform-minded leaders have become eager to  
make it into WTO and end a 13-year effort to join world trade's 
rule-making body. A deal could come as early as Saturday, when 
President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin join a summit 
of Pacific rim leaders in New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and China agreed today to restart negotiations  
on Chinese entry into the World Trade Organization, brightening the 
atmosphere before the presidential summit. The most senior U.S. and 
Chinese trade negotiators hashed out the decision in an 
unexpectedly lengthy three-hour meeting in Auckland, New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismal state of the economy and the potential for social  
unrest have made the Communist Party's leadership desperate for 
solutions, and one is WTO membership. Deficit spending and interest 
rate cuts have failed for nearly two years to arrest sliding 
economic growth and falling prices. Deflation is looming, and 
beyond that, perhaps a devaluation of the yuan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambitious reforms that Jiang and his premier, Zhu Rongji, hoped  
would remove the last vestiges of central planning from the economy 
have all but stalled. 
</P>
<P>
	After Clinton rejected a broad market-opening offer by Zhu in  
April, opponents of reform -- managers of big state industries 
fearful of competition, provincial politicians and communist 
conservatives -- coalesced and called the proposal a sellout. 
Military hawks wary of foreign intentions joined in after NATO 
bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, and China called off WTO 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese people ought to remind Chinese leaders not to  
place China-U.S. relations above the national interest,'' Gan Yang, 
a conservative scholar and magazine editor in Hong Kong wrote in an 
article that became an anti-WTO rallying call. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders hope joining WTO will spur the economy and  
``avoid political debates and ideological obstacles'' to further 
reform, said Hai Wen, an economist at Peking University. 
</P>
<P>
	``China is at a kind of crossroads because we are a socialist  
market economy,'' Hai said. ``The political risk is very high if 
you want to push for further market-oriented reforms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To recapture the initiative, Zhu sent foreign trade officials to  
major provincial cities during the past two months to sell WTO 
membership, Western and Asian diplomats said. The message, 
according to the diplomats, focused on the benefits of joining the 
WTO and the inevitability of global competition. 
</P>
<P>
	By binding China to a series of steps to lower tariffs and open  
its domestic markets, WTO membership would boost imports and 
exports, force cosseted state industries into the market and 
re-energize foreign investors whose interests have waned, Hai and 
other economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	WTO could bring China as much as a full percentage point of  
economic growth, according to an estimate by the solidly capitalist 
China International Capital Corporation Ltd., China's first 
investment bank. Even that slim margin could mean fewer jobs lost. 
</P>
<P>
	China's labor minister said last month that 7.4 million urban  
workers lost their jobs in the first half of the year, nearly as 
many as all of last year. On top of that, 130 million farmers are 
scouring cities for work. Beijing alone estimates it has 1.5 
million more migrants than needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outsiders come in here looking for work, and there are  
already so many laid-off people,'' said Cui, a retired factory 
worker who would only give his surname. He augments his pension 
repairing bicycles near the Yongding Gate overpass, one of many 
spots migrants gather hoping to pick up work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reform is bad and not reforming is bad too. The only thing is  
to reform slowly,'' Cui said with a resigned sigh. 
</P>
<P>
	China International Capital, in a recent report, predicted that  
WTO membership would push millions more farmers off China's tiny, 
inefficient farms. Chinese and Western economists expect workers in 
the automobile, pharmaceutical, telecommunications and steel 
industries to be hard hit. 
</P>
<P>
	By joining WTO now, Zhu and his government hope to be able to  
blunt the pain. A quick entry would give China a say in the next 
round of global trade talks, due to start in November. Agricultural 
tariffs are a key target. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
