<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.S.: No Troops for East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration sees no need to  
commit troops if a U.N. peacekeeping force is agreed to in East 
Timor because Australia and New Zealand already have promised such 
forces and other countries may make similar offers, a senior 
official says. ``America or nothing doesn't apply,'' the official 
said yesterday, adding that the administration could be helpful in 
other ways if U.N. peacekeepers are sent to the troubled province. 
In a bid to overturn last week's referendum, in which almost 80 
percent of East Timorese supported independence, rampaging armed 
militias with ties to the Indonesian military have created a 
humanitarian disaster in the province. 

</P>
<P>
	Analysts Brace for E. Timor Outcome  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- As East Timor sinks further into chaos,  
economists and analysts in this regional business hub say that 
Indonesia's response to the crisis could determine the country's 
economic future. ``How Indonesia handles the case will speak 
volumes to investors about the Indonesian government and armed 
forces,'' said Friedrich Wu, chief economist at Development Bank of 
Singapore, Southeast Asia's largest bank. Indonesia, the world's 
fourth-most populous country, is under severe international 
criticism for its conduct in East Timor, whose overwhelming vote 
for independence has been met by terror by pro-Jakarta militia. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Frees Palestinian Prisoners  
</P>
<P>
	BEITUNIYA, West Bank (AP) -- The first concrete sign that the  
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process is coming to an 
end walked out of prison today, as Israel released Palestinians 
held as security prisoners. By midmorning, a total of 200 prisoners 
held for anti-Israeli acts, such as killing suspected Palestinian 
collaborators and wounding Israelis, were to be released, including 
28 citizens of Arab countries. All signed a pledge not to revert to 
violence. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Wavers on Immigration Payments  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Responding to Republican rivals, Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush retracted a statement opposing federal 
reimbursements to states for costs they incur from illegal 
immigration. ``That's not a federal role, in my judgment,'' Bush 
told the San Francisco Chronicle last week. Those costs can include 
providing illegal immigrants medical treatment and education and 
incarcerating criminals among them. In 1982 the Supreme Court ruled 
states must educate illegal immigrants and the federal government 
now requires states to also provide ``emergency'' medical care to 
them. Bush's campaign issued a prepared statement yesterday saying 
he had ``misunderstood'' the question. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Toll in Greece Quake at 72  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Late-night rescues buoyed the spirits of  
emergency teams working round the clock, but there were few signs 
of life from dozens believed to still be trapped in crumbled 
buildings as the death toll from Greece's quake rose to at least 
72. Authorities scrambled to set up tents and find shelter in 
hotels for thousands sleeping outdoors in parks and soccer 
stadiums, while inspectors today were to expand checks on homes 
damaged by the capital's strongest quake in nearly a century. 

</P>
<P>
	14 Dead in Moscow Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Authorities searched for survivors and clues today  
after a huge explosion tore apart a nine-story Moscow apartment 
building, killing at least 14 people and leaving dozens more feared 
dead in the rubble. Rescue workers said at least 60 people were 
hospitalized with serious injuries after being pulled from the 
wreckage. Up to 100 people could be trapped in the debris, they 
said. The Federal Security Service, the country's main intelligence 
agency, launched an investigation into the blast. Some officials 
said it appeared to have been a natural gas explosion, but others 
said it was too early to rule out a terrorist attack. Police 
checked the wreckage for possible clues. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks End Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In Tokyo today, the Nikkei rose 36.18 points to  
close at 17,677.56. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones 
industrial average was up 2.21 points to close at 11,036.34. 

</P>
<P>
	McEnroe Is Captain of Davis Team  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- By winning seven Grand Slam championships, 77  
career singles titles and 77 career doubles crowns, John McEnroe 
had his share of tennis thrills -- right up there, though, was his 
appointment yesterday as captain of the U.S. Davis Cup team. ``It 
is one of the proudest moments of my life,'' McEnroe said after 
Judy Levering, president of the United States Tennis Association, 
named him to the post. Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi, who came into 
the U.S. Open ranked 1-2 in the world, have passed on Davis Cup 
play in the past, but seem enthused about McEnroe's appointment. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
