<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Leads in Airline Bumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines continues to lead the industry in  
the rate of involuntary passenger bumpings. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second quarter, Delta reported 5,519 bumpings -- nearly  
half the total of 11,908 for all 10 major airlines. The 
Atlanta-based carrier ranked worst in the industry with a rate of 
2.07 involuntary bumpings per 10,000 passengers, according to the 
figures released Wednesday by the Department of Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline with the next highest rate of involuntary bumpings  
was Southwest, which reported 2,509 bumpings for a rate of 1.48 per 
10,000 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Embarrassed by a similar ranking last winter, Delta vowed  
improvement. But a Delta spokesman said computer software deployed 
to fix the overbooking problem wasn't in use soon enough to be 
reflected in the April-June period. 
</P>
<P>
	``Starting in July, we've seen major progress that will be  
reflected in the next set of numbers,'' spokesman John Kennedy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most bumpings are voluntary, with passengers agreeing to take  
later flights in exchange for credits toward future flights. Delta 
reported 45,221 voluntary bumpings in the second quarter. That was 
second to American, which had 64,664 voluntary bumpings, but only 
717 involuntary. 
</P>
<P>
	Involuntary bumpings occur when planes are overbooked and some  
passengers are rerouted on later flights. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 18:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Won't OK Budget Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top congressional Republicans said Thursday  
they will not engage President Clinton in budget summit talks this 
year because he would insist on higher spending in exchange for the 
GOP's cherished tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not prepared to trade with the president with the  
American people's money, a spending buck for me, a tax reduction 
for you,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	While not ruling out that Republicans themselves will break  
budget limits to help push the coming fiscal year's spending bills 
through Congress, Armey renewed the GOP's pledge to use Social 
Security surpluses solely to reduce the $5.6 trillion national 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to let one dime of Social Security money be  
spent'' to expand other federal programs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to give a little and take a little,'' said  
Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, a Senate GOP leader. ``But we're going 
to have to protect Social Security, that's a must.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks partly reflect Republicans' distaste for high-level  
budget bargaining with Clinton and distrust of him. Many 
Republicans think Clinton has outfoxed them in past talks, and 
there is also resentment about decisions being made by a handful of 
GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments also underline the GOP's goal of casting this  
autumn's budget battle as their desire to protect Social Security 
vs. Clinton's plans for higher spending. Republicans say they will 
win the public relations war if voters view the budget fight that 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as Republicans rallied behind Social Security, their  
leaders were all but abandoning hope of achieving a major tax cut 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	As Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Wednesday,  
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said Thursday that Clinton's 
virtually certain veto of the GOP's $792 billion, 10-year tax cut 
will probably end this year's legislative battling over taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our one chance to do that,'' Hastert told reporters.  
He cited the difficulty of pushing a second tax package through 
Congress during this session's dwindling weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey and others insisted that their August strategy of staging  
hundreds of town meetings talking up tax cuts had worked. 
</P>
<P>
	But few opinion polls reflect a deep public interest in tax  
reductions. And about 10 conservative Democrats from districts 
where the popularity of tax cuts would be likeliest to appear said 
their voters prefer using surpluses for debt reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Clinton said Thursday he is willing to be flexible  
in reaching a tax cut deal this fall, but said the ball is fully in 
the GOP court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether there is (a compromise) bill, of course, is up to  
them. They can control what bills come up,'' Clinton said at the 
White House. ``But if they're saying, well, it's our way or no way, 
then that is evidence that this has been pretty much about politics 
all along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one believes the budget showdown will cause a shutdown of  
federal agencies, as occurred in 1995 and 1996. But short of using 
Social Security surpluses, it is unclear where GOP leaders will 
find enough money to push all 13 fiscal 2000 spending bills through 
Congress, let alone get Clinton's signature. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending bills finance agency budgets. So far lawmakers have  
sent just two of the measures to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 2000 begins on Oct. 1, just three weeks away. By then,  
GOP leaders plan to send Clinton a stopgap bill temporarily 
financing agencies while the two sides work through their spending 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Clinton wants more than $20 billion in spending beyond  
initial GOP plans. Even many Republicans want billions more for 
favorite programs, such as the $7 billion emergency package for 
farmers passed by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans plan to bridge some of the gap with the $14 billion  
non-Social Security surplus expected for next year. They had 
planned to use $5 billion of it for the tax bill, but Clinton's 
veto will let that portion be used for spending instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending any of that money will bust spending limits enacted in  
the 1997 budget-balancing law. GOP leaders have long conceded that 
those funds will be used, but will need billions more. Republican 
lawmakers and aides are scouring the budget for spending they can 
cut or delay. 
</P>
<P>
	As Congress worked through spending bills:  
</P>
<P>
	--The House by 235-187 approved a $92 billion measure financing  
housing, veterans and environmental programs. The White House has 
promised to veto it because of insufficient spending. 
</P>
<P>
	--Senate Democrats blocked a GOP effort to cut mass transit aid  
to New York and California as part of a $49 billion transportation 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	--Facing Democratic opposition, Senate Republicans set aside an  
effort to prevent the Clinton administration from raising royalties 
paid by oil companies drilling on public lands. 
</P>
<P>
	--House-Senate bargainers agreed to a compromise $28 billion  
measure financing the Treasury Department and smaller agencies. It 
would double the next president's salary to $400,000 and give 
members of Congress a $4,600 pay boost next January, raising their 
annual salaries to $141,300. 
</P>
<P>
	--The House passed, 208-206, a compromise bill providing $429  
million for the District of Columbia's municipal budget. The White 
House has threatened a veto because the bill prohibits the city 
from using other revenues to provide hypodermic needles to illegal 
drug users. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 18:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Microsoft Legal Filings Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government and Microsoft Corp. are  
expected to rebut each other's courtroom arguments in the final 
exchange of legal filings before the judge's initial ruling in a 
sweeping antitrust case. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides were under orders from U.S. District Judge Thomas  
Penfield Jackson to present by Friday their final written versions 
of the facts of the case. The filings could approach 1,000 pages 
for each side. 
</P>
<P>
	The filings also give them opportunity to rebut each other's  
arguments in the last batch of court papers submitted to the judge 
a few weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers will appear in court for a single day's closing  
arguments in less than two weeks, before the first phase of the 
judge's two-part verdict. That ruling could come as early as late 
October, although the case is almost certain to wind through 
appeals courts for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson is clearly interested in moving ahead. He has denied  
requests to delay the trial and limited the number of witnesses to 
testify. Last month at a law panel, he explained he was trying ``to 
avoid the Vietnam morasses'' that other antitrust cases, such as 
the breakup of AT&AMP;T, became. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft was expected to argue in its filing Friday that  
developments in the nation's high-tech industry undermine the 
government's antitrust claims. 
</P>
<P>
	A Microsoft attorney said the company will point to the  
remarkable financial success of Red Hat Inc., a leading vendor of 
the upstart Linux software operating system. Red Hat stock has 
soared from $14 on its first day trading last month to close 
Thursday at $123.25. 
</P>
<P>
	An economist who testified for the Justice Department, Franklin  
Fisher, had dismissed as ``a joke, of course'' the potential threat 
that Linux posed to the market dominance of Microsoft's Windows 
software. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microsoft lawyer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
the company will tell the judge it believes Linux to be ``real 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the essence of competition in this business,'' the lawyer  
said. ``You have to see the trend and react to it before it has 
market share or you'll be relegated to the history pages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department has argued that Linux has been successful  
challenging Microsoft in the sale of high-end business ``server'' 
computers, not consumer machines. 
</P>
<P>
	And Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates was quoted in earlier evidence  
in the trial as saying at a technology conference this spring that 
Linux's impact ``will be fairly limited'' and that he's never had a 
customer mention Linux to him. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also was expected to cite an announcement just days  
ago by rival Sun Microsystems Inc. that it has begun distributing 
free on the Internet a package of business applications meant to 
compete with Microsoft's Office software. 
</P>
<P>
	But asking Jackson to take ``judicial notice'' of the industry  
changes is an unusual legal ploy since the evidentiary record in 
the trial is officially closed. The judge can recognize these 
events but can't consider them as evidence because the government 
wasn't given the opportunity to challenge Microsoft's 
interpretation of their meaning. 
</P>
<P>
	One antitrust scholar said the recent business challenges to  
Microsoft were in part fueled by pressure exerted by the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government created an environment by which bolder moves by  
companies are going to occur,'' said William Kovacic, an antitrust 
expert at George Washington University. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kovacic described that effect as a double-edged sword for  
the government, since it appears to decrease the need for 
government action to restore competition in the high-tech industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tantalizing dilemma,'' he said. ``It reduces some of  
the urgency to intervene.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the trial began last October, the sides have met formally  
three times outside the courtroom, including once in early June. 
Future talks are anticipated later this year, but outside experts 
consider a settlement unlikely. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 18:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1 Dead, 500 Sick in E.coli Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Nearly 500 people have been sickened and one  
child died in the largest E. coli outbreak in state history -- and 
possibly one of the worst nationally -- health officials said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The outbreak of the deadly bacteria at the Washington County  
Fair, about 35 miles north of Albany, was likely caused by the 
contamination of the fair's water. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials said the water supply may have been tainted  
when rainwater washed over cow feces from a nearby farm and ran 
into an underground aquifer tapped by the fair's wells. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, officials were worried that the contamination may  
have spread beyond the Greenwich fair. 
</P>
<P>
	A fair worker who sold sausages might have taken three gallons  
of tainted water with her to use for coffee, lemonade and frozen 
treats at the Rensselaer County Fair in Schaghticoke, state Health 
Commissioner Antonia Novello said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Novello said no cases of E. coli had been connected to the  
Rensselaer fair, one county to the south. 
</P>
<P>
	By Thursday, 497 people had been treated at hospitals for E.  
coli symptoms, Novello said. Eighty-five case have been confirmed 
as E. coli poisoning, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A child, 3-year old Rachel Aldrich of Clifton Park, succumbed to  
the Greenwich outbreak. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests showed that one of the wells at the Washington County Fair  
was infected with E. Coli bacteria. Health officials also think 
that a deadly strain of E. Coli, 0157:H7, also came from that well, 
but they have yet to find any traces of it. 
</P>
<P>
	The well is near a cattle barn and the ground around it had been  
dug up for the installation of two new wells. Heavy rains in late 
August could have driven E. coli contaminated cattle manure into 
the well, Novello said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is possible that health officials will never find the deadly  
strain since the first tests for E. coli were done Sept. 3, four 
days after the fair ended, said Donald Dixon Despommier, a 
microbiology professor at Columbia University's School of Public 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like closing the barn door after the horses are already  
gone,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests on the well in June showed no contamination, health  
officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hall of Fame Honoring Globetrotters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- The Harlem Globetrotters will be  
honored by the Basketball Hall of Fame for their contributions to 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globetrotters are the first team to receive the John Bunn  
Award, named after the Hall of Fame's first executive director. The 
award, for outstanding contributions to the game, will be presented 
Sept. 30 as part of this year's enshrinement festivities. 
</P>
<P>
	Also being honored at the awards dinner are NBC broadcaster Bob  
Costas and the late Smith Barrier, who was executive sports editor 
of the News &AMP; Record of Greensboro, N.C., for more than 30 years. 
Both will receive the Curt Gowdy Award for their coverage of the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globetrotters, founded by Abe Saperstein and Inman Jackson,  
started barnstorming as the ``Savoy Big Five'' in 1926. Saperstein 
changed the name in 1930. 
</P>
<P>
	Then one night in 1939, with the Globetrotters leading by the  
score of 112-5, the players began clowning around to keep the crowd 
occupied. And more than 20,000 games later they are still amusing 
crowds with the ``pivot weave'' dreamed up by Jackson, the team's 
first ``Clown Prince.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1970s, the team was featured in a television cartoon  
series and in 1982 the Globetrotters became the only sports team to 
receive a star on Hollywood's Walk of Fame. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Reaches Pact on Anti-Drug Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Olympic officials reached agreement Thursday on  
the framework for a world anti-drug agency to be launched by the 
end of the year. But the location and head of the organization have 
yet to be decided. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee said a special working group  
achieved consensus on the possible structure for the agency, which 
is intended to spearhead a global campaign against banned 
performance-enhancing drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said documents will be finalized shortly and submitted  
to political and sports officials in time for the agency to be in 
place by Jan. 1 and fully operational before next year's Sydney 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the format, the statutes and possible terms of  
reference,'' IOC director general Francois Carrard, the project 
coordinator, said. ``I am reasonably confident the agency will be 
set up before Jan. 1. We are on schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said a foundation would be created under Swiss law in  
Lausanne, home of the IOC. The board of the foundation, including 
Olympic officials and some governmental bodies, will decide where 
the agency will be based and who will run it. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said several cities have expressed interest in serving  
as headquarters for the agency, including Lausanne; Vienna, 
Austria; Madrid, Spain; Lisbon, Portugal, and Stockholm, Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said the board would invite nominations for a chief  
executive to run the agency's day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Creation of an international anti-doping agency was approved in  
February at a world drug summit in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	That meeting produced heated debate over the status and location  
of the agency. Critics said the agency should be completely 
independent of the IOC and should not be based in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has insisted that it should play a leading role in the  
project, pointing out that it is putting up the initial $25 million 
to set up the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said the agency, as promised, would be up and running by  
the Sydney Games. But he said the agency was not designed to be 
directly involved in testing during those games. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's main task will be to coordinate year-round  
drug-testing programs around the world, particularly unannounced 
out-of-competition controls. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency will also seek to harmonize anti-doping policies and  
procedures, intensify research and educational programs and publish 
an annual list of banned substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the IOC allocated $2 million towards efforts to  
develop reliable tests for human growth hormone and EPO, two common 
performance-enhancing drugs which cannot be detected by standard 
urine controls. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 16:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ex-College Coach Raveling Ill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Former college coach George Raveling was  
hospitalized in Thursday after passing out while putting the Nike 
NBA All-Star team through a workout. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors at the Asepeyo clinic at Sant Cugat, just outside  
Barcelona, said Raveling would be kept overnight for observation. 
He was said to be in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, it was feared Raveling had suffered a heart attack,  
but doctors ruled that out and said the illness was more likely due 
to something the coach had eaten. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from Nike said Raveling had passed out because of  
stress from a busy schedule in recent months. The company said it 
expected him to be ready to coach the All Stars, which include 
Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen, for a game Friday against FC 
Barcelona. 
</P>
<P>
	Raveling, in his 31 years as coach, took three teams to NCAA  
Tournaments, Washington State, Iowa and Southern Cal. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the Olympic team and was voted national coach of the  
year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0134 </DOCNO>
