<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 18:54:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jockey Dies in LA County Fair Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POMONA, Calif. (AP) -- Jockey J.C. Gonzalez of Mexico was killed  
Thursday in a spill in the fifth race on opening day of the Los 
Angeles County Fair meeting at Fairplex Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, the Fairplex Park riding champion with 28 victories  
last year, died of head injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, 23, was leading the 1 1-16-mile race when his horse,  
Wolfhunt, broke down on the final turn. 
</P>
<P>
	Accommodator, ridden by Danny Sorenson, tripped while passing  
Wolfhunt, throwing Sorenson to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Both jockeys were taken to the Fairplex first-aid station, where  
Dr. Neal Archer pronounced Gonzalez dead. Sorenson was examined and 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the 12-race program was canceled.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're just saddened at Fairplex. He was a very special jockey  
to us because he won the jockey title last year in a runaway,'' 
said George Bradvica, the equine manager at Fairplex Park. ``He was 
a young kid, he was up and coming, and he was here to defend his 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all very upset. This is our 61st racing season. We've  
never had a fatality before, and it just hurts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, a resident of nearby Arcadia, won his first major  
riding title with 24 victories in the 1998 Hollywood Park fall 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez had 181 career victories in 1,478 races, with 172  
seconds and 161 thirds and earnings of $4,155,00. 
</P>
<P>
	In 237 starts this year, Gonzalez's mounts won 23 races and  
$365,310. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfhunt, the 5-2 second-favorite in a field of eight, broke  
both forelegs and was destroyed. Accommodator reportedly was in 
good condition, according to a track spokesman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 09:30:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed at Midday / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with the biggest names  
in technology outperforming the rest of the market. A sinking 
dollar held most stocks lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 0.95 at 11,037.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 2.02 at 1,342.13, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 15.22 at 2,823.96. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet and technology companies were the strongest performers  
in a relatively quiet, flat market. IBM, up 4 1/16 to 134 13/16, 
helped the Dow stay in positive territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo rose 5 15/16 to 159 3/8 after Lehman Brothers raised its  
rating on the stock to ``outperform'' from ``neutral.'' And online 
auctioneer eBay rose 5 1/16 to 139 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat, which sells Linux software, rose 6 1/2 to 123 1/4. The  
company's shares have been on a tear as it attracts more coverage 
from Wall Street brokerages, and got a further boost this week from 
Gateway Inc.'s decision to join the Linux operating system reseller 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big-cap technology stocks are performing well, and  
everything else is middling at best,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, 
chief investment strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader market was held to slim gains by the dollar's  
continuing decline against the Japanese yen. After the Japanese 
government released a stronger-than-expected report on the nation's 
economic growth, the dollar fell to 108.84 yen today from 111.22 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong report and the rising value of the yen helped push  
Japan's Nikkei stock average 0.2 percent higher. Weakness in the 
dollar has been a persistent undercurrent in the U.S. stock market 
in recent weeks, as improving economies in Asia and Europe attract 
investors who previously sought out U.S. securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington today, the Labor Department reported the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits fell 
unexpectedly last week to 286,000. Any level below 300,000 is 
considered a sign of an extremely tight labor market. 
</P>
<P>
	Wage pressures that could result from a tight labor market are  
among the concerns of the Federal Reserve as it watches out for 
inflation. The Fed has already raised interest rates twice this 
year, hoping to keep the economy from growing too quickly, and 
investors fear that a third rate increase will come later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will probably stay in a holding pattern until more data  
comes out,'' Battipaglia said. ``Each bit of economic data is 
important as people try to figure out what the Fed is going to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products dropped 3 7/16 to 38 7/8 amid reports that  
the company is facing a federal investigation involving the 
government's 1996 approval of the drug Redux. American Home 
Products has already seen its share price battered as the company 
faces thousands of civil lawsuits over its diet drugs, which have 
been linked to heart valve problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues and decliners were nearly even on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 341.98 million shares, behind 
Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.18 to 437.08.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0140 </DOCNO>
