<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 08:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Markets Close Mostly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mostly higher  
Thursday on unexpectedly strong news about Japan's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, news that the gross domestic product grew in the  
second quarter boosted share prices, but pushed the U.S. dollar 
lower against the yen. GDP is the measure of all goods and services 
produced in a country. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 36.18 points,  
or 0.21 percent, to 17,677.56. On Wednesday, the average had fallen 
0.37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Confounding market expectations, the Japanese Economic Planning  
Agency announced Thursday that the economy grew 0.2 percent in the 
April-June quarter, while the overall economy was growing at an 
annual rate of 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Market gains, however, were limited by the yen's continued rise  
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 108.84 yen in late trading, down 2.38 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
111.08 yen overnight. It ranged between 108.73 yen and 111.16 
during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen hurts Japan's exporters because it pushes up the  
prices of their goods overseas, making the companies less 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares surged 3.7 percent on optimism that China  
would finally be joining the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index soared 498.25 points to an  
eight-week high of 13,854.88. On Wednesday, the index had dropped 
0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders from China and the United States are expected to  
continue talks on the long-awaited WTO membership at the Asia 
Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in Auckland, New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stands to gain from likely growth in trade when China  
joins the WTO and opens up its market to foreign businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, shares surged 3.3 percent as investors snapped up  
blue chips, whose prices slumped in recent days on political 
uncertainties. 
</P>
<P>
	The JSX Composite Index ended up 17.394 points at 538.015.  
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares had plunged 4.5 percent Wednesday as foreign  
investors dumped their holdings amid threats by international 
lenders to suspend loans amid escalating violence in the territory 
of East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares soared 2.3 percent on buying in banking and  
finance stocks. The SET Index gained 9.52 points, to 431.08. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares fell on selling of selected blue chips. The  
Composite Index fell 3.91 points, or 0.51 percent, to 751.15. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell on regional currency concerns sparked by the  
chaos in East Timor. The PSE Index fell 31.98 points, or 1.5 
percent, to close at 2,133.60. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on selective buying by institutional  
investors. The Straits Times Index rose 30.02 points, or 1.4 
percent, to 2,127.42. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on gains by resource sector stocks. The All  
Ordinaries Index rose 7.4 points, or 0.20 percent, to 3,008.1. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares surged 1.5 percent on a stronger yen, which makes  
South Korean exports more competitive against Japanese goods. The 
Kospi soared 13.60 points to close at 950.53. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares rose on gains by computer-chip makers and a rise  
in bank earnings. The Weighted Price Index was up 51.72 points, or 
0.65 percent, at 8,025.02. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares closed higher on gains by market heavyweight  
Telecom Corp. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index was up 13.57, or 
0.64 percent, at 2,127.18. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
