<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:28:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President of PBS To Leave Oct. 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ervin S. Duggan, president of the Public  
Broadcasting Service for the past 5 1/2 years, announced Thursday he 
was leaving the job on Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Duggan said he had fulfilled his objectives for the Alexandria,  
Va.-based association of public television stations during his 
tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	``A strategy to create greater financial security and enduring  
value for PBS and its member stations is now in place,'' Duggan 
said in a statement. ``I have relished serving as a public champion 
of PBS's unique mission of education, culture and citizenship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Duggan's leadership, PBS increased revenues 70 percent --  
from $182 million in 1995 to a projected $309 million in 2000. PBS, 
which serves 100 million people weekly, also took on new ventures, 
including PBS Online and the PBS Kids channel. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a man who has really strengthened public television  
... both in terms of finances and in terms of extension of 
services. He is going to be very much missed,'' said Colin G. 
Campbell, chairman of the PBS board. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said Duggan courted congressional support when it  
seemed the network's funding was in jeopardy, and maintained 
quality programming in an era of increased competition from cable 
and other commercial ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Duggan's future, PBS spokesman Tom Epstein said, ``He's  
going to explore what else is out there. He felt he couldn't look 
for something new while he was still full time with PBS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PBS board member John F. Swope will serve as interim chief  
executive when Duggan leaves. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
