<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Day of Nines Goes By Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dreaded date 9-9-99 arrived Thursday with no  
immediate reports of any major Y2K-like computer trouble, boosting 
the confidence of the end-of-millennium programming experts. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been fears that the string of nines might cause some  
computers to misread the date as an old command to end a program. 
</P>
<P>
	But those concerns appeared to be largely unfounded, as most  
experts predicted after months of review and tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one more confirmation that our analysis and testing  
have been really solid,'' said T.D. Fehr, vice president for 
airplane systems at Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, computers abroad also behaved well, according  
to information from more than a dozen countries gathered by the 
International Y2K Cooperation Center in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The only possible glitch occurred at a Tasmania technical  
college where Australian officials were looking into reports of 
malfunctioning spreadsheet programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Year 2000 bug, which can cause some computers to wrongly  
interpret the two-digit year ``00'' as 1900, is still a looming 
issue. Nevertheless, Y2K officials believe that because they were 
on target Thursday, they should be on target with Jan. 1 
predictions, too. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``no one should be foolish enough to take this as a sign  
that we're going to coast through the Y2K changeover with no 
problems,'' warned Don Meyer, spokesman for the Senate's Y2K 
advisory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Several industries took advantage of the changeover to rehearse  
their New Year's Day operations and test backup systems. 
</P>
<P>
	About 15,000 employees from at least 400 electric utilities --  
from senior executives to janitors -- took part in a nationwide 
drill monitored by U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson from the 
Bonneville Power Administration in Vancouver, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	The test was designed to simulate electric outages in different  
parts of the country, test communications under those circumstances 
and determine how utilities and agencies would respond. 
</P>
<P>
	The results came up with another pair of ``9s'' -- as in 99  
percent ready for the millennium, Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there's still that 1 percent,'' Richardson said. ``And  
that 1 percent covers a lot of consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 9 was one of several dates that could cause computer  
trouble. The next one comes on Oct. 1, the start of the fiscal year 
for the federal government. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
