<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate To Vote on Timber Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate is weighing in on a controversy  
that has blocked already curtailed timber cutting on federal land 
in another dispute over protection of endangered species. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of timber sales by the U.S. Forest Service were put on  
hold earlier this year in the South and Northwest when federal 
judges found the government failed to adequately assess the 
potential harm to rare plants and wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was expected to vote today on an attempt to get  
around the court ruling by declaring that federal agencies -- and 
not the courts -- have the ``sole discretion'' on what surveys 
should be conducted. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., wants the provision deleted from a $14  
billion Interior Department spending bill that includes money for 
federal timber sales as well as other natural resource and energy 
programs. A vote on Robb's amendment was expected today. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the House turned back another effort to kill NASA's  
space station as Congress, returning from its summer recess, jumped 
into the first of a string of spending measures. 
</P>
<P>
	By a 298-121 vote, the House defeated an attempt by Reps. Tim  
Roemer, D-Ind., and Mark Sanford, R-S.C., to eliminate $2.4 billion 
for the space station, one of NASA's high profile programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision is part of a $92 billion measure financing  
veterans, housing, science and environmental programs for fiscal 
2000, which begins next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, sponsors of the Interior bill had hoped to finish  
the measure this week, but a dispute over oil royalty payments and 
a threat of a filibuster could push it into next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, wants to block the Clinton  
administration from boosting royalties paid by oil companies 
drilling on public lands, arguing the proposed rule change amounts 
to an additional tax on an industry already reeling from low oil 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchison's amendment would prevent royalty payment changes for  
at least another year. But Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., on 
Wednesday threatened to filibuster the massive spending bill if 
Hutchison's amendment were not withdrawn. She argues that under 
current royalty rules, oil companies are shortchanging the 
government by as much as $66 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The logging controversy stems from two federal court decisions --  
one in Georgia and another in Washington state -- in which judges 
determined that the U.S. Forest Service wasn't adequately surveying 
forests for endangered species prior to issuing logging permits. 
</P>
<P>
	First a judge blocked timber sales in the Chattahoochee National  
Forest in the South. Then, another judge suspended timber sales in 
Oregon and Washington under the compromise Northwest Forest Plan 
forged in 1994 as a way to allow limited cutting and still protect 
the endangered spotted owl. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sens. Slade Gorton of Washington and Larry Craig of  
Idaho crafted language in the Interior bill aimed at overcoming the 
new court restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig maintained the suspension of already curtailed timber  
sales amounted to a broken promise to loggers, who under the 1994 
agreement were assured some timber harvesting. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has estimated that about 550 million board feet of  
timber will not be cut in the Northwest because of the court 
requirement for more detailed forest surveys for sensitive species. 
Logging on 8,000 acres of federal forest in the South also has been 
affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., in debate on the Senate bill  
Wednesday, called the decision on the new survey requirements a 
``fraud'' aimed at reneging on promises made to loggers and a blow 
to logging communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about a survey vs. families, about snails and slugs  
vs. streets and schools,'' Smith said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
