<DOCNO> APW19990909.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 08:28:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ministers Criticize Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Ministers from the Americas, Asia  
and Europe criticized Indonesia today for failing to stop the 
terror in East Timor but stopped short of endorsing a peacekeeping 
mission to the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia indicated it could cope with the East Timor crisis on  
its own and did not want any uninvited interference from outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Some countries have urged the United Nations to send troops to  
stop a deadly rampage that pro-Indonesian militias launched after 
the territory voted for independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Jakarta declared martial law in East Timor on Tuesday, but the  
situation has not improved, government ministers said in an 
emergency session. The meeting was held on the sidelines of the 
annual Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian President B.J. Habibie on Wednesday canceled his trip  
to the APEC summit. 
</P>
<P>
	The only top-level Indonesian official in Auckland for the APEC  
meetings, Economic Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita, refused to 
attend the East Timor session. A lower-level Indonesian official 
attended but only listened, a senior U.S. administration official 
said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginandjar told The Associated Press that Indonesia was working  
to restore order and outside help should only be considered if 
Jakarta found a reason to request it. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we need assistance, we will ask for it, but I don't think  
we like to be pushed,'' Ginandjar said. The minister expressed 
concerns that some Western leaders had called for Jakarta to 
restore order quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``The term `quickly' is ambiguous, because, `How quick?'''  
Ginandjar said. ``The factions in East Timor have been fighting for 
a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Ginandjar said Indonesia did not want to be pushed, New  
Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said the foreign ministers are 
putting ``as much pressure as we can on the Indonesian 
government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and British officials agreed they would rather see the  
Indonesians restore peace on their own, but they're holding out the 
possibility of an international response. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's emergency meeting did little to move beyond earlier  
warnings to Jakarta, but officials said the consensus reached by 
most of the world's powerful and wealthy nations should give 
Indonesia a clear message that the crisis can't drag on 
indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Washington ruled out the use of U.S. troops in any  
international peacekeeping force and said any soldiers can't be 
sent in without Indonesia's blessing. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia annexed East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, in  
1975 but the occupation was never accepted by the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook came to the East Timor  
talks in Auckland to represent Britain and the European Union, even 
though Britain is not a member of APEC. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Britain was dispatching the Glasgow, a guided-missile  
destroyer, to the East Timor area in case it is needed. The British 
government also is considering the possibility of sending in ground 
troops as part of a peacekeeping force, Cook told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior International Monetary Fund official today stepped up  
pressure on Indonesia to rein in violence in East Timor, which he 
said was a necessary condition for the fund to continue with a 
rescue loan program. 
</P>
<P>
	``The events in East Timor are first of all a large human  
tragedy, and the international community including the IMF cannot 
be indifferent to that,'' Hubert Neiss, IMF's Asia Pacific 
director, told CNN on a nightly news program. ``We haven't 
threatened to cut off funding, but we have to work under the right 
conditions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
