<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 19:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Movement on L.A. Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Less than a week before an important deadline  
in the troubled effort to bring the NFL back to Los Angeles, the 
only decision a group of league owners could make was that a 
decision needs to be made soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``No recommendation, no consensus and a lot of different points  
of view,'' commissioner Paul Tagliabue said Thursday after a 
meeting of the league's expansion committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the dozen owners at the meeting, some remained determined  
to have the league place a team in the nation's No. 2 television 
market. Others expressed strong sentiment for Houston, where a 
financing plan for a new stadium is in place and awaiting an NFL 
go-ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that surprised me today was that there were so many  
divergent opinions,'' committee co-chairman Bob Kraft, owner of the 
New England Patriots, said. ``People who've spent a lot of time on 
this would like to see this end and let us get on with our other 
business. But the bottom line is we need to get 24 votes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league gave Los Angeles groups a six-month window to come up  
with a suitable site and financing plan for a stadium for the 
league's 32nd franchise. The deadline is Sept. 15, and four Los 
Angeles-area groups are still trying to make a viable case. The 
proposals include renovating the Los Angeles Coliseum or building a 
new stadium in nearby Carson, Hollywood Park or Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked with (NFL executive) Roger Goodell, and we are going  
back for a meeting on Monday,'' said Ed Roski, one of the 
businessmen leading the effort to bring a team to the Los Angeles 
Coliseum. ``I got the impression from him that Los Angeles was 
still very much alive and they want to hear our proposals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue said he and the committee co-chairmen will meet in New  
York with representatives of each of the four groups, plus Bob 
McNair, who heads the Houston effort. The commissioner said the 
deadline will remain in place, and the committee likely will 
discuss the matter via conference call between Sept. 15 and Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee would then take a vote at a meeting Oct. 5, on the  
eve of a full ownership meeting in Atlanta. The votes of 
three-fourths of the 31 owners are required to approve a final 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be making a final decision, hopefully, on the sixth of  
October,'' Tagliabue said. ``And that'll be based on the status of 
things as of Sept. 15.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue would not say which city or bid had the upper hand.  
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has essentially been trying to find its way back to Los  
Angeles since both the Raiders and Rams left town in 1995, but the 
league has not yet found a proposal to its liking. Asked if there 
could be another postponement, beyond the Oct. 6 meeting, Tagliabue 
wouldn't rule it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL often goes into overtime,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
