<DOCNO> APW19990909.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pats' QB Bledsoe Ready To Face Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Drew Bledsoe fidgeted on the sideline at  
the Meadowlands, his finger broken and his teammates beaten. 
</P>
<P>
	That was last December when the New England Patriots ended their  
regular season with a 31-10 loss to the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Bledsoe is fidgeting again, but this time it's because he can't  
wait to return to the Meadowlands. He's healthy now and will start 
in Sunday's season opener against the same opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be on the sidelines in a situation where I felt like maybe  
I could make a difference was very frustrating,'' he said. ``So I'm 
very excited to get back out there and start playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bledsoe broke his right index finger Nov. 23 against Miami, but  
still threw the winning pass with 29 seconds left in a 26-23 
victory. Despite the injury, he led the Patriots to two straight 
wins before losing to St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Zolak took over the next week in a 24-21 win over San  
Francisco, but flopped against the Jets and then Jacksonville in 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Bledsoe's back in control.  
</P>
<P>
	``This time around, we're able to put our best foot forward,''  
Patriots coach Pete Carroll said. ``This could be a very exciting 
time for the Patriots and he'll be the guy leading the charge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's added incentive as the Jets are 3-1 against the Patriots  
since Bledsoe's former coach, Bill Parcells, took over in New York, 
a move that turned up the hype on the rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's faded to a certain extent,'' Bledsoe said. ``There's  
still that motivation to go try and beat your old coach and beat a 
very good football team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1993, Bledsoe was simply feeling his way after being  
taken with the first pick in the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my rookie year in a lot of situations I was just dropping  
back and looking for somebody to get the ball to,'' he said. ``I 
didn't know too much about what was happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he took the Patriots to the playoffs in 1994 and to the  
Super Bowl two years later. They've been in the playoffs in four of 
his six seasons and Bledsoe has emerged as a team leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things have gotten bad, he's the one that steps up and  
says, `I'm raising my game. You guys can come with me or not but 
I'm going to raise my game anyway,''' wide receiver Shawn Jefferson 
said. ``He wants to win more than anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And so far the big prize -- a Super Bowl championship -- has  
eluded Bledsoe. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite holding most of the Patriots' passing records and three  
NFL marks, he's far from satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to win a championship,'' he said. ``That's what it's  
all about in the end unless you do something outlandish like (Dan) 
Marino where you throw for a bazillion yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a quarterback, you're judged by how many championships did  
you win and I've yet to prove that I'm capable of taking our team 
to a championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the years are flying by.  
</P>
<P>
	He can't believe he's in his seventh season, even though he's  
just 27 years old. And his original estimate that he'd play 10 
seasons and then retire may be changing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like I'm just getting started,'' Bledsoe said. ``I'll  
play as long as I'm having fun. I'll play as long as I feel 
effective and I'll play as long as I feel like we have a chance to 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, at some point, any one of those three things is no longer  
true, then I'll hang it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that probably would be with the Patriots. He said he'd  
retire rather than go to another team just for an opportunity to 
win an NFL title. 
</P>
<P>
	But he knows the chances to achieve that are few.  
</P>
<P>
	``This may be the best team I ever have a chance to play on,''  
Bledsoe said. ``So you have to have a sense of urgency going into 
each season and going into each game because you just don't know 
how many opportunities you're going to get.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
