<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurer Aims for Worker Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD (AP) -- Aetna Inc. is launching a new managed care  
program aimed at bringing workers who are out on disability back to 
work as quickly as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	HealthWorks, which will be offered nationwide next year, deploys  
case managers to work with an employee's doctor to ease the 
transition back to work from disability leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we can anticipate health-related absences, we're more  
likely to influence a successful recovery and transition back to 
productivity,'' said Frolly Boyd, head of group insurance for Aetna 
U.S. Healthcare. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Kroll, an analyst with SG Cowen Securities, Inc., in New  
York, said the program should be successful. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very positive program for Aetna,'' said Kroll. ``In  
getting people back to work, it's not just the employer who wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a national  
organization for health care consumers, said the program sounds 
fine on paper, but should be carefully evaluated. 
</P>
<P>
	``The value and the harm will totally depend on how they  
implement it,'' said Pollack. ``If it pressures people to come back 
to a job before their disability really warrants their coming back, 
then it will cause a great disservice to both the company and the 
person with the disability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Aetna maintains that the program is designed to help  
employers improve productivity while reducing steep health care 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we can anticipate health-related absences, we're more  
likely to influence a successful recovery and transition back to 
productivity,'' said Frolly Boyd, head of group insurance for Aetna 
U.S. Healthcare. 
</P>
<P>
	Disability is a major expense for U.S. employers. The 90 million  
Americans who suffer from chronic conditions such as asthma, 
diabetes, heart disease and back pain account for $1 of every $6 
spent on health care, according to a survey by the Agency for 
Health Care Policy and Research. 
</P>
<P>
	And according to Towers Perrin, a benefits consulting firm, the  
indirect costs of disability such as overtime wages and temporary 
replacements account for 12 percent to 20 percent of a large 
company's payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the HealthWorks plan, once an employee becomes disabled,  
an Aetna medical team that includes disability trained nurses and 
rehabilitation specialists coordinate case management. 
</P>
<P>
	Nurses would help teach the worker how to manage his or her  
disability at home. They also would collaborate with the patient's 
doctor and employer on a schedule for rehabilitation and return to 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The company began assembling the HealthWorks staff a year ago,  
selecting case managers from its nursing team. Aetna spokeswoman 
Julie Brown said the company chose individuals with the ability to 
effectively negotiate among a number of parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna, based in Hartford, Conn., is the largest U.S. provider of  
health benefits with 21 million members. It also is among the top 
four U.S. providers of disability insurance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
