<DOCNO> APW19990909.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 09:10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Just as many Christians go to church only on Easter and  
Christmas, many Jews enter synagogues only on the holiest of Jewish 
holidays, Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur. 
</P>
<P>
	Inevitably, some become overwhelmed by the prayers of  
repentance. Strangers in a strange land, they're lost before the 
first ``amen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Adin Steinsaltz, the Israeli scholar and mystic and author  
of the forthcoming book, ``Simple Words: Thinking About What Really 
Matters in Life,'' has reassuring words for the religiously 
unschooled: Don't try to keep up with the liturgy. Find one 
sentence in the prayer book that has meaning for you and focus on 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That,'' says the rabbi, ``is the beginning of a real  
connection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Connections are central to the rabbi's work, whether it's his  
three-decade project, a multi-volume translation of the Talmud, 
Judaism's 1,500 year-old compendium of tradition, law and legend; 
or ``The Thirteen Petalled Rose,'' a discourse on the essence of 
Jewish belief. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli scholars have called him a once-in-a-millennium thinker  
who speaks with authority and self-deprecating humor on topics from 
science fiction to Talmudic thought. He is known for his personal 
exploration of Jewish mysticism and his examination of the human 
soul as a spark of divine light. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New Year that starts Friday at  
sundown, begins a 10-day period of examination and rebirth known as 
the Days of Awe. It ends with Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement, 
when Jews communally confess their sins so they can renew their 
lives and turn toward God. 
</P>
<P>
	Such renewal, Steinsaltz said, can occur on an ordinary day.  
``It can be done when one is undressing,'' he said in a telephone 
interview from his home in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	But on the High Holy Days the synagogue becomes the stage for a  
more profound encounter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a meeting place,'' he says. ``As symbolic as it may be,  
in one way or another I'm coming to visit God ... It's a framework 
for thinking about subjects (people) didn't have time to think 
about all year ... `Am I really doing what I should do? What is 
really important for me?' It may begin a whole chain of thought and 
action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teshuvah, Hebrew for repentance, denotes both a return to God  
and a change of direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an endeavor to break away from the past and reach a  
higher level,'' Steinsaltz writes in ``The Thirteen Petalled 
Rose.'' ``Repentance is the highest expression of man's capacity to 
choose freely. It is a manifestation of the divine in man.'' Still, 
sudden transformation is rare even during the Days of Awe. 
</P>
<P>
	``(It's) generally ... a series of small turnings,'' he writes.  
</P>
<P>
	Turning toward God is the theme of many Rosh Hashanah and Yom  
Kippur prayers, and Steinsaltz says it can be a daunting prospect 
for religious and secular souls alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps our greatest difficulty in relating to God is our  
inherent inability to form any coherent understanding of the 
Almighty,'' he writes in ``Simple Words.'' Sometimes, people 
construct ways of understanding God that ``should be helpful 
crutches, but these crutches may actually cripple us instead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The main crutch, he says, is giving God a human face. ``For many  
people, the image of God is quite clear: a big, white-bearded man 
sitting on a throne very high in the sky. He has, at least 
figuratively, a stick in one hand, and a bag of candy in the other, 
bestowing each on his subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	``As enticing as this grandfather image of God is, it contains  
within itself its own destruction. The budding atheist or agnostic 
11- or 12-year-old is one who cannot -- with full justification -- 
continue believing in this definition of God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steinsaltz proposes another, plainer avenue toward understanding  
God: ``the belief that things somehow fit together into a whole 
that makes sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The mystical writings about God say things that every child  
knows,'' he writes. ```God, You are the completeness of 
everything.' 
</P>
<P>
	``The secret of belief is not to expect to see miracles, or to  
have grand mystical experiences, but rather, to preserve the innate 
notion they are born with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People looking for an immediate response from God during the  
High Holy Days are bound to be disappointed, he says. ``For most 
people, the ram's horn will sound at Yom Kippur's end without any 
revelations or signals that they are on the right track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steinsaltz writes with the consoling tone of a rabbi who has  
counseled many a discouraged disciple: ``A person generally hears 
the longed-for answer not when he puts his question, not when he is 
struggling, but when he pauses at a summit and looks back on his 
life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 12:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Jailed for Extra 19 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- For 19 years, a convicted killer told prison  
officials, prosecutors and a string of court-appointed attorneys 
that he had done his time and was no longer supposed to be locked 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a deal with prosecutors, he kept telling them.  
</P>
<P>
	But it was not until this summer that anyone could find the  
paperwork. 
</P>
<P>
	David Marshall Brown, 54, was finally released last week.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised that he had no anger. His feeling is that he  
knows there had been a mistake made and he wanted to get out of 
prison,'' said one of Brown's current attorneys, Sharon Meisler. 
</P>
<P>
	During the years he languished behind bars, Brown described in  
detail a 1965 plea agreement in which he was supposed to be 
released by 1980. But no one could find the seven-page deal, and 
his original lawyer was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Meisler, who works in the public defender's office and was  
hired to research Brown's case in March, found the lost paperwork 
in July -- misfiled in a folder for one of his co-defendants, who 
was freed in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like what happened is the boys' (files) got separated  
into different boxes and the memo goes into a box that does not 
belong to David Brown. And nobody checks,'' Ms. Meisler said. 
``This was before the days of copy machines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor who agreed to the deal in 1965, Richard S. Lowe,  
who is now a judge, said he does not recall the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown declined to be interviewed. He has no family in the area  
but is staying with friends and looking for a manual labor job, Ms. 
Meisler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant District Attorney Mary Ann Killinger said her office  
has not opposed Brown's release since the 1970s, but she did not 
know why he remained in prison. The state parole board was unable 
to find a file on him. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no plans for a lawsuit against the state, according to  
Brown's current court-appointed attorney, Dominick Centrella. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear whether he could sue anyway, said University of  
Pennsylvania law professor Edward Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a very hard thing to file suit about, that someone  
should have found something that was misfiled,'' Rubin said. 
``There's a natural instinct that there ought to be some remedy in 
a situation like this. The real tragedy is that no one can give him 
his life back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was 19 when he was arrested with two other Warminster men  
-- Michael McCaffrey and Daniel O'Neill -- for the murder of Eugene 
T. Jordan, the 62-year-old owner of a delicatessen. Brown, who was 
armed with a police nightstick, was charged with accompanying 
O'Neill, the shooter, into the deli. McCaffrey drove the getaway 
car. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown and McCaffrey pleaded guilty to murder and robbery and got  
life sentences in a deal that stipulated that prosecutors would not 
oppose parole after 15 years. McCaffrey was released more than two 
decades ago. O'Neill remains in prison serving a life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown earned a high school equivalency degree in prison and has  
about half the credits necessary for a college degree. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, he was allowed to work outside prison in various  
programs, including one in which he described what it was like to 
be behind bars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Hits 31-Month High  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures soared past the $23-a-barrel mark Thursday for  
the first time since early 1997 on the New York Mercantile Exchange 
after reports showed inventories had sunk lower than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of other energy products also rose sharply. In other  
markets, palladium rose to a five-month high, helped by the 
dollar's fall against the yen, and pork futures fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for October delivery rose 67 cents to $23.33 a barrel,  
the highest since February 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3 percent jump was in response to a pair of reports which  
showed U.S. inventories at their lowest level since January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute said late Wednesday that crude  
oil stockpiles had fallen by nearly 6 million barrels last week -- a 
decline about twice the size analysts had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	In similar findings Thursday that helped spur the rally, the  
U.S. Department of Energy reported a 4.5 million barrel decline in 
crude stockpiles and a 2 million barrel drop in gasoline stockpiles 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The world oil glut that sent crude prices spiraling to a record  
low of $10.35 a barrel last December has shrunk rapidly in response 
to production cutbacks by the Organization of the Petroleum Export 
Countries and a rebounding Asian economy that has spurred demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``This data just fuels the concern about the mid- to long-term  
scenario,'' said Tim Evans, senior energy analyst for the Pegasus 
Econometric Group in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still an expectation that OPEC will make no change in  
production at its September meeting in Vienna,'' he said. ``And 
that is going to leave the market with a supply-demand deficit 
during the fourth and first quarters, when crude demand is 
strongest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil, meanwhile, jumped to its highest level since Oct.  
6, 1997. October heating oil rose 1.56 cents to 61.08 cents a 
gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	October regular gasoline rose 1.70 cents to 68.40 cents a  
gallon; October natural gas rose 2.39 cents to $2.851 per 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in  
October rose 77 cents to $23.04 a barrel at the International 
Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures rose nearly 3 percent based on the yen's climb  
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Since metals are dollar-based commodities, a rise in its value  
encourages selling to lock in profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium rose $9 to $361.85 an ounce on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures' slide on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange was due  
mostly to technical selling on a market with abundant supplies, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	October lean hogs fell 2 cents to 43.30 cents a pound; February  
frozen pork bellies fell 1.20 cents to 53.10 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
