<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKenzie's Start Streak May End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Barring something unforeseen, veteran  
offensive lineman Raleigh McKenzie will begin Sunday's game on 
unfamiliar territory: the sideline. 
</P>
<P>
	McKenzie has started 126 straight games as a lineman for three  
teams, none of them the Packers. Green Bay signed him in the 
offseason, and he was penciled in as the starting left guard during 
minicamps. 
</P>
<P>
	But after an indifferent preseason by the entire line,  
second-year pro Mike Wahle beat out McKenzie for the position last 
week. The Packers plan to use McKenzie as a backup to Wahle and 
right guard Marco Rivera, but he will almost certainly miss his 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	McKenzie, a 14-year veteran, isn't worried about it.  
</P>
<P>
	``That kind of thing is just about being in the right place at  
the right time,'' he said. ``It doesn't mean you've got something 
special. All streaks come to an end anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 36, McKenzie is the oldest player on the Packers' roster. He  
spent the last two seasons in San Diego, where he landed after a 
two-year stint in Philadelphia under current Green Bay coach Ray 
Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	His streak began in 1991, when he helped the Washington Redskins  
win the Super Bowl with his play at right guard. He has played all 
five offensive line positions during his career, and his 
versatility was a primary reason the Packers signed him. 
</P>
<P>
	For McKenzie, the move to Green Bay was a chance to reunite with  
twin brother Reggie, a former NFL linebacker in his third season as 
the Packers' director of pro personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just happy to be with a good team that wants me and where  
I can contribute,'' he said. ``I'm getting to the end here, so I'd 
like one more Super Bowl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers' offensive line was a weak link during exhibition  
play. Miami's pass-rushers pressured quarterbacks Brett Favre and 
Matt Hasselbeck relentlessly, and Green Bay never established a 
consistent running game. 
</P>
<P>
	Wahle, who didn't look sharp against Miami, will be pressured by  
guard Joe Andruzzi, who has been out with a ligament tear in his 
knee. Andruzzi, who was on his way to a starting spot before the 
injury last month, has practiced this week and is probable for 
Sunday's game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
