<HEADLINE> Reebok To Cut More Than 600 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOUGHTON, Mass. (AP) -- Reebok International Ltd. on Thursday  
said it plans to lay off 10 percent of its 6,600 workers worldwide 
in an attempt to cut costs and restructure its business. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the reductions, 120 jobs will be cut at the company's  
headquarters in Massachusetts. Other details about the locations 
and amount of job cuts will be announced over the next few weeks, 
company spokeswoman Nancy Moss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a close competitor to Nike, Reebok has been fighting  
falling sneaker sales and losing market share to Adidas and New 
Balance Athletic Shoe Inc. of Boston. Reebok's U.S. market share 
has fallen from more than 21 percent in 1995 to 14 percent last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Reebok has been troubled by marketing problems such as an  
inability to maintain a brand message that leaves consumers with a 
clear Reebok identity, industry observers said. 



  	   	
