<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Masscare Rumors Sweep East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATAMBUA, Indonesia (AP) -- Allegations of widespread killings in  
East Timor's turmoil are sweeping fast-growing border refugee 
camps, where an estimated 50,000 people now shelter under the gaze 
of militiaman accused of creating the mayhem. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the frightened refugees said they were forcibly sent  
across the border to camps controlled by the same army and militias 
spreading terror at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The tens of thousands who huddled under blue and orange plastic  
tarpaulins in one camp near Atambua, 10 miles west of the border, 
swapped horror stories, but reports of large-scale slayings were 
impossible to confirm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw some dead. But I don't know how many or who killed them.  
I just tried to get out as quickly as possible,'' said Jesus da 
Costa, a taxi driver who fled Dili Tuesday at the height of the 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor plummeted into lawlessness after Saturday's  
announcement that an overwhelming majority of voters approved 
independence. Militias opposed to independence turned wild and 
violent, forcing thousands to flee to West Timor, the half of the 
island that has been anchored in Indonesia since it gained 
independence from the Netherlands in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, thousands more were arriving any way they could --  
usually hungry, tired and dirty. Supplies of food and water were 
running low in the camps, and many feared overcrowding and 
sanitation problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Some hitched rides on military vehicles. Others were so  
desperate they took empty garbage trucks from Dili, about 120 miles 
to the east. 
</P>
<P>
	They clutched their meager possessions -- furniture,  
refrigerators, television sets and even dismantled satellite 
dishes. Some displaced farmers took their goats, chickens and pigs. 
</P>
<P>
	Several people in the camps described to reporters how they  
witnessed slayings by the militias. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw dozens of people shot,'' said one man who said he  
witnessed the storming by militiamen of the Dili house of Roman 
Catholic Bishop Carlos Belo last Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Militia men wearing black shirts and masked stabbed a young  
man right in front of me. He bled to death,'' said the man, who 
spoke on condition of anonymity because he fears retribution. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations, which planned to withdraw most of its staff  
on Friday, has been unable to monitor the scale of the violence. 
Militias have threatened to kill foreign journalists and observers 
who try to get to refugee camps or enter East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vatican's missionary news service FIDES cited local church  
sources as saying three priests were slain in a grenade attack on a 
parish in the town of Suai on Monday. One hundred people were 
reportedly killed in the attack. Priests and nuns were reported 
killed in other attacks around East Timor, a predominantly Roman 
Catholic province in mostly Muslim Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian government has denied massacres are taking place  
and says the situation will stabilize when martial law takes hold 
under a new general. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some rogue elements have been noted, among them, rogue army  
elements,'' Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said Thursday. ``Also 
perhaps some East Timorese who have been part of the Indonesian 
army.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, many militia members made their way to the border and  
-- after being accused of perpetrating weeks of terror before and 
after Saturday's vote -- were supervising and guarding the camps 
along with the Indonesian military. 
</P>
<P>
	The wives of some militia members still in East Timor said they  
feared for the lives of their husbands and rejected claims of 
atrocities against innocent civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ready to be widows. Our militia husbands are fighting  
so that East Timor will stay part of Indonesia,'' said Hermandinda 
Bobu, 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Police estimated the collective size of the camps, as well  
numbers of refugees in schools, homes and churches, at about 
50,000. Humanitarian groups have estimated that up to 200,000 
people -- a quarter of East Timor's population -- might be homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who have made it across the border were unsure of their  
future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm worried. My two sons are missing,'' said Katarina Borse,  
30. ``I'm too tired to cry now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
