<DOCNO> APW19990909.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 13:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brees-Jackson Duel Highlights Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- When Drew Brees takes the snap, it's  
well known what he's going to do. With Jarious Jackson, it's 
uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no secret that Brees will try to outgun the 16th-ranked  
Irish (1-1) Saturday with his magnificent arm. How Jackson attacks 
No. 20 Purdue (1-0) is a mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	``They present a number of problems in the sense that they run  
option football, as well as power football, as well as spread 
football,'' Purdue coach Joe Tiller said. ``You can't afford to be 
one-dimensional defensively when you're setting your plan against 
them. You have to be ready for everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, playing behind an inexperienced offensive line and in  
front of young tailbacks, carries the brunt of the Irish offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, that wouldn't be such a bad thing. He ranked 13th  
nationally last season in passing efficiency and was intercepted 
only six times while guiding Notre Dame to a 9-2 record. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, he has been erratic. Against Michigan, he threw for  
a career-best 302 yards but also had five errant option pitches, 
fumbled as he was sacked near the Wolverines' goal line and was 
sacked four times. He's also thrown four interceptions already. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame's offense has stumbled right along with him,  
committing seven turnovers after having 13 in all of 1997 and 18 
last year. To make matters worse, Jackson missed several practices 
this week with a turf toe injury but that isn't expected to keep 
him out of Saturday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to eliminate the sloppiness,'' Irish coach Bob Davie  
said. ``We cannot pitch the ball on the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brees, however, seems to have continued his success from last  
season. He threw for 273 yards against Central Florida last week, 
completing 26-of-43 for four touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his progress, Brees has been working to force fewer  
passes, like the two interceptions he threw last year when Notre 
Dame beat Purdue 31-30. The first set up the winning field goal 
with less than a minute to play after Brees threw wildly across the 
middle rather than take a sack. The second ended Purdue's final 
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Brees likes what he sees of Notre Dame's secondary, which has  
been prone to give up big gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they try to disguise anything,'' Brees said.  
``If they're going to blitz, they show you they're going to blitz. 
They've got such good players, such great athletes, they're good 
enough to let you know what's there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of what defense the Irish use, they know the only way  
to beat Purdue is to keep Brees off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	To do that, the Irish will have to mount a consistent, sustained  
offensive attack, something they have yet to do. While they rushed 
for 363 yards against Kansas and Jackson threw for 302 against 
Michigan, large chunks of both totals came on big plays, rather 
than the grind-it-out style Notre Dame thrives on. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to control the football to try to keep them off the  
field with their offense,'' Davie said. ``But they are such a 
quick-strike offense that they are going to score, so you can't 
just button it up and say you are going to just run the football. 
You are going to have to create some plays to score.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 06:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jollibee Foods May Buy ChowKing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Philippine's food giant Jollibee  
Foods Corp. said Thursday it is interested in acquiring full 
ownership of ChowKing Food Corp., the nation's largest Chinese 
fast-food chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Jollibee, which owns and operates the largest hamburger chain in  
the Philippines, said it wants to acquire ChowKing if majority 
owners accept its terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Buying ChowKing would expand Jollibee's revenue base and enhance  
its dominance in the Philippine fast-food market. 
</P>
<P>
	The family of Jollibee Chairman Tony Tan Caktiong, who owns half  
of ChowKing, is urging a group led by ChowKing President Robert 
Kuan, the chain's other major shareholder, to approve a buyout, the 
national Philippine Daily Inquirer reported. 
</P>
<P>
	No timetable was set for completing the deal, Jollibee said in a  
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale needs the approval of the Securities and Exchange  
Commission. 
  	   	
</P>
