<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defendants Innocent in Fur Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Three men were found innocent Thursday of  
charges they plotted to bomb a fur farm that sustained more than $1 
million in damages in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Bishop, 25, of Ithaca, N.Y., and Sean Gautschy, 23, of  
Salt Lake City, were found innocent of charges stemming from the 
bombing of the Fur Breeder's Cooperative on March 11, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam Troy Peace, 21, of Huntington Beach, Calif., was found  
innocent of two counts from an earlier attempt to the bomb the 
farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The case hinged on the credibility of testimony given by  
prosecution witness, Douglas Joshua Ellerman, 21, who was sentenced 
to seven years after offering information that led to the current 
indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellerman testified that he, Gautschy, Bishop and Alexander Slack  
-- who committed suicide in June -- broke into the co-op, planted 
five bombs and lit two fires. He also said Peace took part in an 
earlier aborted attempt to bomb the same facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop's lawyer, Fred Metos, argued that Ellerman and his  
brother gave several inconsistent statements while testifying, 
including conflicting accounts of who bought the bomb-making 
materials. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants were all reportedly members of the ``Straight  
Edge'' movement, whose members swear off drugs, alcohol, tobacco 
and casual sex. Some members also support animal liberation causes. 
</P>
<P>
	The cooperative is one of the country's largest and provides  
mink to hundreds of farmers in the West. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
