<HEADLINE> Mom Won't Go To Jail for Negligence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A woman whose infant son starved to death, in  
part because her surgically reduced breasts failed to supply enough 
milk, was sentenced Wednesday to probation rather than jail time. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabitha Walrond, 21, could have gotten four years in prison for  
criminally negligent homicide in the death of 2-month-old Tyler, 
although prosecutors asked for a six-month sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Judge Robert Straus gave Ms. Walrond five years'  
probation, saying he didn't believe ``incarceration would serve the 
public interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond was ordered to undergo counseling and must either  
hold a job or attend school during the probationary period. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond claimed she did not realize her reduced breasts were  
leaving the baby malnourished, and her lawyer said she was turned 
away when she tried to take him to a clinic because he did not have 
a Medicaid card. 
</P>
<P>
	The baby's paternal grandmother, Marsha Purrell, spoke at the  
sentencing, holding up photos of the baby as a healthy 8-pound 
newborn and as an emaciated 5-pound corpse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tabitha, how could my beautiful grandson change from this to  
that?'' she asked. ``How could your mother -- especially your mother 
and her family -- allow this to happen?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond also faces sentencing on an unrelated charge of  
marijuana possession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
