<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 10:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Fall by 4,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment benefits  
unexpectedly declined last week, good news for job seekers but a 
sign of potential trouble to economists who worry about inflation 
down the road. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 286,000 Americans filed new claims for jobless  
benefits for the week that ended Saturday, a drop of 4,000 from the 
previous week, the Labor Department said Thursday. That was the 
lowest level since Aug. 21, when claims were at 285,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists had been expecting that new claims would  
actually rise a little to 290,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for claims, which smoothes out  
week-to-week volatility, rose by just 750 to 287,500 last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists consider jobless claims levels below 300,000 an  
indication of an extremely tight labor market. In August, the 
nation's unemployment rate inched down to 4.2 percent, returning to 
a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	That is good for workers but worrisome to economists. They fear  
employers scrambling for workers will offer higher wages and 
benefits, which could drive up prices and trigger inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	That has not happened so far. Although growth in productivity --  
the amount of output for each hour worked -- slowed in the spring, 
it is one of the forces helping to keep inflation low. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the government last week said hourly earnings for workers  
rose slightly in August. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the government will release a report on inflation at  
the wholesale level; many economists are expecting a slight rise to 
0.3 percent, reflecting higher energy and food prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The decrease in new jobless claims ``certainly sound great for  
Mr. and Mrs. Public but unfortunately it's not going to be too 
great for the Federal Reserve -- at least the more hawkish members 
of the Fed,'' said economist Richard Yamarone with Argus Research 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't bode well for Fed members who are worried that wage  
inflation is going to spark soon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed on Aug. 24 bumped up interest rates for the second time  
this year but signaled that no additional increases may be 
necessary unless the economy shows signs of overheating or if 
inflation flares. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets have been worried about the prospects of the  
Fed raising interest rates again this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech Thursday, Federal Reserve board member Roger  
Ferguson Jr., who has been nominated to be vice chairman of the 
Federal Reserve, did not address the prospects of another rate 
increase. He did mention the policy challenges of keeping inflation 
low. 
</P>
<P>
	``To paraphrase, Chairman (Alan) Greenspan, the economy works  
best when inflation is so low that businesses and households do not 
have to take it into account when making everyday decisions,'' 
according to the prepared text of Ferguson's speech at the National 
Economists Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the short run, however, difficult choices may be required  
about the timing and magnitude of policy actions consistent with 
achieving price stability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One approach to such difficult choices, he said, is to ``mandate  
a quantitative inflation target for the central bank, or to have 
the central bank select an inflation target that it must endeavor 
to achieve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the Labor Department said that for the week  
ending Aug. 28, 33 states and territories reported decreases in new 
jobless claim applications, while 20 reported increases. The state 
data lag a week behind the national figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest decrease was California, down 1,990.  
Officials attributed the decline to fewer layoffs in the trade and 
service industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states with big decreases were: Georgia, down 1,756; South  
Carolina, down 1,750; Tennessee, down 1,348; and Michigan, down 
783. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest increase in jobless benefits claims  
was New York, up 1,216. State officials did not offer an 
explanation for the increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states and territories with increases were: Kentucky, up  
674; Illinois, up 661; Puerto Rico, up 632; and Virginia, up 481. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
