<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Family To Sell Ranch to Govt. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- Environmentalists are applauding the  
federal government's plan to purchase a 95,000-acre cattle ranch 
described as a ``scientific treasure'' and manage it as public 
land. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservation groups had lobbied for federal acquisition of the  
scenic Baca Ranch to preserve open space in northern New Mexico. 
They got their wish Wednesday when a Texas family agreed to sell 
the ranch, home to one of the nation's largest elk herds, for $101 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was hailed by The Wilderness Society, which  
called the ranch ``a scientific treasure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This place deserves to be added to the federal public land  
system for the American people,'' said Pamela Pride Eaton, 
Denver-based regional director of the group. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, reached after two years of negotiations, still needs  
congressional approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we are still a long way from the day when people can  
hike and fish up there, I can say in all honesty that we have never 
been this close to a deal,'' said Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, the land would be sold to the Forest  
Service and managed as the Valles Caldera National Preserve by nine 
trustees appointed by the president. It would continue to be 
operated as a cattle ranch while also providing recreational 
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranch is owned by the heirs of oil man James P. Dunigan, who  
died in 1980. It was a land grant in 1860 to the heirs of a Spanish 
leader, and the property remained mostly intact as it passed 
through three owners before the Dunigans bought it in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	They paid $2.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The heirs have said they wanted to be sure the property was  
never developed. The forests on the ranch had been extensively 
logged before the Dunigans bought it, but a new growth of trees 
masks most of the scars of clear-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	Situated in the Jemez Mountains, the area features mountain  
towers, grassy meadows, trout streams and six valleys that include 
the Valle Grande, which stretches nearly six miles wide. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranch contains the Valles Caldera, the collapsed crater of  
an ancient volcano that has been closed to the public since 1860. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildlife abounds on the property, including bear, mountain lion,  
bald eagles and golden eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	About 60 miles northwest of Santa Fe, the ranch is surrounded by  
publicly owned lands in the Santa Fe National Forest and Bandelier 
National Monument. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
