<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shutdown Ordered at Ky. DOE Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PADUCAH, Ky. (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has ordered  
a one-day shutdown of a U.S. Department of Energy cleanup site in 
Paducah to check safety procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	The order issued Wednesday is believed to be the first ever for  
a plant owned by the agency, which runs nuclear facilities 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``safety stand down'' ordered for today followed the  
completion last week of an initial visit to the site at the Paducah 
Gaseous Diffusion Plant by the agency's environment, safety and 
health team. 
</P>
<P>
	The team didn't uncover any imminent hazards to the plant's  
workers or the general public but found some room for improvement 
in radiological protection and plant operations, the DOE said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been security-related stand-downs, but this is the  
first for safety,'' said Steven Wyatt, a spokesman for the Paducah 
plant. 
</P>
<P>
	All operations, except for emergency-related activities, will be  
suspended while employees and managers of the agency and of Bechtel 
Jacobs, the contractor hired by the DOE to clean up the site, 
review safety procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension of DOE activities at the plant won't directly  
affect operations of U.S. Enrichment Corp., which uses the plant to 
enrich uranium for use as fuel in nuclear reactors. 
</P>
<P>
	The DOE investigation follows allegations that workers were  
unknowingly exposed to plutonium for many years. Plutonium has been 
linked to leukemia and other forms of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has said that 100,000 tons of spent  
nuclear fuel recycled at the plant from 1953 to about 1975 
contained trace amounts of plutonium. The state has said traces of 
plutonium found near the plant were in similar, insignificant 
amounts and posed no significant public risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The order drew fire Wednesday from Kentucky's two senators, Jim  
Bunning and Mitch McConnell. 
</P>
<P>
	``This looks like a classic case of locking the barn door after  
the horses have been stolen,'' the Republicans said in a joint 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we are glad that the Department of Energy has taken this  
preliminary step to address and improve safety standards at the 
Paducah plant, we have serious concerns about how the DOE has 
handled this matter so far,'' they said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
