<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Tries To Iron Out Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Top Pacific Rim officials met  
Thursday but came up with no quick answers for two pressing issues: 
What to ask for in the next big round of global trade talks and how 
to admit China to the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade officials at the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit  
hope to reach agreement on proposals for cutting numerous tariffs 
charged on industrial goods, in some cases to zero, a move they 
believe would create more trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met with  
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan but came up with no formula 
for getting China into the World Trade Organization, the 
Geneva-based body that governs most global trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're pursuing negotiations this week but there was no  
breakthrough on it one way or another,'' said a senior U.S. 
administration official, speaking to reporters early Thursday on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright and Tang spent much of their 90-minute session working  
toward talks Saturday between President Clinton and Chinese 
President Jiang Zemin, the U.S. administration official said. 
</P>
<P>
	APEC trade ministers have reached consensus on parts of their  
wish list to present to the WTO at major global trade talks 
beginning Nov. 30 in Seattle, but they still faced many unresolved 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand Trade Minister Lockwood Smith told reporters the  
ministers were still trying to work out a final report for their 
leaders. He declined to elaborate on the sticking points, and other 
delegations had nothing to say to journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	The APEC ministers are discussing topics ranging from forestry  
to finance. They hope, for example, to agree on proposals for 
reforming financial markets -- a topic that has resonated in the 
region since the Asian economic meltdown that began in July 1997 
and exposed many economic problems that had festered for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations about any broad trade agreements have been played  
down at the APEC summit that ends Monday, with much attention 
focused on the deteriorating political situation in East Timor, 
where Indonesia has declared martial law amid chaos that followed a 
recent independence vote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
