<DOCNO> APW19990909.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 05:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Rim Trade Officials At Odds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Halfway through their negotiations,  
senior Pacific Rim trade officials failed today to find common 
ground on a strategy for the next round of global trade talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade ministers made progress in the first of two days of talks  
on reducing agricultural subsidies and devised a plan for letting 
China and Taiwan take part in the next World Trade Organization 
negotiations -- even if they have yet to formally joined the global 
trade body. 
</P>
<P>
	On the sidelines of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum,  
U.S. trade negotiator Charlene Barshefsky and Chinese trade 
minister Shi Guangsheng discussed China's entry to WTO, trying to 
restart talks Beijing suspended in May after the bombing of its 
embassy in Belgrade by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ministers did not resolve what recommendations they will  
make to WTO for new trade talks, due to open in the United States 
in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Their difficulties followed two days of inconclusive talks by  
lower-level officials and put in question whether this year's APEC 
conclave would meet its key goal: devising a strong, common WTO 
strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	While once focused on liberalizing markets within the group,  
APEC has in recent years acted as a lobbying bloc within the 
134-member WTO. APEC members carry weight, accounting for 45 
percent of the world's trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Violence in East Timor, where pro-Indonesian militants have  
rampaged against supporters of independence, has drawn attention 
away from APEC's free-trade agenda this year. Officials attended a 
separate meeting today to urge Indonesia to end the violence or 
seek foreign help. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade ministers still have negotiations Friday to come up with a  
solution, before leaders of the 21 governments in APEC are to 
endorse a statement at a weekend summit. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand Trade Minister Lockwood Smith expressed optimism a  
compromise could be found. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident that we'll be able to achieve significant  
progress,'' Smith told reporters after the first day's session. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade ministers were trying to reach a compromise between  
two broad approaches to the new WTO talks, Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	One would be to have countries make specific early commitments  
to open markets, or parts of them. The other, known to negotiators 
as ``a single undertaking,'' would have countries open markets 
comprehensively at the conclusion of the WTO talks, due to last 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	APEC ministers are discussing trade issues ranging from forestry  
to finance and are considering cutting numerous tariffs on 
industrial goods, in some cases to zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said APEC members also seemed ready to recommend  
abolishing export subsidies and some non-tariff barriers for 
agricultural goods. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 00:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Alternative Schools Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A growing number of parents are taking  
advantage of educational alternatives such as charter schools 
despite little proof that they boost student performance, a new 
study shows. 
</P>
<P>
	About one in four U.S. schoolchildren attend schools other than  
neighborhood public schools, researchers at the Policy Analysis for 
California Education said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But while school choice is on the rise, there is surprisingly  
little evidence that it improves student achievement, the 
researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The jury is still out,'' concluded the study by PACE, based at  
Stanford and the University of California at Berkeley. 
</P>
<P>
	Private school enrollment has remained at about 10 percent for  
years. But with newer options of charter schools, magnet schools, 
open enrollment and voucher programs, the alternatives -- including 
private schools -- are attracting an increasing percentage, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	School choice advocates say the real measure of achievement is  
the happiness of parents who have taken their children out of 
failing neighborhood public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``Choice is really popular out there among parents, particularly  
among minority, low-income parents in districts that are not doing 
a good job,'' said Terry Moe, a political science professor at 
Stanford whose book, ``Politics, Markets and America's Schools,'' 
has been influential in the school choice movement. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the think tank's report ``unduly negative.''  
</P>
<P>
	``There is every reason to be very positive and optimistic about  
the effects of competition on public schools and on children,'' Moe 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as school choice expands, a rising number of public  
districts are relying on a private school tactic -- advertising -- to 
lure pupils and the reimbursement money they bring from their home 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
	Private schools, of course, have long advertised, and  
privately-run public charter schools often do so. But, until school 
choice in the 1990s, there was no reason for public schools to 
advertise for students. 
</P>
<P>
	Public districts that advertise say it's just a logical  
extension of word-of-mouth promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gateway education system in Huntington, Mass., began  
advertising this year in daily and weekly newspapers in Berkshire 
County and Springfield. An ad in Wednesday's Berkshire Eagle 
announced 83 places were still open for students at five schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we promote here is a rural environment, small class size,  
a safe and nurturing environment,'' said Superintendent Don 
Nicoletti. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 21:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ABIQUIU, N.M. (AP) -- On a plateau across the Rio Chama from this  
250-year-old Hispanic village, the stillness of the afternoon is 
pierced by a man's chanting voice. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the call to prayer heard five times a day by hundreds of  
millions the world over, the signal for Muslims to drop what they 
are doing and turn their attention to God. 
</P>
<P>
	In this pocket of rural northern New Mexico, it draws a small  
group of worshipers from the blindingly bright sunshine into the 
cool darkness of a domed-roof, adobe mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	They slip off their shoes, splash water on their hands, feet and  
faces in a tiled anteroom, then enter the main mosque. Facing east, 
toward Mecca, they pray: ``Praise be to Allah, Creator of the 
worlds ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	An increasing number of the world's religions have become part  
of the fabric of faith in largely Roman Catholic New Mexico. 
Besides Islamic mosques, there are Sikh gurdwaras and Buddhist 
stupas. And the state is not alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The religious landscape of the United States is changing  
rapidly, with temples and mosques going up from coast to coast, 
said E. Allen Richardson, author of ``Strangers in This Land: 
Pluralism and the Response to Diversity in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just in the major metropolitan areas. It's every  
place,'' said Richardson, an expert on Hinduism who teaches Eastern 
religions at Cedar Crest College in Allentown, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Mainstream religions of the Eastern Hemisphere -- including  
Islam, often called the fastest-growing religion in the United 
States -- have become American religions, fueled by immigration over 
the past three decades, Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mosque near Abiquiu is part of Dar al Islam, an organization  
with a two-fold mission: to educate non-Muslims about Islam, and to 
bring Muslims together. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded 20 years ago, Dar al Islam built the North African-style  
mosque and attached madressa, or school, with the dream of starting 
a model village -- a showcase for Islam in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Anchored by a school that operated for six years in the 1980s, a  
small community of Muslim families grew at the site. But the dream 
of a self-sustaining village in rural, poor, northern New Mexico 
proved elusive. 
</P>
<P>
	The handful of Muslims who remained by 1989 turned the Abiquiu  
complex into a site for summer programs -- part of a nationwide 
outreach that includes workshops, conferences and training 
sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Dar al Islam sponsors intensive religious retreats aimed  
particularly at young Muslims, to teach them about traditional 
Islam, spokesman Hakim Archuletta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Muslims in America, he said, have learned a distorted  
version of Islam. Traditional Islam is ``very universal, very 
tolerant ... not this other thing that you're seeing out there in 
the news -- politically oriented, fundamentalist, mean Islam,'' 
Archuletta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Abiquiu is also a site for residential programs for non-Muslim  
teachers from public and private secondary schools, who get a 
grounding in the faith and world view of Islam. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe how much I've learned in two weeks,'' said  
Renee Townley, a social studies teacher from suburban Cincinnati 
who joined 19 other teachers at an August session. ``I knew very 
little about Islam and Muslim life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A community of Sikhs, distinctive in their turbans and white  
clothing, has become a fixture in northern New Mexico since it was 
founded nearly 30 years ago. Sikhism is a monotheistic religion 
founded by a Hindu teacher in the 15th century. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sikhs begin their day before 4 a.m., with 2 1/2 hours of  
prayer, yoga and meditation in the gold-domed gurdwara, or temple, 
on the outskirts of Espanola. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sikhs run a variety of thriving businesses -- a nationwide  
security firm, companies that distribute tea, cereals and herbal 
products, and computer and other consulting services. 
</P>
<P>
	The community of about 325 has become a political force in the  
state, contributing to both major parties. The annual birthday 
party for Yogi Bhajan, their spiritual and administrative leader, 
draws the governor and local congressmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here, and we're here long-term. We befriend everybody  
... political leaders as well as ecumenical leaders, business 
leaders,'' said spokeswoman Mukta Kaur Khalsa. 
</P>
<P>
	Sikhs are vegetarians and use no alcohol, drugs or cigarettes,  
and they teach Kundalini Yoga in local communities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buddhist community in New Mexico includes immigrants from  
China, Laos, Vietnam, Thailand and Tibet, as well as Westerners. 
Some attend services led by monks at Albuquerque temples. Some sit 
in meditation at adobe Zen centers in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	In Santa Fe, on a busy commercial and residential thoroughfare,  
the spire of a stupa rises from a small oasis of grass and gardens 
strung with fluttering prayer flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Built in the mid 1980s by followers of Tibetan Buddhism, it's  
the site of public meditations several times a week. There is a 
resident lama, or teacher, and a bookstore. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the local Tibetan refugee community, about 100  
people, go to the stupa on special occasions, but usually gather in 
private homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to establish a Tibetan cultural center for the  
community, where the young people can learn about Buddhism,'' said 
spokesman Pema Rabgay. 
</P>
<P>
	That is a common attitude within the nation's growing religious  
minorities, said Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of these faiths are here to stay. ... In the next century,  
we're going to be a very different people than we've been, 
religiously,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
