<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Metals Producers Reject Phelps' Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Merger partners Cyprus Amax Minerals Co. and  
Asarco Inc. said Thursday their boards of directors have rejected a 
$2.7 billion all-stock offer by Phelps Dodge Corp. to acquire both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of both metals producers also urged their  
shareholders to reject the offer from Phelps, a Phoenix-based 
mining company, and to approve the planned merger between Cyprus 
Amax and Asarco. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Amax, based in Englewood, Colo., and New York-based  
Asarco are two of the world's leading copper and metals producers. 
They agreed in July to merge and form the nation's largest copper 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders are expected to vote on the merger Sept. 30.  
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge spokeswoman Sue Suvers said Thursday's announcement  
would not deter efforts to sell shareholders on the Phelps 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Milton H. Ward, chairman and chief and executive of Cyprus Amax,  
and Francis R. McAllister, chairman and CEO of Asarco, said in a 
joint statement that they rejected the offer from Phelps because it 
would not give their shareholders a fair ownership interest and it 
could raise antitrust issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is absolutely clear from Phelps Dodge's actions over the  
course of the last few weeks that it is trying to coerce Cyprus 
Amax and Asarco shareholders into a situation that is not in their 
best interests,'' they said in the statement. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
