<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casino Compromise Near in Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Indian tribes and California Gov. Gray  
Davis drew closer Thursday to an agreement that would keep Indian 
casinos open, with many tribes ready to give in to the governor on 
union rights for casino workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal leaders, under the gun to reach an agreement before the  
Legislature's 1999 session ends Friday, said Thursday that many 
tribes would agree to unionizing rights for casino workers despite 
concerns it would infringe on their sovereignty. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizing rights was one of the remaining hurdles for  
negotiators. Davis and labor-supportive lawmakers had insisted that 
any agreement between tribes and the state include such 
protections. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Macarro, tribal chairman of the Pechanga band in Temecula,  
said tribes may not favor mandatory union rights, but ``those who 
favor the compact have a reluctant acceptance about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tribes were forced to the bargaining table when the state  
Supreme Court recently overturned a 1998 voter-approved measure 
allowing a major expansion of Indian casinos. The court ruled that 
the measure allowed Nevada-style gambling banned by the state 
constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	As the governor and tribal leaders worked on the compact  
Thursday night, legislators were working on a proposed ballot 
measure that would let voters change the state Constitution to give 
tribes a monopoly on slots and Nevada-style blackjack games. 
</P>
<P>
	But before legislators approve the ballot measure, they and the  
Davis administration want the compact signed. A signed compact 
would let the casinos continue operating until the measure goes to 
voters in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Thursday the tribes sent Davis a proposed compact close to  
one he proposed. Both included a plan for limiting the number of 
slot machines, something many of the tribes had considered a 
roadblock. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis proposed a limit of 42,000 slot machines. The tribes'  
proposal set the bar at 43,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In both proposals, a coordinator for all the tribes would  
oversee the slot allocations and the distribution of revenues 
generated by the slot acquisitions. The revenue-sharing would 
benefit all tribes, including those without casinos. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
