<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Esprit CEO Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The chairman and chief executive officer at  
clothing maker Esprit de Corp. has resigned, the company said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Margolis, who has been leading the company since 1996, will  
leave Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	At its peak in 1989, San Francisco-based Esprit had 80 stores  
and discount outlets around the country. Now it has only 20 stores 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Esprit has recently began targeting a slightly older customer --  
women aged 19 to 30 as opposed to preteens and teens -- by offering 
higher quality and slightly more expensive clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Esprit's new market niche is ``more contemporary than the Gap  
but less expensive than Banana Republic,'' said Margolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the initiative, Esprit has stabilized. Many attribute the  
success to Margolis' advertising and catalog design vision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity to take a brilliant brand and revive a segment  
of our industry was a great challenge,'' Margolis said. ``I have 
accomplished what I set out to achieve at Esprit and now it is time 
to move on to other pursuits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not say what those pursuits would be.  
</P>
<P>
	A replacement for Margolis has not been named.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
