<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Arrested for Burning Teen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORWALK, Calif. (AP) -- A man and his 15-year-old stepson are  
being held without bail in connection with the burning death of a 
teen-age girl. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy, whose identity was withheld, and 36-year-old Michael  
Crosby were arrested Wednesday at their Norwalk home, about 15 
miles southeast of Los Angeles, and booked for investigation of 
murder. 
</P>
<P>
	They could be arraigned as early as today, said Sgt. Norine  
Plett of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The identity of girl, believed to be between 13 and 17 years  
old, is unknown. She was apparently doused with a flammable liquid 
and set on fire outside a machine shop in nearby Whittier on July 
9. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors who reported hearing screams coming from the flames  
alerted authorities, and firefighters found her body in a heap of 
flaming shrubbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Plett said a neighbor of Crosby's led police to him. Crosby, who  
has a criminal record, initially was jailed Wednesday on a 
probation violation but was booked for investigation of murder 
following further investigation, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	No other details were released.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators had no motive for the killing and said Crosby and  
his stepson apparently had no relationship with the victim. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
