<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burtons Start 1st, 3rd at Autolite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Jeff and Ward Burton, the Virginia brothers  
who finished 1-2 in last week's Southern 500 at Darlington, will 
start bumper to bumper again in Friday night's Autolite Platinum 
250 NASCAR Busch Grand National Series race. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Burton, who led his brother across the finish line for the  
second time in the Winston Cup series last weekend, posted a fast 
lap of 121.984 mph to earn his first Busch Grand National pole of 
the season and seventh of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to tell a real good lap from a good lap. I'm pretty  
proud of this,'' Jeff Burton said. ``When we qualify well, that's 
unusual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Green, third in the driver standings, was second at 121.907  
mph on the three-quarter-mile oval, and Ward Burton was third at 
121.841 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew my first lap was good and I knew I had to get a good  
first lap in,'' Green said. ``Hopefully we can outrun those Cup 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Series points leader and defending race champion Dale Earnhardt  
Jr. qualified 20th at 120.714 mph, and second-place Matt Kenseth 
was 29th at 120.482. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to get into race trim and see what we've got,''  
said Earnhardt, who dominated this race a year ago, leading the 
last 154 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've struggled since we got here and I don't know what's  
really wrong,'' Kenseth said after his run. ``This probably won't 
get us in on the first day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With seven races left in the season, Kenseth trails Earnhardt by  
26 points and Green is another 190 back despite missing the second 
race of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Martin, the career leader with 39 BGN victories, qualified  
fourth at 121.764 mph, even after a first lap that he said 
``stunk.'' Todd Bodine will start fifth after touring Richmond 
International Raceway at 121.709 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is the career leader with five BGN victories at Richmond,  
and he's also won five of his 10 starts in the series this year, 
including last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Winston Cup regulars who attempted to qualify included  
Jimmy Spencer, who was seventh; Ken Schrader, who was 17th; and 
Kenny Wallace, who was 22nd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
