<HEADLINE> Chicago Firms Settle Piracy Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Smurfit-Stone Container Corp. has agreed to pay  
$350,000 to an alliance of software developers to settle piracy 
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The Business Software Alliance, a Washington-based watchdog  
group, said Thursday the claims were related to unlicensed copies 
of programs installed on computers that belonged to Stone Container 
Corp. before its recent merger with Jefferson Smurfit Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials did not immediately return telephone calls  
Thursday morning. But in a statement released by the Business 
Software Alliance, a Smurfit-Stone official said the firm was now 
in full compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Smurfit itself has always been careful to ensure that it owned  
an adequate number of licenses to support all of the software 
installed on its computers,'' Jim Hayssen, vice president of 
information technology for Smurfit-Stone, said in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Jefferson Smurfit Corp. merged with Stone Container Corp.  
last fall, we became aware of licensing deficiencies at many of its 
plants and offices spread throughout the country,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Business Software Alliance has collected about $40 million  
in fines from U.S. companies illegally pirating software over the 
past five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The unlicensed software at Stone Container was brought to the  
group's attention by a phone call to its anti-piracy hotline. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
