<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Heading Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is heading overseas for a  
week just as the GOP-controlled Congress resumes work with promises 
to confront him with their $792 billion tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's promise in return -- to veto the package as  
irresponsible -- probably will have to wait until he concludes a 
week of political and economic diplomacy in South Asia. He returns 
to Washington on Sept. 16 and likely will find the tax cut 
legislation on his desk. 
</P>
<P>
	All week, as Clinton prepared to leave for New Zealand, he  
worked criticism of the tax cut into speeches on education, welfare 
and crime. He contends the package would waste an expected budget 
surplus and force a return to deficit spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Answering a reporter's question on the subject Thursday, Clinton  
took a last shot before leaving the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``They know good and well I'm not going sign this bill. It's  
wrong for America. It's bad for the economy,'' he said. At the same 
time, Clinton said there is some room for negotiation. ``It's up to 
them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, he was off for Auckland and a meeting Saturday that  
the White House hopes will produce a trade breakthrough with China. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will meet with Chinese President Jiang Zemin on the eve  
of a summit of Pacific Rim leaders -- the two leaders' first meeting 
in 15 months. Since then, relations plummeted on allegations of 
Chinese spying and theft of U.S. nuclear secrets, the U.S. bombing 
of the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia and tensions between China and 
rival Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks aimed at allowing China's entry into the World Trade  
Organization stalled after NATO's bombing of the embassy on May 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the White House before his departure, Clinton said  
the United States has tried to mend fences since the ``terrible 
accident'' in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would very much like to resume the WTO negotiations. I think  
it would be good for China, good for the United States and good for 
the world economic system,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also applauded economic progress in Japan, which he called a  
boon for the world economy. ``They're doing better and I'm real 
pleased about it. I think the world should be pleased about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will meet jointly Sunday with Presidents Keizo Obuchi of  
Japan and Kim Dae-jung of South Korea, discussing North Korea's 
suspected preparations to test a long-range ballistic missile. 
Clinton also will meet with Russia's new prime minister, Vladimir 
Putin, on the heels of new allegations about Russian corruption and 
money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Sunday, Clinton will join leaders for the opening talks of  
the 21-member Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC). 
</P>
<P>
	After the conclusion of the APEC meeting, Clinton will fly to  
Queenstown on Tuesday for a day of rest. On Wednesday, the 
president will travel to Christchurch, a southern city that is the 
starting point for most American expeditions to the Antarctic. 
</P>
<P>
	He will speak at the Antarctica Center about efforts to protect  
the global environment. The president also will meet with New 
Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley and opposition leader Helen 
Clarke. He also is to attend a black-tie dinner given by Shipley 
before a late takeoff for home. En route to Washington, Clinton 
will stop in Hawaii again for refueling and a day of golf. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
