<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Student Pleads Guilty to Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ERIE, Pa. (AP) -- A 15-year-old boy pleaded guilty today to  
fatally shooting a teacher at a middle school graduation dance. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Wurst's plea to a third-degree murder charge spares the  
teen-ager the mandatory life sentence a first-degree murder 
conviction would have carried. Under Pennsylvania law, Wurst could 
not have been sentenced to death because he was younger than 16 
when science teacher John Gillette was shot and killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial had been scheduled to begin next month.  
</P>
<P>
	Gillette, 48, was killed in April 1998 at a James W. Parker  
Middle School graduation dance at a banquet hall in Edinboro. Two 
students were wounded. It was one of a series of school-related 
shootings that shocked the nation that spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The teen's lawyers had not disputed that he fired the shots, but  
said he was insane. The boy was 14 and in the eighth grade at the 
time of the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst has been held in the Erie County Jail since the shooting,  
except for a few weeks last fall when he was sent to a state 
hospital for a psychiatric evaluation. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-degree murder -- which state law defines as an  
unpremeditated killing with malice -- carries a maximum sentence of 
20 to 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst also pleaded guilty to attempted homicide and assault  
counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst would be eligible for a separate unit at a state prison  
for inmates younger than 18 who have been convicted as adults. That 
unit is part of the state prison at Houtzdale, in central 
Pennsylvania. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
