<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Area Off Limits to New Memorials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several federal commissions are calling for a  
ban on new memorials in a cross-shaped area stretching from the 
Capitol to the Lincoln Memorial and from the White House to the 
Jefferson Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed restricted area, called ``the Reserve,'' includes  
the central grassy region known as The Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Reserve is a unique national space, an embodiment of our  
democratic ideals and achievements, and must be preserved as an 
indispensable and nationally significant cultural resource,'' 
according to the proposal drafted by the staffs of the National 
Capital Planning Commission, the National Capital Memorial 
Commission and the Commission of Fine Arts. 
</P>
<P>
	To take effect, the proposal must be approved by the  
commissions' members, who are appointed by the president. Some have 
already endorsed the plan, including the Fine Arts Commission 
chairman, J. Carter Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban would exempt the proposed World War II Memorial, which  
would cross the Mall near the Lincoln Memorial. It has been 
approved by the commissions but not yet begun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitol's grounds are exempt from the proposed ban since  
Congress controls them. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's announcement opens a 60-day period when citizens may  
express their views before the commissions take final action. The 
first public meeting is scheduled for Sept. 29 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
