<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures were mixed early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors awaited the government's 
monthly harvest forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for both corn and soybeans had slipped on Wednesday after  
a week-long rally when the U.S. Agriculture Department indicated 
crops were faring better than anticipated despite a sustained dry 
spell. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans rebounded slightly amid investor jockeying ahead of  
Friday's USDA reports on production and supply and demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn, the nation's leading crop, was pressured by news that  
South Korea had rejected offers for three cargoes of corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.87 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn was unchanged at $2.21 a bushel; December oats rose 1/4 
cent to $1.16 a bushel; November soybeans rose 3 1/2 cents to $5.11 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures advanced in early trading on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .13 cent to 67.50 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .28 cent to 79.55 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .20 cent to 45.50 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies rose .35 cent to 54.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
