<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mob Hit Man Cuts Deal With Feds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A mob hit man who says he killed 20 people has cut  
a deal with prosecutors that would allow him to get out of prison 
in as little as eight years, according to documents released 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Martorano, 58, agreed to plead guilty to 12 of the  
slayings. His victims included a millionaire executive in Tulsa, 
Okla., and two teen-agers in Boston who happened to be with one of 
his targets. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Donald K. Stern said all of the killings probably  
would have gone unsolved without the deal, which requires Martorano 
to testify against his former cronies. 
</P>
<P>
	Those other reputed mobsters include James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger  
and Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, who were themselves federal 
informants allegedly given free rein by the FBI to commit crimes 
short of murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger, who is on the run, Flemmi and Martorano are defendants  
in a federal racketeering case that includes reputed New England 
mob boss Francis ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers say the case should be thrown out because of the  
cozy relationship between the FBI and Flemmi and Bulger. A federal 
judge is expected to rule on their motion within days. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we didn't go forward with this agreement, there always  
would have been the lingering suspicion that the reason was to 
protect the FBI,'' Stern said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano agreed to plead guilty to federal racketeering,  
race-fixing, bookmaking and extortion charges in return for his 
testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	If U.S. District Judge Mark L. Wolf also agrees, Martorano will  
be sentenced to 12 1/2 to 15 years in federal prison, with credit for 
the five years he has already served while awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano, so nondescript he didn't even have a nickname, is  
nonetheless among the mob's deadliest admitted killers. 
</P>
<P>
	The list includes Sammy ``the Bull'' Gravano, the Gambino family  
underboss who admitted to 19 killings and served five years after 
testifying against the New York mob. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968 in Boston, Joseph ``The Animal'' Barboza admitted  
killing 26 people but served less than a year in prison after 
agreeing to testify against the New England mob. He was slain in 
San Francisco in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Martorano said he first killed in 1965. He shot an ex-convict  
who had testified before a grand jury that indicted his brother 
Jimmy for being an accessory to murder. 
</P>
<P>
	That was one of the killings he admitted but will not plead  
guilty to. 
</P>
<P>
	He will plead guilty to murder in the 1981 shooting of Roger  
Wheeler, the chairman of Telex Corp. and owner of World Jai Alai, 
outside his country club in Tulsa; and in the 1982 killing of John 
Callahan, a former president of World Jai Alai whose body was found 
in the trunk of a Cadillac at Miami International Airport. World 
Jai Alai operated frontons, which are where the jai alai games are 
played. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
