<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 08:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Van Kampen Funds Fined by SEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the first case of its kind, the Securities  
and Exchange Commission has fined a mutual fund family for 
misleading investors regarding the first-year gains of one of its 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC announced Wednesday it had fined Van Kampen $100,000 for  
failing to accurately disclose how Van Kampen's Growth Fund 
generated huge returns in its first year. In addition, a former Van 
Kampen employee, Alan Sachtleben, was fined $25,000 for his part in 
the effort to mislead investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Kampen and Sachtleben agreed to settle the case without  
admitting or denying the charges. In a statement released after the 
settlement was announced, Van Kampen noted that the Growth Fund 
itself was not under investigation, only the company's failure to 
disclose how the fund had performed so well in its first year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a real bucket of ice water that the SEC is throwing on  
the promotion of short-term results,'' said Burt Greenwald, a 
Philadelphia-based mutual fund consultant. ``It's a positive thing 
for investors in that the SEC is acting aggressively, and not 
against a marginal player but one of the major players in the 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case grew out of Van Kampen's efforts to market its Growth  
Fund in late 1996 and early 1997. Mutual fund companies often use 
first-year gains to promote a new fund to the public, and this was 
no exception: The company claimed the fund grew 62 percent in 1996, 
its first year in existence. 
</P>
<P>
	But Van Kampen failed to disclose that much of that return was  
prompted by investments in initial public offerings. IPO shares 
tend to perform extremely well in their early days of trading and 
can have a big impact on small mutual funds that include them. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout 1996, Van Kampen's Growth Fund was not open to wide  
public investment because it was an incubator fund -- a small, 
startup fund used to generate a performance track record that can 
be used by a mutual fund company to market the fund to a wide array 
of potential investors. Therefore the fund's assets remained 
relatively small during that year, never containing more than 
$380,000, and were highly susceptible to IPO increases, according 
to the SEC. Larger funds with more assets are less susceptible to 
the IPO surges. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on advertisements that touted the previous year's 62  
percent gain, Van Kampen's growth fund grew to $110 million from 
$1.1 million when it was opened to the public in early 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the SEC, Sachtleben was aware that the fund's  
growth rate was due primarily to the performance of hot IPOs but 
failed to inform Van Kampen executives. Sachtleben's silence 
allowed the company to advertise the fund using misleading 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said Sachtleben continued to mislead Van Kampen  
officials even after an online investment newsletter raised doubts 
about the fund's performance. In the wake of the newsletter story, 
Sachtleben, according to the SEC, conducted a study that showed the 
disproportionate impact the IPOs had had on the fund, but he kept 
the information to himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwald said mutual fund companies that do large amounts of  
business with investment banks can frequently obtain shares of hot 
IPOs from those banks before the shares hit the public market and 
balloon in value. A strong performance by of one of those IPO 
shares can then be used to skew the overall performance of a small 
mutual fund, Greenwald explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC brought the charges against Van Kampen Advisory, the  
advisory unit of Oakbrook, Ill., -based Van Kampen Funds. 
Sachtleben, 57, of Houston, was the unit's chief investment officer 
until he retired in June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to track down Sachtleben were unsuccessful. No public  
listing of Sachtleben was available in Houston, and Van Kampen said 
he wasn't available for comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 13:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
