<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rules Vs. GM in Atlanta Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The widow of an Atlanta man who died in a fiery  
1997 wreck has won the right to use potentially damaging, 
decades-old General Motors Corp. documents in her wrongful death 
suit against the company. 
</P>
<P>
	State Court Judge Gino Brogdon directed GM to produce the  
documents and said they were admissible in the trial of the suit 
scheduled to start Oct. 4. He also called the company's efforts to 
withhold the material ``a shameful scheme by GM to defraud and 
mislead several courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brogdon's findings on Tuesday stem from a collection of lawyers'  
notes and memos about a crash-safety report written by GM engineer 
Edward Ivey 26 years ago. GM has withheld the documents from 
plaintiffs, citing attorney-client privilege. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, Ivey's research has already surfaced in several  
trials involving the safety of GM's fuel tanks, including one that 
led a California jury to award a record $4.9 billion in July. A 
judge later reducted that verdict to around $1.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Brogdon was harshly critical of GM and its lawyers in his  
ruling, accusing the company of trying to defraud the courts and 
obstruct justice by keeping the documents from plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``In certain instances GM, by and through its counsel, toyed  
with and ignored court orders, ethical constraints and legal 
barriers,'' Brogdon wrote. ``Plaintiffs have exposed a shameful 
scheme by GM to defraud and mislead several courts, to thwart and 
obstruct justice and to enjoy the ill-gotten gains of likely 
perjury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Hill, an attorney for GM, said the company  
``emphatically denies'' any fraud or obstruction in the cases and 
will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia case was filed by the widow of George Yaw  
Bampoe-Parry, who died from burns he suffered when his Chevrolet 
Chevette was clipped in the rear and burst into flames in May 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens now is that the reckoning begins,'' said lawyer  
Jim Butler, who is representing Bampoe-Parry's widow. ``Two decades 
of concealing the truth and lying are coming to an end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1973, Ivey conducted a cost-benefit analysis of fire-related  
deaths in GM vehicles. The study which has been public for years 
and cited in various trials since the early 1980s, calculated that 
fuel-related fatalities cost the company $2.40 for every GM 
automobile. 
</P>
<P>
	After interviewing Ivey in 1981 about the analysis, one GM  
lawyer wrote: ``Obviously, Ivey is not an individual whom we would 
ever, in any conceivable situation, want to be identified to the 
plaintiffs in a case and the documents he generated are undoubtedly 
some of the potentially most harmful and most damaging were they 
ever to be produced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM has said Ivey's report was an independent intellectual  
exercise riddled with flaws. For this reason, GM has argued, it has 
never been adopted by the company and should not be given to a 
jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler has contended that former GM lawyer Kenneth Starr, the  
independent counsel who investigated President Clinton, 
participated in concealing documents related to Ivey's findings. He 
used to be a partner at the Kirkland &AMP; Ellis law firm and 
successfully argued that certain Ivey-related documents be shielded 
under the attorney-client privilege. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkland &AMP; Ellis has strongly denied Butler's allegations about  
Starr and GM has said the company's representation by Starr and his 
law firm was ``proper in every respect.'' Brogdon made no mention 
of the independent counsel in his order. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
