<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sega Goes High-Tech With Dreamcast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Sega's powerful new Dreamcast game console  
hit store shelves today, complete with flashy graphics, a computer 
that ``learns'' from its mistakes -- and the company's future quite 
possibly at stake. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have managed to create a big buzz and now they have to  
deliver,'' said John Davison, editor-in-chief of Electronic Gaming 
Monthly, a magazine based in Oakbrook, Ill. ``They can't afford to 
stumble at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the buzz is working. Numerous stores across the country  
stayed open late Wednesday night and early today to give video-game 
fans a chance to be among the first with the new gaming system. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to be the first one to get the system. It's the  
best,'' said Ryan Ontiveros, 15, who had pitched a tent outside 
Software Etc. in San Jose on Tuesday night just to be sure he could 
get the game today. 
</P>
<P>
	Store employee John Deegan said about 1,500 people were lined up  
early today waiting to buy the console. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Grose, a 21-year-old college student joined a group of 30  
people at the Electronics Boutique store at the King of Prussia 
mall outside Philadelphia to wait in line for his Dreamcast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been such a big fan of Sega, but then I saw how  
different the Dreamcast system was compared with everything else,'' 
said Grose. ``It was awe-inspiring. I couldn't believe how real it 
looked on the screen. I knew I had to have it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dreamcast faces strong foes as the vital holiday selling season  
approaches, especially with industry leader Sony's PlayStation the 
clear leader and rival Nintendo's N64 doing well, 
</P>
<P>
	The Dreamcast retails for $199.99, reasonable for the power and  
features packed into it. But both Sony and Nintendo recently cut 
prices to under $100 -- and with far bigger game libraries, it may 
be hard to keep the momentum going after the first rush of 
excitement fades. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 games are currently available for the PlayStation,  
and new ones come out almost every week. Nintendo's library is 
smaller, but still more substantial than the 16 Dreamcast games, 
priced at about $50 each, available at today's launch. 
</P>
<P>
	With sales already drooping in Japan, industry watchers warn  
that Sega will have to provide a steady stream of new games for 
Dreamcast to make it in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Sega to succeed, they need to reach their goal of 1.5  
million units sold by next March,'' said Dan DeMatteo, president of 
Babage's Etc., a 500-store chain based in Dallas. ``They need to 
keep the third-party developers developing games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One element in Sega's favor: Both companies are planning  
Dreamcast fighters, though PlayStation 2 and Nintendo's ``Dolphin'' 
won't be ready until next year, giving Sega a good head start. 
</P>
<P>
	Sega was an industry leader in the early 1990s with its Genesis  
gaming console. But the replacement, Saturn, bombed when it was 
launched in 1995 and the Tokyo-based company now holds a puny 1 
percent of the U.S. video-game market. 
</P>
<P>
	With a $100 million marketing and advertising campaign, Sega  
hopes to convince consumers that the new 128-bit system -- four 
times as powerful as PlayStation and twice as fast as the N64 -- 
will provide a more exciting gaming experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreamcast is the first home-gaming system to include Internet  
capabilities. With a built-in modem, consumers can e-mail, chat, 
browse the Web and download game enhancements. Starting next year, 
they'll be able to play one another online. 
</P>
<P>
	The machine features advanced 3-D graphics that make the  
on-screen images clear, crisp and marvelously detailed. In the 
Dreamcast football game, NFL2K, select bad weather and a 
spectacularly realistic rain storm begins on the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreamcast's computer brain can ``learn'' from mistakes. If your  
quarterback passes repeatedly to a single receiver, the game reacts 
after a handful of throws with a defense designed to counter that 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's not clear whether Dreamcast's high-tech capabilities  
will be enough to maintain momentum into next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of good things about Dreamcast. It's price is  
right. It is very powerful,'' DeMatteo said. ``But there is that 
question looming out there over whether it be able to survive a war 
with the other players in the next few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AP Business Writer Rachel Beck contributed to this story.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
