<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Receives Chinese Gift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Smithsonian Institution is adding more  
than 5,000 art objects -- most from ancient China -- to its 
collection after a bequest by an immigrant from central Europe who 
made a career in the United States both as a collector and a 
psychiatrist. 
</P>
<P>
	A foretaste of the gift from the late Dr. Paul Singer went on  
exhibit unannounced last month at the Smithsonian's Arthur M. 
Sackler Gallery. The 18 pieces include a bronze bell 3,000 years 
old and a pierced jade disk a millennium older. Scholars are still 
trying to figure out what kind of ceremony the disk was used for. 
</P>
<P>
	``This generous gift ... adds enormous depth and range to the  
832 objects included in Dr. Sackler's original gift and greatly 
expands the opportunities we can offer for the study and exhibition 
of China's unique cultural heritage,'' said Milo Beach, director of 
the Sackler. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer and Sackler, both physicians, became close friends and  
associates. Sackler's children and foundations helped with the 
accumulation of Singer's collection, estimated to be worth about 
$60 million, in the last years of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer left Austria in 1938 to escape Nazi persecution. He died  
in 1997 at 92. 
</P>
<P>
	The Singer collection was a museum in itself.  
</P>
<P>
	``Visitors to Singer's house frequently were surprised to find  
that his collection took up virtually every inch of space in each 
of the modestly proportioned rooms,'' Thomas Lawton, a former 
director of the Sackler wrote at the time of Singer's death. 
``Antiquities of every kind were arranged, according to material 
and type, in rows four or five deep on tiered shelves that lined 
all the walls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born in what is now Bratislava, Slovakia, Singer began  
collecting East Asian art in nearby Vienna when he was 17. Later, 
he specialized in the southern China state of Chu, founded about 
2,800 years ago. Other experts were skeptical at first, but Lawton 
wrote that due in part to Singer's work ``the art of ... Chu 
emerged as one of the most exciting of all research topics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sackler is putting together a catalog of its new holdings.  
The collection makes it, along with its neighboring sister 
institution, the Freer Gallery, one of the leading centers for the 
study of Chinese art. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, another of the Smithsonian's 16 institutions will  
delve into a different ancient civilization with the help of 
today's technology. The Museum of Natural History will start 
showing, on a screen more than six stories high, the National 
Geographic Society's first large-format film -- ``Mysteries of 
Egypt.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
