<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ervin S. Duggan, president of the Public  
Broadcasting Service, resigned today after shepherding PBS through 
more than five years of ``mission-oriented'' growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``PBS has been significantly strengthened under Ervin Duggan's  
leadership,'' PBS Board Chairman Colin G. Campbell said in a 
statement. ``His efforts have earned the appreciation of our 
colleagues in public broadcasting and of a citizenry that 
recognizes and depends on the excellence he has championed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duggan said he had fulfilled his objectives for the Alexandria,  
Va.-based association of public television stations during his 
5 1/2-year tenure. ``A strategy to create greater financial security 
and enduring value for PBS and its member stations is now in 
place,'' Duggan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have relished serving as a public champion of PBS's unique  
mission of education, culture and citizenship,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Duggan's reign, PBS increased revenues 70 percent -- from  
$182 million in 1995 to a projected $309 million in 2000. PBS, 
which serves 100 million people weekly, also took on new ventures, 
including PBS Online and the PBS Kids channel. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Duggan is not retiring, said PBS spokesman Tom Epstein.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to explore what else is out there,'' Epstein said.  
``He felt he couldn't look for something new while he was still 
full time with PBS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PBS board member John F. Swope will serve as interim chief  
executive when Duggan leaves Oct. 31. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
