<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drugmaker Needs Its Own Pain Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, N.J. (AP) -- American Home Products, stung by thousands  
of lawsuits over its once-popular diet drugs and a profusion of 
other product failures, is betting that a handful of new medicines 
will restore the company's flagging finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the drug maker, with $13 billion a year in  
revenues, is big enough to survive the troubles, but uncertainty 
will hang over the maker of Robitussin and Advil for at least 
another year. And that spells trouble for American Home on Wall 
Street, which has seen its stock price drop more than 40 percent 
since April. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel sorry for them in way because almost every day  
something bad happens,'' said Sally Schaadt, an analyst with 
Fourteen Research in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home's stock tumbled another $2.25, or 5 percent, to  
$40.06 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday, after The Wall 
Street Journal reported the FBI is probing whether the company 
revealed all it knew about dangers of the diet drug Redux prior to 
its approval by the government in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Redux and its older chemical cousin Pondimin were sold by  
American Home with another drug in a combination called fen-phen. 
The treatments were pulled from the market in 1997 after being 
linked to heart valve problems. Thousands of patients have sued the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home, which has denied any wrongdoing related to  
fen-phen, said it is unaware of an FBI investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home's troubles pushed its sales down by 5 percent last  
year. Its operating profits rose by less than 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's prescription for a turnaround centers on five new  
drugs, including a new sleeping pill, an ulcer and heartburn 
medication and a vaccine to prevent ear infections and pneumonia in 
infants. Sonata, the new sleeping pill, was approved last month. 
The other approvals are expected in the next eight months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We now have a drug pipeline that rivals the best in the  
industry,'' said Robert Essner, American Home's executive vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also hopes to expand the use of its top selling  
drug, Premarin, an estrogen therapy that women take to lessen 
symptoms of menopause such as hot flashes and night sweats. 
</P>
<P>
	Essner said the company plans more aggressively market Premarin  
as a drug to prevent osteoporosis, a deteriorating bone disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite these hopes, American Home's problems are mounting.  
</P>
<P>
	This summer a jury awarded a Texas woman who claimed heart valve  
damage from fen-phen $23 million and a judge in Philadelphia 
certified a class-action suit that could require the company to pay 
out millions over years to monitor the health of fen-phen users. 
</P>
<P>
	This July, the company stopped selling its rotavirus vaccine,  
used to prevent serious diarrhea, after it was linked to dangerous 
bowel obstructions in infants. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, it had to recall 600,000 defective allergy kits used  
by people at risk for severe reactions from bee stings, certain 
foods or asthma. The drugs used in the kits weren't potent enough, 
the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also last month, the company reportedly agreed to pay $50  
million to settle claims by women that its contraceptive Norplant 
caused headaches, irregular menstrual bleeding and nausea. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, American Home recalled Duract, a painkiller that  
caused fatal liver problems in some long-term users. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with these problems, Alex Zisson, an analyst with Hambrecht  
&AMP; Quist, has recommended American Home stock for months. ``Their 
pipeline is exceptionally good and expectations can't get any lower 
for their fen-phen liability,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a worst-case scenario, Zisson estimates the company could end  
up paying as much as $10 billion to settle the diet drug suits. 
That's an amount, he said, American Home can afford. 
</P>
<P>
	But others are leery.  
</P>
<P>
	Hemant Shah, an analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. said American Home can  
overcome some big one-time legal costs, but he worries about suits 
that call for the company to pay for medical monitoring thousands 
of patients for years. ``That can be really dangerous because you 
can't quantify it,'' Shah said. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home has been seen as a takeover target for months, but  
analysts say its legal liability could scare away potential 
suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, American Home was poised to merge with Monsanto, a  
life sciences company, but it was called off because of disputes 
between executives of the two companies. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
