<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates Brown Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A jury spent six hours Thursday deliberating  
in football Hall of Famer Jim Brown's domestic violence case 
without reaching a verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel of eight men and four women sent no messages, asked no  
questions and retired for the day without giving any indication of 
whether they were close to a decision. They were scheduled to 
resume deliberations Friday morning at Hollywood Municipal Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 63, is charged with making a terrorist threat against his  
25-year-old wife and vandalizing her car by smashing the windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The football great has a history of domestic violence charges,  
but never has been convicted. Jurors heard testimony during the 
seven-day trial about his relationship with Monique Brown and her 
911 call on the night of June 15 reporting that her husband had 
threatened her life and there was a gun in the house. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown later recanted her allegations against her  
husband, but the city attorney's office decided to prosecute 
without her cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, defense lawyers portrayed Monique Brown as  
mentally unstable. Prosecutors said she was an abuse victim who was 
browbeaten into recanting her story. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
