<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hasbro Buying Pokemon Cards Seller  
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- The immensely popular Pokemon trading  
cards are joining G.I. Joe and Monopoly in the toy lineup of Hasbro 
Inc. The nation's second-largest toy maker said today it is buying 
Wizards of the Coast, a games company that not only sells Pokemon 
cards but also owns the best-selling game Magic: The Gathering as 
well as Dungeons &AMP; Dragons. The $325 million deal is the latest 
acquisition in Hasbro's steady expansion into the games industry. 
Hasbro will also get dozens of shops in the deal with the potential 
to sell more of its goods. Shares in Hasbro closed down 5/16 at 
24 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 43.06 at 11,079.40  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher today as a late rally  
lifted a market that had sputtered for much of the day amid worries 
about a sinking dollar and rising interest rates. At the close of 
trading on Wall Street, the Dow industrials were up 43.06 at 
11,079.40. Broader stock indicators also ended higher. Internet and 
technology companies were the strongest performers. IBM helped the 
Dow contain its losses. Yahoo rose after Lehman Brothers raised its 
rating on the stock. And online auctioneer eBay rose after CIBC 
World Market launched coverage with a ``strong buy'' 
recommendation. 

</P>
