<P>
	Fleet Paying $1.9M to Settle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The investment division of Fleet Financial  
Group has agreed to pay $1.9 million to settle charges by federal 
regulators that Shawmut National Bank of Boston, which Fleet later 
acquired, misused brokerage commissions to pay for client 
referrals. The Securities and Exchange Commission announced the 
settlement today. It also filed related fraud charges against East 
West Institutional Services Inc., a Detroit brokerage firm, and 
eight individuals, including Michael J. Rothmeier, the former 
president of Shawmut's investment operation. 

</P>
<P>
	Hispanic Groups Launch TV Boycott  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A coalition of Hispanic organizations is calling  
for a boycott of the four major networks during the first two weeks 
of the TV season to protest ``the continued invisibility of Latinos 
on television.'' The ``brownout'' of ABC, CBS, Fox and NBC begins 
Sunday and continues through Sept. 25. The National Council of La 
Raza counts just one Hispanic -- Martin Sheen, on NBC's ``The West 
Wing'' -- among the lead characters in the 38 new series premiering 
this fall. Three others continue on returning series: Bruno Campos 
(NBC's ``Jesse''), and, on CBS, Hector Elizondo (``Chicago Hope'') 
and Cheech Marin (``Nash Bridges''). 

</P>
<P>
	Sony Signs On With TiVo  
</P>
<P>
	SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) -- Sony Corp. of America joined a growing  
list of companies rushing to market the latest device for couch 
potatoes by taking a stake in TiVo Inc., a maker of digital video 
recorders that could one day replace VCRs. Sony plans to invest 
more than $25 million in TiVo and will become one of the company's 
two producers of ``personal video recorders'' -- set-top devices 
that rely on hard drives rather than videotape to record television 
shows. Stock in Sony rose 4 percent, closing up 5 at 133 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	New Mercedes Ads Use Humor  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A new ad campaign from Mercedes-Benz takes a  
sharp turn from previous marketing efforts, relying more on humor 
than horsepower to sell the German automaker's luxury cars. The 
first ad for Mercedes' largest marketing push ever shows images of 
Kojak with hair and the Mona Lisa with a toothy grin, asserting 
that it's silly to change something that already works. There's 
only a brief, distant glimpse of cars. 

</P>
<P>
	Reebok To Cut More Than 600 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	STOUGHTON, Mass. (AP) -- Reebok International Ltd. today said it  
plans to lay off 10 percent of its 6,600 workers worldwide in an 
attempt to cut costs and restructure its business. As part of the 
reductions, 120 jobs will be cut at the company's headquarters in 
Massachusetts. Once a close competitor to Nike, Reebok has been 
fighting falling sneaker sales and losing market share to Adidas 
and New Balance Athletic Shoe Inc. of Boston. Reebok's U.S. market 
share has fallen from more than 21 percent in 1995 to 14 percent 
last year. Reebok closed up 1/4 to 11 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	President of PBS To Leave Oct. 31  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ervin S. Duggan, president of the Public  
Broadcasting Service for the past 5 1/2 years, announced today he was 
leaving the job on Oct. 31. Duggan said he had fulfilled his 
objectives for the Alexandria, Va.-based association of public 
television stations during his tenure. Under Duggan's leadership, 
PBS increased revenues 70 percent -- from $182 million in 1995 to a 
projected $309 million in 2000. PBS, which serves 100 million 
people weekly, also took on new ventures, including PBS Online and 
the PBS Kids channel. 

</P>
<P>
	Depression Felt in Most Workplaces  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Depression among workers poses problems in  
most American offices and factories, according to human resource 
managers who responded to a questionnaire. Among those human 
resource managers for 406 U.S. companies, more than half -- 56 
percent -- said employees suffering from depression have had a 
negative impact on productivity at their companies in the past 
three years. Nearly four in 10 said depression among workers is a 
moderate or large problem for their companies. The survey was 
conducted by the Society for Human Resource Management and the 
National Foundation for Brain Research. 

</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Orders French Bank Probe  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French investigators have opened an inquiry into a  
Paris-based bank for its management of funds from Russia's Central 
Bank, including money loaned by the International Monetary Fund, 
judicial sources said. The investigation is aimed at determining 
whether Eurobank moved money from Russia's Central Bank to the 
Financial Management Co., or FIMACO. Eurobank owns FIMACO, and 
Russia's central bank has a 70 percent stake in Eurobank. It was 
the latest episode in an inquiry into the Russian Central Bank's 
handling of its funds. 

</P>
<P>
