<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar jumped against the yen Friday morning  
after Japan's central bank repeatedly intervened to stem the U.S. 
currency's slide. Tokyo stock prices advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.92 yen at late morning, up 1.08 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also higher than its level of 107.78 yen 
in New York. The dollar had traded at 107.65 yen before the 
intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average gained 138.96 points, or 0.79 percent,  
to 17,816.52 at the end of the morning session. On Thursday, the 
average closed up 36.18 points, or 0.21 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar initially sank further against  
the yen in early Asian trading, extending its three-year low hit in 
New York on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Bank of Japan intervened, buying dollars in an attempt  
to stop the yen's rapid rise, lifting the U.S. currency above 109 
yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa confirmed  
later that Japanese authorities stepped into foreign exchange 
markets to weaken the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the BOJ chose today to intervene ... on worries that  
standing to the sidelines would create a vicious circle of a strong 
yen and stock losses,'' said Shuji Takano of ABN AMRO bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said the central bank intervened intermittently,  
purchasing an estimated $1 billion in an attempt to push the 
currency above 110 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	At a separate news conference, Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu  
Nonaka said an excessive strengthening of the yen could damage 
Japan's nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Thursday, the dollar plunged to its lowest level  
against the Japanese currency since August 1996 after Japan 
reported that the nation's economy grew at an annualized rate of 
0.9 percent in the April-June quarter, well above the expectations 
of many economists. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 115.44 yen, down  
from 115.55 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened slightly lower but quickly  
rebounded as concerns about the strong yen subsided following the 
morning jump in the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, cutting into earnings of export-oriented 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 43.06  
points, or 0.6 percent, to 11,079.40 at Thursday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 9.25 points, or 0.61 percent, to 1,516.87. The 
TOPIX closed up 5.05 points, or 0.34 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8150  
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8300 percent. Its price rose 
0.12 point to 100.71. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
