<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famer Catfish Hunter Dies  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hall of Fame pitcher Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter died  
today at the age of 53 after battling the muscle disease named 
after Lou Gehrig, another New York Yankees great. Hunter died at 
his home in Hertford, N.C., according to the Swindell Funeral Home 
in Hertford. He fell and hit his head on concrete steps at his home 
on Aug. 8 and was unconscious for several days, but he had improved 
enough to be sent home Saturday. During 15 seasons (1965-79), 
Hunter earned five World Series rings with the Oakland Athletics 
and the Yankees. The right-hander had five straight 20-victory 
seasons, pitched a perfect game and won a Cy Young Award. He went 
224-166 with a 3.26 ERA. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Wary on N. Korea, Iran Missiles  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Over the next 15 years, North Korea and Iran  
are likely to develop missiles potentially capable of killing 
millions of Americans, the CIA said today In an intelligence report 
with major implications for the Pentagon's efforts to develop 
defenses against ballistic missiles, the CIA said Iraq posed an 
additional -- though somewhat more distant -- threat. The report is a 
summary of a classified National Intelligence Estimate, the first 
the CIA has done on ballistic missile threats since 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Leaders Won't OK Budget Summit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top congressional Republicans said today they  
will not engage President Clinton in budget summit talks this year 
because he would insist on higher spending in exchange for the 
GOP's cherished tax cuts. ``We're just not prepared to trade with 
the president with the American people's money, a spending buck for 
me, a tax reduction for you,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, 
R-Texas, said. Armey renewed the GOP's pledge to use Social 
Security surpluses solely to reduce the $5.6 trillion national 
debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Offers Gun-Buyback Cash  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today introduced a $15  
million federal plan to buy back guns. The new program will give 
local police departments up to $500,000 to buy guns in and around 
public housing projects for a ``suggested price'' of $50. The guns 
will be destroyed. Clinton said American children under 15 are nine 
times more likely to die by accidental shooting than children in 
the other 25 industrialized nations combined. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon Shuns Indonesia Military  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon announced today it has suspended  
official relations with the Indonesian military in light of 
Indonesia's failure to contain the crisis in East Timor. Pentagon 
spokesman Navy Rear Adm. Craig Quigley told a news conference that 
the decision was made jointly by Defense Secretary William Cohen 
and Army Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of 
Staff. It was conveyed overnight to Gen. Wiranto, chief of 
Indonesia's military forces, by Navy Adm. Dennis Blair, commander 
of U.S. Pacific Command. 

</P>
<P>
	Moscow Explosion Kills 32  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Moscow's mayor today blamed Islamic militants for  
an early-morning explosion that ripped through a nine-story 
apartment building. However, with other Russian officials 
contradicting Mayor Yuri Luzhkov's statement, the cause of the 
explosion remained unclear. The explosion on the capital's 
southeastern edge killed at least 32 people, including three 
children, injured 249 and was believed to have left dozens more 
buried in the debris. 

</P>
<P>
	9-9-99 Goes Smoothly  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dreaded high-tech date 9-9-99 arrived today  
with no immediate reports of major Y2K-like computer trouble, 
boosting the confidence of the year 2000 programming experts. There 
had been fears that the string of nines for Sept. 9, 1999, might 
cause some computers to misread the date as an old command to end a 
program. But those concerns appeared to be largely unfounded, as 
most experts predicted after months of tests. Computers abroad also 
behaved well, according to the International Y2K Cooperation Center 
in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 43.06  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher as a late rally lifted a  
market that had sputtered for much of the day amid worries about a 
sinking dollar and rising interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial 
average rose 43.06 today to end at 11,079.40. Internet and 
technology companies were the strongest performers. On the NYSE, 
gainers led losers 1,480-1,478. The Nasdaq rose 43.29 to 2,852.03. 

</P>
<P>
	Sammy Sosa Hits 59th Home Run  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs hit his 59th homer  
today, moving within one of becoming the first player in major 
league history to reach 60 twice. Sosa drove an 0-1 pitch from 
Cincinnati's Pete Harnisch into the back row of center field bushes 
at Wrigley Field. Sosa is eight games ahead of his 66-homer pace of 
a year ago, when Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals 
established a major-league record 70. Sosa's homer gave him a 
five-homer lead over McGwire, whose Cardinals were idle. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
