<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Announcement Irks Fishermen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore announced last week $5  
million in emergency funds for New England fishermen. But some 
observers had a sense of been there, done that. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because the aid had been announced last fall by  
congressional representatives who spent much of the year putting 
the package together. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really stinks of cheap, election-year politics,'' Paul  
Cohane, head of the Gulf of Maine Fisherman's Association, told The 
Boston Globe. ``Mr. Gore had very little to do with this, and yet 
he came and took all the glory. He stole the limelight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Cohane, it was Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., who did  
much of the work to get the funding from the Senate Appropriations 
Committee last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry declined to comment on Gore's announcement or on reports  
that Gore had called him to apologize after the Boston 
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry's spokesman, David Wade, said that Kerry ``really  
appreciates the vice president drawing national attention to a 
pressing regional problem that has long been a top priority to New 
Englanders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said the vice president simply made  
a formal announcement so the money could be made available. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president was extremely pleased to be able to make  
the formal official announcement on behalf of the administration to 
make available emergency relief,'' Lehane said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fishermen said they were angry that the money, first  
announced last October, has not yet materialized. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the fishermen care who gets credit for it. But  
they are concerned because they certainly need assistance. And most 
of their problems stem not from any shortage of fish but from this 
administration's policies,'' said Stephen Ouellette, an attorney 
for the association. 
</P>
<P>
	The emergency funds are supposed to provide some fishermen with  
up to $1,500 for each day their fishing grounds in the Gulf of 
Maine were closed by federal officials last spring. In return for 
the money, fishermen may be required to work with scientists 
conducting research on the health of the fish stocks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 12:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Budget Cuts for SLOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Olympic organizers have once again revised  
their budget -- and said today they have found a way to cut $190 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Salt Lake Organizing Committee already trimmed the  
$1.45 billion budget approved in April for the 2002 Winter Games 
down to $1.33 billion, recent calculations showed a few spots for 
correction and adjustment. 
</P>
<P>
	Most significantly, said SLOC chief operating officer Fraser  
Bullock, the group defined a $74 million wish list of things that 
will only get bought if the revenue comes in to cover them. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, SLOC has cut $10 million from its budget for hiring  
workers. But another $20 million will go into a category of 
``tiered expenses'' that will add to the $116 million in definite 
cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	But because a detailed examination found $67 million in new  
costs, mostly due to errors, there are only about $7 million in new 
savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``tiered'' plan is part of SLOC's new mantra of putting on  
the best possible games without going overboard. Only $1.15 billion 
in funding has been secured or semi-secured, leaving a gap of $179 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have to do it bigger and better,'' Bullock told the  
SLOC board today before members went into closed session to discuss 
the budget in further detail and vote on it. ``We're focused on 
delivering what we have to deliver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC president Mitt Romney said that might mean occasionally  
going over budget to protect the integrity of the athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Romney said, it turns out that the ice on the new  
bobsled run at the Utah Winter Sports Park melts in some patches 
because of variations in sun and shadow. Thus SLOC will have to 
shell out extra money to provide more shade along the course to 
make competition fair. 
</P>
<P>
	But Romney also said that like a private corporation, SLOC will  
have to be responsible for such unforeseen expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is a popular conception in the community that we  
have the ability to spend lots of money and go into debt and leave 
the taxpayers to pay the bills,'' he said. But that is not the 
case, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The new budget does have $140 million built in for  
contingencies. But Bullock insisted most of that money will likely 
be spent. 
</P>
<P>
	Board members voted to automatically close all meetings of the  
ethics committee, unless the group votes to open portions. The 
ethics board members now vote before each meeting whether to close 
the proceedings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Classes Finally Begin in Detroit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Detroit's teachers ended a nine-day strike and  
finally welcomed back 180,000 students from summer vacation 
Thursday, starting the first school year under a board appointed to 
turn the struggling district around. 
</P>
<P>
	The students lost six days of school to the strike by the  
11,500-member union. 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers agreed on Wednesday to go back to work after the  
union and the school board reached a tentative contract over the 
Labor Day weekend. The teachers defeated, for the time being at 
least, such reform measures proposed by the board as merit pay and 
a longer school day. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents were relieved to have their children back in class.  
</P>
<P>
	Alice Martin, a 42-year-old mother of nine, had been relying on  
her 18-year-old daughter to baby sit while Ms. Martin was at work. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's been a lifesaver for me, actually, because I was trying  
to get my other kids into day care. I don't know what I would've 
done without her,'' she said as she dropped off some of her 
children at a spruced-up Joy Middle School. 
</P>
<P>
	The clean-up was among reforms sought by district chief  
executive David Adamany, who pushed through $80 million worth of 
renovations to most of the district's 270 school buildings over the 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The paint was chipping outside. They didn't have the flowers  
or the shrubs, the tennis court was overgrown, the toilets didn't 
work and some of the toilets didn't have doors,'' said 
administrative unit head Barbara Pitts. ``Now, all the plumbing 
works. Everything looks great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Renaissance High School teacher Jacob Ishakis said he had hoped  
to return to school because he didn't like picketing. ``It's not 
what a teacher is supposed to do,'' he said. ``It's degrading, and 
it's demeaning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adamany was named to his post by Mayor Dennis Archer, who took  
over the school styem this spring and replaced the elected board 
with an appointed one to help turn around a district plagued by low 
test scores, graduation rates and attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers still must ratify the contract. Ballots will be mailed  
out later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Johnson, the union's chief negotiator, said that rejection  
of the contract could send teachers back to picket lines, but that 
he doesn't think that is likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Adamany said he still intends to create a merit pay system.  
``We're going to implement it this year,'' he said. ``It'll be up 
to the union to challenge it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
