<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guilty Plea in Pa. School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ERIE, Pa. (AP) -- A 15-year-old boy accused of killing a teacher  
at a school dance last year may have spared himself life in prison 
without parole by pleading guilty to a lesser murder charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Wurst pleaded guilty to third-degree murder Thursday in  
the shooting death of 48-year-old teacher John Gillette, who was 
killed when Wurst opened fire at a dance for his eighth-grade class 
at a banquet hall in Edinboro. He was also accused of wounding two 
students and holding a gun to the principal's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Erie County Judge Michael Palmisano sentenced Wurst to 30 to 60  
years in prison on the murder charge and for attempted homicide, 
assault and weapons charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst must serve at least 30 years before he is eligible for  
parole. His attorneys said he would have received a mandatory life 
sentence if convicted as an adult of first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst was scheduled to go to trial Oct. 25.  
</P>
<P>
	The teen-ager's attorneys had planned an insanity defense, but  
encouraged their client to agree to the guilty plea for fear jurors 
would not accept that Wurst was mentally ill. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way he would have done better is if the jury would  
have found him insane, and insanity is a very difficult defense, 
especially in the tenor of today's times with these shootings 
around the country,'' defense attorney Philip Friedman said. 
</P>
<P>
	A month before the killing, Wurst told classmates at James W.  
Parker Middle School that he wanted to kill people and commit 
suicide. Another classmate noticed that Wurst was becoming curt and 
unfriendly in weeks before the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting -- which occurred within months of those involving  
students in Jonesboro, Ark., West Paducah, Ky., and Pearl, Miss. -- 
stunned residents of Edinboro, a town of 7,000 in northwestern 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Conti said the victims had approved of the plea agreement.  
Gillette's wife, Debbie, and the other victims were in court. None 
commented. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gillette's attorney, Charles Longo, said he plans to sue  
the Wurst family and a landscaping business owned by the boy's 
father, Jerome Wurst. 
</P>
<P>
	Longo said the Gillette family was neither happy about, nor  
satisfied by Wurst's guilty plea. ``They're able to accept it,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
