<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits Three-Year Low vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar plunged to a three-year low against  
the yen Thursday after Japan surprised markets with 
stronger-than-expected economic growth in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 107.78 yen,  
down sharply from 111.08 late Wednesday. It was the dollar's lowest 
level against the Japanese currency since August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0544 against the  
dollar, off slightly from $1.0595 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy grew at an annual rate of 0.9 percent in the  
April-June period, well above the expectations of many economists. 
The advance followed an even stronger showing of 8 percent annual 
growth in the previous quarter, suggesting that Japan's efforts to 
get its economy back on track are showing results. 
</P>
<P>
	``The figures were definitely stronger than expected,'' said  
Masaaki Kanno, an economist with J.P. Morgan. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has been rising against the dollar in recent weeks as  
the outlook for Japan's economy gradually improves. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5185 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5101, and 1.4786 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4883. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound continued to rise following the Bank of  
England's decision to raise a key interest rate Wednesday. The 
pound rose to $1.6356 from $1.6192. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8549 German 
marks, up from 1.8458; 6.2211 French francs, up from 6.1906; and 
1,836 Italian lire, up from 1,828. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
