<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- In an unusual expression of unity,  
Conservative and Reform Jews are helping an Orthodox community 
create an eruv. 
</P>
<P>
	From sundown Friday until sundown Saturday, traditionally  
observant Jews are not allowed to carry anything outside their 
homes. But religious law allows creation of an eruv, a physical 
enclosure that expands the definition of ``home'' beyond the four 
walls. Thus, they may move about, for example, with their children 
in tow. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the largest eruvim in the United States is in the Boston  
area; it stretches over several miles south of the Massachusetts 
Turnpike and was completed in January 1993, after eight years of 
planning and construction. 
</P>
<P>
	An eruv can be anything from a wall to a wire. The Orthodox  
alone generally create these costly and labor-intensive projects. 
Many use utility lines as boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Young Israel congregation of Elkins Park has received  
permission from PECO Energy Co. to put plastic strips on power 
lines. Those strips, known as ``lechi,'' serve as symbolic poles 
under the wire, making the boundary conform with Jewish law. 
</P>
<P>
	Few non-Orthodox congregations observe the Sabbath in a manner  
so strict as to require an eruv. But those in Elkins Park have 
joined Young Israel in an effort to complete the 5-mile, $50,000 
project in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did it as a gesture of community support,'' said Rabbi  
Seymour Rosenbloom of Congregation Adath Jeshurun, a Conservative 
synagogue. ``This is one small area where we were able to show that 
the things that unite us are more important than the things that 
divide us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Jerome M. Epstein of the United Synagogue of Conservative  
Judaism, the New York-based group linking Conservative 
congregations, said he knew of no other such cooperative effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't the usual situation,'' he said, ``so I would say that  
it is special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Cohabiting couples and Catholicism    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Catholic bishops' committee on  
marriage and family has issued a report on cohabiting couples, 
which many priests consider the most troublesome issue in 
premarital counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1995 nationwide survey by Creighton University showed 43.6  
percent of Catholic couples were living together when they began 
premarital counseling. The report terms this ``a fairly recent 
phenomenon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which does not set policy, notes that living  
together out of wedlock violates church teaching. It emphasizes 
that cohabiting couples have a higher risk of divorce. Citing two 
dozen scholarly studies, the report advises priests to help couples 
confront the reasons behind increased risks of divorce. 
</P>
<P>
	Many dioceses ask priests to urge cohabiting couples to live  
apart before the wedding, the report says, but under canon law a 
couple cannot be denied a church ceremony even if they refuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, Catholicism worried that public weddings for  
cohabiting couples would scandalize the community. But the report 
says the social stigma has lessened. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Patriarch sees 'winter of ecumenism'    	
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew, the  
world leader of Eastern Orthodoxy, says stalled efforts toward 
Christian unity have ``caused many, perhaps rightly so, to proclaim 
this period to be the winter of ecumenism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks were made in a welcoming address when presiding  
Bishop Frank T. Griswold of America's Episcopal Church visited in 
mid-July. They were made public Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartholomew noted that Eastern Orthodoxy was a founding member  
of the World Council of Churches in 1948 and participates in other 
such organizations, as does the Episcopal Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite progress in some theological discussions, the patriarch  
noted a recent ``cooling off of relations, a loss of our initial 
drive'' and said Christians must ``recognize and contend with the 
current ecumenical malaise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that some Orthodox had withdrawn from ecumenism to  
express ``uneasiness over particular issues.'' The Russian Orthodox 
Church has suspended activity in the World Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The patriarch said there are legitimate concerns, including the  
incursion of non-Orthodox missionaries into Orthodox lands and the 
``changing criteria for ordination to holy orders,'' an apparent 
reference to Protestants' ordination of women. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartholomew said that despite difficulties, the church ``is  
dedicated and will continue to promote the cause of Christian 
unity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
 *Leader for religious freedom commission    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steven McFarland, director of the Center for  
Law and Religious Freedom, has been named executive director of the 
U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom. The commission 
was established by Congress last year to monitor American policy. 
</P>
<P>
	At the center, McFarland was the strategist on public issues for  
the Christian Legal Society, an organization of evangelical 
Protestant lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a leader in interfaith coalitions working toward the  
commission where he now works; the 1993 Religious Freedom 
Restoration Act, later overturned by the Supreme Court; and the 
Religious Liberty Protection Act, now pending in the Senate. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
