<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Has Organ Transplant Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The network that coordinates organ transplant  
policy unveiled an Internet system Thursday that it hopes will make 
it easier for patients to get information about hospitals that 
perform transplants. They also introduced a system meant to help 
doctors find the right recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Network for Organ Sharing introduced Transplant  
Living, an Internet program located on its Web site, which offers 
consolidated information for transplant patients, including how 
long patients usually wait for transplants at specific centers and 
average survival rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has become for patients a single comprehensive place to  
find information they need for details about what it is going to be 
like after the doctor has said you need an organ transplant,'' said 
Margo L. Akerman, the network's vice president. ``This is first 
Internet-based health-care site to provide this depth of 
information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But skeptics say the network, which has come under fire for  
resisting requests for data, is still not providing what patients 
really need. 
</P>
<P>
	``It needs to be more current, more timely and more complete so  
people can get more information about their procedures,'' said Jon 
Nelson, who oversees transplant policy at the Department of Health 
and Human Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Irwin, president of the National Transplant Action  
Committee, said anything to ``improve the process is a good idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, Transplant Living will make it easier for  
patients and their families to ``shop around'' for health care 
centers that provide organs quickly and successfully, Irwin said. 
</P>
<P>
	But for many, that information won't affect their care.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is a large segment of the population that, regardless of  
the information, has no choice,'' Irwin said. ``They are covered by 
Medicaid or managed care programs (and) their choices are 
limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The network says the program is designed to help everyone by  
providing a reliable source of information for patients to open a 
discussion with their doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	Later this month, the network will also provide doctors and the  
transplant community with UNET, a secured Internet program to 
exchange information on patients and potential donors. 
</P>
<P>
	The program will make the matching process more efficient,  
replacing a 20-year-old system that relies on telephones and fax 
machines, said network spokesman Bob Spieldenner. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nelson has his concerns.  
</P>
<P>
	``Arguably, that will help a lot,'' he said. But he added:  
``There are a lot of details that have to be worked out, and it 
remains to be seen how much this is going to correct it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
