<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missed Field Goal Haunts Anderson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Gary Anderson is still dealing with  
the biggest letdown of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure you ever forget those kinds of things,'' said  
Anderson, who missed the field goal that would have sent the 
Minnesota Vikings to the Super Bowl. ``It's part of life, 
unfortunately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson had been perfect all season long, kicking on grass and  
turf, indoors and outdoors, reliable from all distances. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit 39 straight field goals and made all 67 extra points,  
becoming the first kicker in NFL history to go an entire regular 
season without a miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the biggest kick of his career.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who has more field goals than any kicker in NFL  
history, hooked one barely wide left from 38 yards out in the NFC 
championship game. Given new life, the Atlanta Falcons drove for 
the tying touchdown with less than a minute to play, then won it in 
overtime, 30-27. 
</P>
<P>
	All week, Anderson was reminded of his monumental miss as the  
Vikings prepare to face the Falcons in Sunday's season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a field goal kicker, one of the abilities that you have to  
learn over the years, especially as long as I've played, is to 
always focus on what's coming up next,'' Anderson said. ``If you 
dwell on the past, that's the kiss of death, even more so in this 
particular situation that I had to go through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was an unpleasant offseason for the 18-year veteran who is  
158 points shy of being the NFL's career scoring leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly wasn't fun,'' Anderson said. ``But it's a new  
year now and I have to concentrate on the upcoming season. Our 
business is always about what you're going to do this upcoming 
season, or, in my case, it's even clearer that you've got to make 
the next kick. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what you devote all your attention and energy to.''  
</P>
<P>
	Although it hasn't been easy to reminisce about his perfect  
season in light of his big miss, Anderson said his 1998 season 
``was beyond my wildest dreams and I dream pretty high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the NFL's new kicking rules, however, in which fresh  
footballs are brought in for field goals, Anderson predicted nobody 
will ever be infallible for an entire season again. 
</P>
<P>
	Perfection isn't what's on his mind, anyway. Redemption is.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been playing longer than anybody here. I've done  
everything but win a Super Bowl and I've been close a number of 
times,'' Anderson said. ``That's my main goal. That's why I still 
play football. It's disappointing any time you come close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson's mood brightened Thursday when veteran long snapper  
and locker room cutup Mike Morris returned to the Vikings for 
$400,000 after coach Dennis Green decided rookie Jay Humphrey 
wasn't ready. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and punter Mitch Berger were thrilled the Vikings could  
afford Morris. ``It's not like he's making $2 million,'' Anderson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson recently restructured his contract to give the Vikings  
room to re-sign Morris, one of the league's best long snappers. But 
Morris was waived Sunday because of salary-cap concerns and numbers 
crunches at other positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey, however, had a bad day at practice Wednesday and Green  
decided Morris would give the Vikings a better shot at making a 
Super Bowl run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a little overwhelming, actually, to sit back and  
kind of watch your own funeral on the television and in the 
newspaper and then have the chance to come back from the 
out-of-body experience,'' Morris said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
