<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economy Grows 0.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy confounded expectations and jumped  
0.2 percent in the second quarter -- a further sign that it may be 
on the path to a stable recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The economy grew 0.2 percent in the April-June quarter from the  
previous three months, or at an annualized rate of 0.9 percent, the 
Economic Planning Agency announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the second quarter in a row of growth after 2.0  
percent in the period from January through March. The economy 
shrank 0.7 percent in the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists had expected the economy to shrink from the previous  
quarter, which posted startling annualized growth of 8.1 percent, 
as the effect of massive government spending wore thin. 
</P>
<P>
	``The figures were definitely stronger than expected,'' said  
Masaaki Kanno, an economist with J.P. Morgan. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen soared against the dollar as traders raised their  
expectations for Japan's economic outlook. The dollar fell more 
than 2 yen against the Japanese currency to 108.84 yen in late 
Tokyo trading, and continued to fall in New York. By midday today, 
the dollar was trading at 107.60 yen in New York, its lowest level 
since August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said one of the brightest spots of the data was the  
rise in private-sector spending, which was up 0.8 percent in the 
second quarter, showing that battered consumer confidence -- a major 
cause of Japan's economic downturn -- may be reviving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was expecting personal consumption and housing investment to  
be strong, but (the numbers) were even better than expected,'' said 
Jun Ishii, chief market economist at Tokyo-Mitsubishi Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said ordinary consumers are finally beginning to spend  
more on nonessential goods like computers and electronic products. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy has been in the dumps ever since the end of the  
potlatch years of the 1980s, when unbridled speculation left banks 
and corporations saddled with huge debts. Fears of being laid off 
have caused workers to squirrel away savings more than ever before, 
and banks have stopped lending as they struggle to write off bad 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the growth rush that started with the beginning of 1999,  
Japan's economy had been in a two-year tailspin -- the country's 
worst recession since the end of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Top economic officials appeared to take today's data in stride,  
and still urged caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was within the high end of the strike zone,'' said Japan's  
chief economic planner, Taiichi Sakaiya. ``We will have to be very 
careful in our economic policies from now on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sakaiya declined to comment on the size of an expected  
supplementary budget designed to keep economic growth on track. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was confident the economy would achieve the  
government's growth target of 0.5 percent, but economists were 
already saying GDP would likely grow by more than twice that much 
in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing investment rose 16.1 percent in the second quarter -- an  
unprecedented pace in Japan on a quarterly basis. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Kanno said the rise in housing investment was mainly  
due to government policies like tax breaks and artificially low 
mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not going to last forever,'' Kanno said.  
</P>
<P>
	Private capital investment declined as big corporations continue  
to tighten their purse strings, said an EPA official, briefing 
reporters on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Public investment also fell, but that was due to the massive  
government spending of the previous quarter, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The level of investment was still high,'' the official said.  
``It was a nominal decline, reflecting an extraordinary increase in 
public investment in the previous quarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who took office in July  
last year, has promised to put Japan's economy on a recovery path, 
with at least 0.5 percent annual growth. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been other bright signs in the economy. The  
government announced earlier this week that increasing demand from 
Asian countries was behind recent growth in Japan's industrial 
output. 
</P>
<P>
	A closely watched government business survey showed that  
Japanese corporate sentiment improved sharply in the April-June 
quarter and is expected to rise further in the next two quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, joblessness has been rising steadily amid attempts by  
corporations to aggressively reorganize. In June, the unemployment 
rate hit a record high 4.9 percent, and many think it will climb 
further as restructuring accelerates. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said that although the economy would probably grow  
again in the third quarter, it was likely to shrink in the fourth 
as public spending measures run dry. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
