                         *Harry B. Robinson    	
</P>
<P>
	SEBRING, Fla. (AP) -- Harry B. Robinson, who worked more than  
three decades for The Associated Press, died Saturday at his home. 
He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was born in Cumberland, Md., in 1914, and joined the AP  
in New York in 1941. He retired in 1979 after 36 years as an 
assistant communications manager. 

</P>
<P>
                           *John K. Tabor    	
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Former Pennsylvania Commerce Secretary John K.  
Tabor, credited with turning around the state's economy in the 
1960s, died Monday from a stroke in Washington D.C. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	President Richard Nixon appointed Tabor U.S. undersecretary of  
commerce in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabor worked for the Pittsburgh law firm until moving to  
Washington 26 years ago. He joined the Washington law firm of 
Purcell &AMP; Nelson and retired in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabor was the son of Pittsburgh attorney Edward O. Tabor, who  
helped found the former Czechoslovak Republic. After his retirement 
in 1990, Tabor wrote a biography of his father, who had been 
decorated by the Czech government. 
  	   	
</P>
