<HEADLINE> Man Pleads Guilty in Licensing Ploy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A former manager of a suburban driver's licensing  
facility pleaded guilty today to fixing tests for truck drivers in 
exchange for payoffs and political contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	George Velasco, 50, entered his plea one day after prosecutors  
said he had given a special oral exam to Ricardo Guzman, the driver 
involved in a 1994 crash near Milwaukee that killed six children in 
one family. 
</P>
<P>
	Velasco and another former supervisor at the McCook licensing  
facility were among six people charged in April with selling 
commercial drivers' licenses to hundreds of unqualified applicants. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors said from 1991 to 1998, the six conspired to  
make sure certain applicants passed licensing tests at the office 
of the Illinois secretary of state, taking bribes of up to $1,200 
per license. The secretary of state at the time was George Ryan, 
who is now governor. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed Wednesday, prosecutors suggested for the  
first time that Guzman's license came as a result of illegal 
payoffs, but stopped short of saying specifically he bought his 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	Before U.S. District Judge Joan Gottschall, Velasco acknowledged  
raising more than $25,000 in campaign funds as part of a conspiracy 
with Marion Seibel, the other McCook manager, who already has 
pleaded guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for an unspecified break when he is sentenced Feb.  
11, Velasco will cooperate with prosecutors at the Oct. 12 trial of 
trucking company operative Gonzalo Mendoza. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendoza, who arranged to have Guzman tested, is charged with  
making payoffs and contributions to Ryan's fund to get licenses. 
Guzman himself has not been charged with wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Duane and Janet Willis, whose six children died in the  
1994 accident, recently settled a lawsuit against five corporations 
and two individuals, including Guzman, for $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan says he knows nothing about using truck drivers licenses to  
raise thousands of dollars for his campaign fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of whether Guzman got his license through  
corruption became central to the 1998 race for governor. Democrat 
Glenn Poshard even ran a television ad that showed the charred hulk 
of the Willis van. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar said when the initial charges were  
announced that Ryan was not a target of the investigation. Since 
then, however, prosecutors have said they will not comment on who 
might or might not be a target. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
