<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Complaints Hit 11-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fort Worth, Texas-based American Airlines led all major U.S.  
airlines in passenger complaints in July as complaints against all 
carriers hit an 11-year high, according to new U.S. Department of 
Transportation figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Southwest Airlines had the fewest complaints and  
the best on-time performance, while America West Airlines, based in 
Tempe, Ariz., ranked last in on-time performance, the agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled,'' said Melanie Jones, a spokeswoman for  
Southwest. ``It's gratifying to see our emphasis on service 
reflected in the numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers filed 2,111 complaints against U.S. carriers in the  
month, and American, the nation's second-largest carrier, had about 
50 percent more complaints than the largest carrier, United 
Airlines. An additional 374 complaints were lodged against foreign 
carriers, tour operators, travel agents and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the complaints lodged against American, half were for  
``flight problems,'' the federal agency said. Other frequent 
complaints were for customer service and baggage problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nothing we're happy about, but most of the complaints  
were associated with severe air-traffic control, and spring weather 
problems we encounted in April, May and June'' led to complaints in 
July, said Tim Smith, a spokesman for American. About a third of 
American's July complaints covered incidents in earlier months, the 
Transportation Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said American was hit hardest of any airline by Federal  
Aviation Administration computer upgrades that slowed air-traffic 
control operations in Dallas-Fort Worth, Chicago and Cleveland. He 
said the airline has taken steps, such as more-timely boarding, to 
improve on-time performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,485 overall complaints nearly doubled the June total of  
1,332 and marked the highest number since March 1988. Nearly half 
dealt with flight problems, including delays, missed connections 
and canceled flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest had the fewest number of baggage complaints per 1,000  
passengers among the largest 10 carriers, followed by Northwest, 
Delta and Continental. 
</P>
<P>
	The same 10 improved their on-time performance slightly from  
June, with just over 71 percent of flights arriving on time. 
Southwest was on time about 78 percent of the time. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
