<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery Shrouds Sanders' Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Deion Sanders remained on the sidelines  
Thursday during the Dallas Cowboys' last big practice of the week, 
and coach Chan Gailey is not expecting him for Sunday's season 
opener in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders practiced on Monday, then sat out Tuesday's drills  
because a toe that he injured last November continued to bother 
him. Gailey said Thursday's practice would be the litmus test for 
whether Sanders could play against the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sanders wasn't even in his pads Thursday. He jogged up and  
down the field several times, tossed a medicine ball briefly, then 
sat on the sidelines, huddled in conversation with owner Jerry 
Jones during practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We listed him as doubtful all along, and I think that will  
probably continue,'' Gailey said. ``It is a long shot that he will 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said: ``It will still be a game-time decision. You've got  
to really be confident and trust you can rely on that foot, and 
he's not there yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said Thursday afternoon: ``It's a long shot, but I've  
shot long before. I know it's getting better. It's hard to believe 
that today, but it's getting better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the toe injury, Sanders has missed five full games and  
parts of two others. He came back for the Cowboys' playoff loss to 
Arizona, but underwent surgery on April 28. 
</P>
<P>
	If he doesn't play Sunday, Sanders could return eight days later  
in a Monday night game at home against the Atlanta Falcons, one of 
the teams he formerly played for. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really, he's going to be the judge of how much pain he can  
tolerate, how much pain there is and whether he can do further 
damage,'' Gailey said earlier this week. ``If we can't do further 
damage, then it's a question of whether it's too painful to do the 
things he needs to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders didn't practice at all on Tuesday because of soreness  
after a half-practice on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old star said he wants no limitations when he  
returns, meaning he would play cornerback and return punts. He was 
a Pro Bowl selection at both spots last season and played in the 
February game despite the toe problem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
