<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed in early trading today, with  
Internet shares posting solid gains while most shares languished. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 7.60 at 11,028.74. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 1.86 at 1,342.29, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 14.29 at 2,823.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were held back by the dollar's continuing decline against  
the Japanese yen. After the Japanese government released a 
stronger-than-expected report on the nation's economic growth, the 
dollar fell to 108.84 yen today from 111.22 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong report and the rising value of the yen helped push  
Japan's Nikkei stock average 0.2 percent higher. Weakness in the 
dollar has been a persistent undercurrent in the U.S. stock market 
in recent weeks, as improving economies in Asia and Europe attract 
investors who previously sought out U.S. securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet companies provided pockets of strength today. Yahoo  
rose 6 9/16 to 160 after Lehman Brothers raised its rating on the 
stock to ``outperform'' from ``neutral.'' And online auctioneer 
eBay rose 5 1/16 to 139 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products dropped 2 13/16 to 39 1/2 amid reports that  
the company is facing a federal investigation involving the 
government's 1996 approval of the drug Redux. American Home 
Products has already seen its share price battered as the company 
faces thousands of civil lawsuits over its diet drugs, which have 
been linked to heart valve problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 90.8 million 
shares, behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.80 to 436.70.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.2 percent,  
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.5 percent. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
