<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Topless Woman Causes Traffic Jam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- It wasn't your standard weekday traffic jam when  
drivers slowed to watch a fire-spitting woman dancing topless atop 
a high-voltage electrical tower beside a freeway bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't meant to be.  
</P>
<P>
	Ara Tripp, 38, of Olympia, told The Seattle Times she planned  
the stunt for weeks to protest discrimination against women and 
laws that allow men to take their shirts off but not women. Tripp 
was a man before undergoing a sex-change operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Tripp climbed the 180-foot tower Wednesday morning, took off her  
shirt and began dancing, occasionally taking swigs from a vodka 
bottle, spitting out the liquor and setting it aflame. 
</P>
<P>
	Traffic on a nearby interstate bridge over the Lake Washington  
Ship Canal slowed to a near-standstill during the hour or so Tripp 
remained on the tower. 
</P>
<P>
	She had made a practice climb of the tower several nights  
earlier. Still, it was ``an extremely dangerous, hazardous 
situation,'' said Larry Vogel, spokesman for Seattle City Light. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility cut electricity to 5,000 homes and businesses to  
protect Tripp from being zapped by the 120,000 volts of juice 
flowing through the lines the tower supports. 
</P>
<P>
	Tripp was arrested for investigation of criminal trespass and  
indecent exposure, each carrying a maximum penalty of a year in 
jail and a $5,000 fine, Best said. She was released after posting 
$690 bail and faces a Sept. 22 court date. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll plead guilty,'' she said. ``It's pretty obvious.''  
</P>
<P>
	Tripp has a wife -- whom she married when she was still a man --  
strongly disapproved of the plan but was out of town Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's not going to be happy,'' Tripp said. ``I'm going to be  
grounded.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990909.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 14:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tribe Takes 5th Straight AL Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Indians were 20,000 feet somewhere above  
the Central time zone when they clinched their fifth straight AL 
Central title. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Cleveland's players didn't find out they were  
officially champs until they walked off their plane in Chicago 
early Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Needless to say, there wasn't any champagne popped near the  
baggage carousel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shook hands and that was about it,'' Indians manager Mike  
Hargrove said from his hotel room Thursday. ``It was very 
subdued.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, perhaps, very fitting.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland was expected to win its division again this year  
without much of a struggle. But the Indians could never have 
imagined the route they would take to get there. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has been ravaged by major injuries almost since opening  
day, and only in the past week have All-Stars Travis Fryman and 
Sandy Alomar returned. Even now, Hargrove has only been able to 
field his opening day lineup four times -- not at all since April 
22. 
</P>
<P>
	At moments this season, Cleveland's lineup had as many Buffalo  
Bisons as Indians. On Wednesday night, Hargrove used his 101st 
different batting order and the team has placed 15 players on the 
disabled list a total of 21 times. 
</P>
<P>
	So when the Indians failed to clinch Wednesday night by losing  
3-0 at Texas, they were forced to pack their champagne back in ice. 
Packed in ice is how many of Cleveland's players spent their time 
healing bumps and bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I expected to win our division, and I don't want to  
come off as arrogant,'' Hargrove said. ``That was one of the goals 
that we set before the season and one that was very attainable. But 
I can't say I thought we would clinch the division as early as we 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With another regular seemingly injured every day, the Indians  
turned to their youngsters at Triple-A Buffalo for help. And the 
kids came through. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, rookie Einar Diaz became the starting catcher when Sandy  
Alomar underwent another surgery on his left knee. After some early 
struggles, Diaz improved defensively and became the team's unsung 
hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland also got major contributions from rookies Jacob Cruz,  
Jolbert Cabrera, Dave Roberts and Alex Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys we have are very good players,'' Hargrove said. ``And  
the guys who came in like Einar Diaz, stepped in and came up very, 
very big for us. That's been nice to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians' pitching staff has also had major problems of its  
own. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland was counting on Jaret Wright to have a breakthrough  
year following an inconsistent '98. But Wright's confidence was 
severely shaken when allegations he was a headhunter prompted AL 
president Gene Budig to call the young right-hander into his office 
in New York in May for a meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright then hid an injury from the Indians, and has spent two  
different stints on the disabled list. He'll be activated this 
weekend for a Sunday start against the White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Karsay, arguably the Indians' MVP in the first half of the  
season, also became a pitching casualty when Hargrove and Cleveland 
GM John Hart tried to convert him from long reliever to starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Dwight Gooden has also shuffled between the minors and the  
Indians as he battled injuries and inconsistency. And Cleveland's 
bullpen, considered the team's strength, has been shaky at best. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the turmoil, the Indians have managed to keep  
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Starters Bartolo Colon, Charles Nagy and Dave Burba have also  
had solid years, backed by the majors' most potent offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Manny Ramirez and Roberto Alomar are each having MVP-caliber  
years, and shortstop Omar Vizquel (.331 average) has become as 
valuable batting in the No. 2 slot as he is at shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Thome, Richie Sexson, David Justice, and newly added Harold  
Baines may all drive in 100 runs, and as the Indians get healthier 
-- Wil Cordero came back from a broken wrist Wednesday -- their 
chances of winning their first World Series since 1948 get better. 
</P>
<P>
	During spring training, Hargrove set two goals: 100 wins and a  
Series title. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Central crown was more of a checkpoint than a goal, but  
one Hargrove, who has done his finest managing job, is nonetheless 
proud of. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never go into a season with any preconceived notions about  
how we might do,'' he said. ``But this is nice.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
