<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean War Adoptees Come Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Susan Soon-Keum Cox walked through the Korean  
War memorial, with its chilling sculptures of tired, pained 
soldiers, and couldn't help wondering, ``Could one of those men be 
my father?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adopted by an American family in the aftermath of the Korean  
War, Cox longed to join with other Korean adoptees, to share 
stories of growing up before international adoptions became 
accepted, even popular. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend, her vision becomes reality, as more than 400  
Korean adoptees gather for the first time, many of them the 
abandoned children of U.S. servicemen and Korean women. 
</P>
<P>
	They were raised in the United States in the 1950s and '60s,  
before there were books explaining adoption and before special 
culture camps helped kids born in foreign lands connect with each 
other. They constantly had to explain why they looked so different 
from their families. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference offers a chance to talk with those who  
understand. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we have children of our own, those questions of identity  
and balance become increasingly important,'' said Cox, who was 
adopted in 1956 after her Korean mother concluded she could not 
raise a child of mixed race. 
</P>
<P>
	A survey of people attending the conference, which is open to  
all adult Korean adoptees, found many of them did not connect with 
their Korean identities until adulthood. Fewer than one-third 
thought of themselves as Korean-American while growing up, with 
about a third calling themselves Caucasian. 
</P>
<P>
	But today, two in three see themselves as Korean-American, with  
just one-tenth of them considering themselves Caucasian. 
</P>
<P>
	The shift is due partly to maturity, researchers say. As  
children grow up, they want to learn more about themselves and 
where they came from. It's also due to changing times, with more 
interest and acceptance of different ethnicities, which helps fuel 
their search for identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a society, we are much more interested in our  
individuality,'' said Cox, who was adopted through and now works 
for Holt International Children's Services, which pioneered 
international adoptions in the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, international adoptions have exploded. Last year,  
nearly 16,000 children were adopted from other countries -- a number 
that's doubled in just 10 years -- and parents have many more 
resources to teach their children about their heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	But that wasn't always the case.  
</P>
<P>
	Paula Johnstone was adopted in 1958 and had a typical American  
childhood, growing up in Portland, Ore., and never thinking much 
about Korea. Then, in 1993, her mother died, and she started to 
think about who she was. 
</P>
<P>
	``I looked in the mirror and said, `I'm not white,''' she said.  
``It was almost like a midlife crisis. Now I'm soul-searching for 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming to the conference meant saving hundreds of dollars for  
the plane fare and other expenses; she says it's the first time she 
has saved for something she really wanted to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought maybe I would find out more about myself, about who  
I am,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soul-searching is on the agenda. Participants will be divided  
into groups by age and asked to talk about their roots and 
childhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	``Growing up, I was the American kid, going to the local  
schools, doing what every American girl would do,'' said Anne Hai 
Ja Curtis, who was adopted in 1973 and grew up in Quincy, Mass. 
``It wasn't until a few years back that I began to look more into 
my identity, who I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of attendees, answered by 167 people, is not  
representative of all Korean adoptees, though it offers some 
insight into their experiences. Many reported racial discrimination 
growing up, and many said they were now interested in learning 
about their birth families and about Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 100,000 Korean children have been adopted by U.S.  
families since 1955, a trend that began with war children and grew 
through the years, fueled by Korean stigmas against out-of-wedlock 
births and adoption. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox, who came up with the idea of the conference while walking  
through the Korean War Veterans Memorial, is looking forward most 
of all to Sunday morning, when the entire group will rise at dawn 
and travel to the memorial together. 
</P>
<P>
	She remembers staring into the reflective black granite, with  
its sandblasted etchings of United Nations troops and Korean 
civilians. Nearby, statues depict infantrymen as they slog through 
a field, fatigue and pain etched into their detailed faces. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what angle you're at, they look at you and they look  
so scared,'' Cox said. ``It brings back all the questions, and 
there are no answers.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
