<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Dealers Facing Tough Times / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) -- The slump in crop prices hurting Pacific  
Northwest farmers is spilling over into other sectors of the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales are down at farm implement dealerships -- prompting layoffs  
and branch closings for some -- and growers are becoming stingier 
when it comes to applying farm chemicals, industry officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty much the first on the food chain,'' said Kirk  
Smith of Smith Truck &AMP; Tractor in Pasco. ``Even the better growers, 
rather than purchase (new), they're rebuilding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He worries the effects will spread throughout the rural economy.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care how far down the food chain you are in this;  
it'll hit fertilizer sales, auto dealers, department stores, 
everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A new combine costs at least $150,000, and low interest rates  
aren't enough to entice budget-conscious farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said several of his regional competitors are laying off  
workers or have closed branches. And the slump has prompted a few 
employees at Smith's store to leave voluntarily, including a sales 
associate on commission and a mechanic looking for more hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The family business has survived other lean years when commodity  
prices nose-dived. But usually, it's only one or two commodities, 
not ``the whole spectrum,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat growers have been particularly hard hit. The soft white  
wheat typically grown in the Northwest costs about $3 per bushel to 
produce, but prices have been running about $2.73 per bushel -- 
about $2 less than the price four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Other crops -- including apples -- are experiencing similarly  
depressed prices due to a range of factors including overproduction 
and the slow recovery of the Asian economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In Othello, Larry Hawley of B&AMP;H Ag Chem said sales have slowed  
and profit margins have shrunk as growers opt for fewer 
applications of fertilizers, herbicides and pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	``This time of year, we have a lot of money out that's yet to  
come in from the growers,'' Hawley said. ``We have to wait for 
their harvest. Hopefully, we're up high on their list to get paid 
when they get paid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pickup truck and car sales have slowed dramatically as regional  
agriculture-based economies struggle and farmers rein in 
discretionary spending, said Wyatt Tone, finance director of a 
Walla Walla Ford dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're selling about half of what we did this last year,'' Tone  
said. ``It's down, down all over in Eastern Oregon, Eastern 
Washington, Northern Idaho and in Montana.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Mackay, chief financial operator for Kennewick-based  
AgriNorthwest, said the large, privately owned farming operation is 
still replacing vital, worn-out equipment and is continuing minor 
development projects started more than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But, ``anything discretionary as far as equipment goes, we're  
cutting back,'' Mackay said. ``We need to be frugal with every 
dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hawley said many farmers are justifiably worried about their  
financial survival in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be an interesting fall and spring, because the  
commodity markets are so far down, these guys are penciling this 
deal out,'' he said. ``A lot of them went in this year on nip and 
tuck. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sad part about it is, we're losing more of the small  
farms, the family farms. I hate to see those things go. ... The 
family farm is what the nation was built on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Golden, a spokesman for Deere &AMP; Co., the Illinois-based farm  
equipment giant, said despite the slump, he's optimistic for the 
farm economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry will work through this,'' he said. ``Overall, the  
farmer is better equipped to handle this downturn than he was in 
the 1980s ...'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
