<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drivers License Manager Admits Fix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A former manager of a suburban Chicago driver  
licensing center pleaded guilty Thursday to rigging exams for truck 
drivers, bringing to a dozen the number of people convicted in an 
ongoing federal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	George Velasco, 50, admitted taking payoffs and using his  
position to raise more than $25,000 in political contributions, 
including contributions to Illinois Gov. George Ryan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan was secretary of state at the time and in charge of driver  
licensing. Prosecutors have said that Ryan was not a target of the 
probe. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 drivers illegally obtained licenses from 1991 to  
1998, U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar said. The drivers were told the 
answers to test questions, illegally coached and in some cases were 
given previously filled out forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Velasco refused to answer reporters' questions after the  
hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	In pleading guilty, Velasco agreed to cooperate with federal  
prosecutors and could testify against others implicated in the 
scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted in federal court that he conspired to rig the tests  
for money with a former trucking company employee, Gonzalo Mendoza, 
and Marion Seibel, another former manager of the driver licensing 
center who has pleaded guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendoza goes on trial Oct. 12 on charges he made thousands of  
dollars in payoffs and contributions to Ryan's campaign in exchange 
for passing scores on license tests for drivers he referred. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
