<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 10:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rents At Military Housing Too High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rents at new apartments built under a  
government experiment to improve family housing for the military 
are too high for some sailors. So 60 units have been rented to 
civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	The garden-style apartments built by private developers near  
Corpus Christi, Texas, range in rent from $525 to $835 a month. 
That's more than what some junior-ranking Navy personnel stationed 
at three nearby bases receive in monthly housing allowances. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty Officer 1st class John Turner's $698 housing allowance  
doesn't cover his $750-a-month rent and $200 in monthly utility 
expenses. Turner said he took a four-bedroom apartment at the 
Corpus Christi complex a year ago because he had only a week to 
find a place for his wife and three children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked that we had to pay so much,'' said his wife,  
Angela. To conserve money, she's cut back on groceries and keeps 
the blinds drawn all day to save on air-conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Navy families received preference from the developer and 85  
percent of the 404 available units were leased to military people. 
But because the rents were high and some Navy families prefer to 
live on base, the complexes didn't fill up with military renters. 
The remaining units were leased to civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon says it has a solution to the rent problem.  
Starting this fall, it plans to pay the developer the difference 
between each sailor's housing allowance and rent, so sailors won't 
have to dip into their base pay, which can be as little as $887 a 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a way to work out the difference, and that is the  
differential lease payments,'' Joe Sikes, director of the Defense 
Department's competitive sourcing and privatization office, said 
this week. Funds for differential payments will be released this 
month, unless Congress objects, Navy officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Turners, whose rent rises to $835 in October, say they'll  
have to move if the differentialpayments don't come through. 
</P>
<P>
	The rent problem is the latest snag in a slow-starting Defense  
Department project aimed at replacing tens of thousands of 
dilapidated military homes with new or renovated units built by 
private developers. 
</P>
<P>
	Finding housing for the growing number of military personnel  
with families has become a serious problem. Two-thirds of the 
300,000 family homes owned by the Pentagon either need extensive 
renovations or are in such bad shape they should be replaced, a 
Pentagon study showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials convinced Congress that private developers  
could build homes faster and cheaper. Lawmakers gave the Defense 
Department the go-ahead in 1996 to provide loan guarantees, land 
leases and commercial incentives to developers, who could own and 
operate military housing units. 
</P>
<P>
	The department pledged that contracts for eight to 10 projects  
totaling 2,000 new units would be awarded within a year, but legal 
and bureaucratic delays slowed the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, just the two apartment developments near Corpus  
Christi and a third Navy privatization project in Washington state 
have been built, and they were in the works before the 
privatization program began. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials now say contracts for 14 projects totaling  
17,475 units will be awarded by August 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy is part-owner of the two complexes near Corpus Christi,  
having contributed $9.5 million, one-third of their cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Civilians who rent there pay the same rate as military  
personnel, are subject to the same lease durations as military 
renters and can renew their leases even if military families are on 
a waiting list. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the Washington state apartments are rented to families  
from Naval Station Everett. 
</P>
<P>
	Sikes said renewal policies for civilian renters will vary at  
each project, but military families will always have preference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department has asked Congress to extend the program  
-- set to expire in early 2001 -- for five more years. 
</P>
<P>
	A skeptical Congress in August approved just $2 million for the  
housing privatization office for next year and directed $76 million 
towards traditional military housing construction. The Pentagon can 
use these funds for privatization projects if it chooses. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dave Hobson, R-Ohio, chairman of the House military  
construction appropriations subcommittee, said privatization should 
``benefit those it's intended to benefit: our troops and their 
families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The program is still in its preliminary stages, so it is  
unclear whether privatization is an efficient means to get families 
new housing,'' Hobson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
