<DOCNO> APW19990909.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 15:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hasbro Buying Pokemon Cards Seller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Pokemon trading cards, so popular that  
stores are finding it hard to keep them in stock, are joining G.I. 
Joe and Monopoly in the toy lineup of Hasbro Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's second-largest toy maker said Thursday it is buying  
Wizards of the Coast, a games company that not only sells Pokemon 
cards but also owns the best-selling game Magic: The Gathering as 
well as Dungeons &AMP; Dragons. 
</P>
<P>
	The $325 million deal is the latest acquisition in Hasbro's  
steady expansion into the games industry. This time, Hasbro also is 
getting dozens of shops with the potential to sell more of its 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Pokemon trading card game is probably the hottest card on  
the market right now, so it's great timing to buy Wizards of the 
Coast,'' said Cliff Annicelli, the managing editor of Playthings 
magazine, a monthly trade publication. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have their hands in basically every toy category that  
there is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Byrne, a toy consultant, said Hasbro is reshaping itself  
into a children's entertainment industry that can more effectively 
compete with video stores and movie theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's really cool about what Hasbro is doing is they are not  
walking away from their basic board games ... but they are walking 
aggressively into the new kind of gaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro's brands include Playskool, Kenner, Tonka, Parker  
Brothers, Tiger and Milton Bradley. The company had $3.3 billion in 
sales last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wizards is expected to generate $400 million in sales this year,  
compared with $150 million last year, according to an analysis by 
Salomon Smith Barney. The investment firm estimates Pokemon cards 
will account for about $225 million in sales in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Pokemon (pronounced po-KEE-mon) is an inexpensive card game that  
debuted as a low-tech video game and burgeoned into an empire. It 
was started in Japan by Nintendo as a Game Boy video game in which 
players find, capture, collect and train 150 pet monsters. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Hasbro obtained rights from Nintendo to make and  
market toys based on the Pokemon cartoon TV show. 
</P>
<P>
	Pokemon made headlines in December when nearly 700 Japanese,  
mostly children, suffered blackouts, convulsions and nausea after 
watching one 30-minute episode of the TV series. A TV Tokyo 
investigation found that flashy special effects may have caused the 
illnesses. Programmers say the problem has been fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Kneeland, owner of The Toy Shop, Ltd., a specialty store  
in Bristol, R.I., said he doesn't normally buy mainstream toy 
products because he can't compete with the mass market. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the case of Pokemon, he felt he had no choice ``because  
every other phone call was, 'Do you have Pokeman cards?' For 
Pokemon cards now, we're probably getting 20 calls a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is sold out of them.''  
</P>
<P>
	About a week ago, he put in an emergency call to a California  
distributor and ordered 144 booster packs. They sold out in two 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing to me,'' Kneeland said.  
</P>
<P>
	A Wizards spokeswoman said with or without the acquisition, the  
company can't immediately increase Pokemon production. ``The 
popularity of the product is so strong that it has been very 
difficult to keep up with the demand. If we could beef up 
production, we certainly would. Our printers have been working at 
full capacity and have been for several months,'' said Charlotte T. 
Skeel. 
</P>
<P>
	It's premature to say whether the purchase will allow Wizards to  
expand its printing operation, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to game cards, Wizards also is a leading publisher  
of fantasy and science fiction literature and owns almost 70 game 
stores. Wizards also hosts thousands of tournaments and owns a 
3,800-square foot entertainment center in Seattle, complete with a 
video and pinball arcade. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro says it didn't intend to embark on a retail trend with  
the purchase, but simply wanted to broaden the gaming market. ``We 
bought the company that happened to have retail stores,'' said 
Wayne S. Charness, Hasbro's senior vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what really got us going ... is it expanded our  
opportunities in games, which is a cornerstone of our growth 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro also announced this week that its subsidiary, Hasbro  
Interactive Inc., will now be developing products for Sega's new 
Dreamcast, the first home-gaming system to include Internet 
capabilities. That could mean a new world of interactive games 
where children play Dungeons &AMP; Dragons with other children in 
different parts of the world, Byrne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Adkison, who founded Wizards in 1990 and is president and  
CEO of the company, will continue to run the business, which will 
remain Seattle-based. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro, which is based in Pawtucket, R.I., said an antitrust  
review already has been completed. It said the shareholders who 
control more than two-thirds of Wizards have agreed to approve the 
deal, which it expects to conclude by the end of this month. 
</P>
<P>
	It also said the acquisition will begin adding to Hasbro's  
earnings next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, Hasbro was  
down 31 1/4 cents at $24.50 a share. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
