<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Gun Buyback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is ready to hand over $15  
million in federal money to help communities take some of the 
nation's 200 million guns out of circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, which has had some success in several cities, will  
allow mayors to tailor the program to meet local needs, Andrew 
Cuomo, secretary of housing and urban development, said today. He 
suggested $50 be paid for each gun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brady law and other gun-control laws are having success in  
keeping new guns out of the hands of those who shouldn't have them, 
Cuomo said on ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have 200 million guns in this country. We have to reduce  
that number,'' Cuomo said. Buying back the guns -- people who have 
guns in the home who don't want them ... is one way to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The District of Columbia bought 2,306 guns from their owners in  
a two-day buyback last month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
