<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Bank Leaves Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The European Central Bank held  
interest rates steady Thursday at a regular meeting of its 
governing council. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank, which sets monetary policy for the 11 nations  
using the euro currency, said it will keep its key refinancing rate 
at 2.5 percent, in line with analysts' expectations. That rate is 
the interest the ECB charges commercial banks for buying back 
short-term securities when the banks need cash 
</P>
<P>
	It also kept its overnight deposit rate at 1.5 percent and its  
marginal lending rate at 3.5 percent.	   The deposit rate is the interest banks earn on overnight 
deposits with the central bank and the marginal lending rate is the 
interest on overnight loans to banks by the ECB. 
</P>
<P>
	The two benchmarks represent the floor and ceiling for  
money-market rates in the euro area. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Central Bank's decision to leave rates unchanged  
followed Wednesday's surprise move by the Bank of England to raise 
its base lending rate to 5.25 percent from 5 percent. The base rate 
is the interest Britain's central bank charges commercial banks for 
loans and last was raised in June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain has yet to adopt the euro.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
