<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners To Donate Balitmore Eatery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The owners of beloved Haussner's Restaurant,  
which offered a rich taste of European cuisine and art for 73 
years, are getting out of the business and auctioning off their art 
collection. 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 1, the restaurant will be donated to the Baltimore  
International College, a culinary school. The school said it will 
use the fully equipped building to train students. It was not clear 
whether the students would serve meals to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Haussner's was founded as a modest lunchroom in 1926 by German  
immigrants William and Frances Haussner. The restaurant was famous 
for its hearty, high-calorie menu, which included crab imperial, 
sour beef, potato pancakes and fried eggplant. Its waitresses were 
impeccably dressed and known for their long years of service. 
</P>
<P>
	The current owner, Frances Haussner George, the founders'  
daughter, said that Haussner's remains profitable but that ``it's 
the right time'' to close the institution, situated in the city's 
Highlandtown neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something you can't explain to anybody,'' she said. She  
said her mother approved of the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Haussner's has a staff of 95, down from 210 at its peak. Nearly  
a quarter of the workers have been there for 20 or more years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all going to feel like women without a country,'' said  
Milly Aristidou, who started work as a waitress om 1957. ``Life 
will never be the same without Haussner's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The art and sculpture that decorated the restaurant walls are  
now receiving attention from experts. 
</P>
<P>
	A set of 160 paintings from the restaurant's collection of 19th  
century art will be auctioned at Sotheby's in New York on Nov. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The paintings are expected to bring nearly $8 million, said  
Sotheby's senior vice president Nancy Harrison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. and Mrs. Haussner's collection is one of the great private  
collections of 19th-century European paintings in America,'' Ms. 
Harrison said. 
</P>
<P>
	But no single painting cost the Haussners more than $3,200.  
</P>
<P>
	Buses from a wide swath of the East Coast continue to deposit  
tourists for dinners selected from a 112-item menu. 
</P>
<P>
	At the height of its popularity, Haussner's served 1,600 meals  
on Saturdays, and patrons waited an hour outside in a line 
stretching around the corner. It still serves 900 diners on 
Saturdays. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a magnificent and extraordinary gift,'' said George  
Piendak, chairman of the Baltimore International College board. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
