<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plane's Landing Gear Collapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Part of the landing gear on a DC-9  
collapsed as the plane touched down Thursday at the airport, 
causing the left wing to scrape the runway as the pilot brought the 
aircraft to a stop. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the 48 people on board the TWA flight from St. Louis was  
seriously hurt. Three people were taken to a hospital with back 
pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was watching the sparks fly off the wing. Everyone was  
pretty scared. We could see fuel,'' said passenger Virgil Whetsell 
of Watertown, S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters converged on the plane and doused it with foam.  
</P>
<P>
	The plane was landing around noon when there was ``a slow  
collapse'' of the left rear landing gear, TWA spokesman Jim Brown 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger Terry Pierce of Sioux City, Iowa, said when the wing  
touched the runway he began thinking of the 1989 crash of a United 
Airlines flight in his hometown. That plane cartwheeled down the 
runway, killing 112. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was afraid the wing would catch and we would just flip,'' he  
said. ``The pilot did a nice job to keep it square.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce said after the plane stopped, the pilot, John Hulett, 39,  
apologized for the ``flat tire.'' The passengers laughed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said it was unclear what caused the accident. TWA  
mechanics were sent to examine the plane, and the National 
Transportation Safety Board was investigating. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
