<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa State Announces $80M Gift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa State University's College of Agriculture  
has received a record $80 million donation, at least some of which 
may literally be seed money. 
</P>
<P>
	The university said Thursday the gift came from two donors who  
died earlier this year and wished to remain anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	But The Des Moines Register said at least part of the donation  
came from the estate of Raymond and Mary Baker of Des Moines. Baker 
graduated from ISU in 1935 with a degree in agronomy and went on to 
become director of research at Pioneer Hi-Bred International, an 
Iowa seed company. 
</P>
<P>
	The gift is the largest to a U.S. college of agriculture, and  
the 26th-largest to higher education in the country, the university 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcing the gift with fireworks, confetti and student cheers,  
University President Martin Jischke praised the donors as 
hard-working Iowans who put their families first, valued their 
state and credited some of their success to ISU. They were ``rich 
in generosity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The university hopes to use the gift to make the college's  
agronomy program a national leader, with emphasis on such things as 
plant breeding and farm profitability. The college has about 3,600 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Tom Vilsack said programs and research conducted at the  
school as a result of the donation will lead to new opportunities 
and markets for farmers and new manufacturing businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacey Kunde, a senior and president of the undergraduate  
agronomy club, said she was overwhelmed when she learned of the 
gift. 
</P>
<P>
	``I almost wish I didn't have to graduate so I could see the  
exciting things they do with this money,'' she said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
