<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Serbs March on Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CACAK, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A crowd of angry Kosovo Serb refugees  
swelled to 700 today, and police set up new roadblocks to try to 
prevent them from marching on Belgrade to protest what they feel is 
government indifference to their plight. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the crowd was evicted Wednesday from a school near  
the central town of Kraljevo. They moved into the school after 
fleeing Kosovo in June, following the withdrawal of the Yugoslav 
army from the southern province. 
</P>
<P>
	The families were forced from the school building 80 miles south  
of Belgrade after the government ruled they could no longer stay 
because of the Sept. 1 start of school. 
</P>
<P>
	After spending most of the day in the open, the refugees were  
offered a windowless, roofless ruin with no electricity or water as 
alternative shelter. They refused and embarked instead on a protest 
march to Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Police then stopped the column of tractors and refugees at an  
overpass leading to the highway to Belgrade and ordered them to 
stay within Kraljevo city limits, the radio report said. After dark 
and in heavy rain, the refugees continued their march early today, 
ignoring police roadblocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, about 350 other refugees from Kraljevo and neighboring  
villages joined them. By early this afternoon, police and 
government officials at new barriers near Cacak, 80 miles southwest 
of Belgrade, were negotiating with march leaders, as the rest of 
the refugees -- many of them women and children -- waited, cramped in 
tarp-covered trailers pulled by tractors under a pouring rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Government negotiator Milovan Nenadovic offered accommodations  
for the group in several towns and villages in the area, adding: 
``You are in no position to set any demands.'' But the protesters 
turned him down, demanding instead to be allowed to march on the 
Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why are they terrorizing us, why are they setting up  
barricades,'' said Mirka Ribac, 60, from the Kosovo town of Klina. 
``We are sick of this, it would be better if they started shooting 
and killing us all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Kosovo's 200,000 Serbs fled the Albanian-majority  
province in June, afraid of reprisal attacks by ethnic Albanians. 
Kraljevo registered some 20,000 Serb refugees from Kosovo but 
10,000 more than that are believed to be in the central Serbian 
town. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
